Name: Rowan Marshall
Comment: Marshall has taken the reigns as solo ruck for two seasons and in that time has clearly been the premier player in Fantasy. Back-to-back 117 seasons, which no other player has achieved in the last five years. His season included a 62 when he battled with a knee complaint in Round 6 which he backed up with a 73, so that 117 could have been higher. He is a genuine stat-stuffer and a rare ruckman who generates scores through transition movement as much as stoppages. The threat of the Saints playing a second ruck has always been there given he shoulders so much of the load. The good news is the two candidates - Tom Campbell and Jack Hayes - have both been delisted. Saints drafted the number one ruck prospect in the draft, but he'll need time. However, the SSP signing of 26-year-old ruck Harry Boyd is certainly cause for concern. Starting the highest priced player hasn't worked in Fantasy since Tom Mitchell in 2018, so history says start someone of value and see Marshall as an upgrade target. That's how I play the game. But if Boyd isn't used, there is no reason why Marshall won't make it a hat-trick of 117+ in his age 28 season. UPDATE: Marshall is touch and go for Round 1 following a stress fracture in his pelvis. I'm not as concerned with him losing this training block as I am the Saints protecting him during the season. I can't see him rucking 85% as he's done the last two years which means a regression is certainly on the cards. I wouldn't start with him and wouldn't draft in the top 10.
Short: Only player to be top three, two years in a row in last five years, 120+ post-bye the last two, however pre-season stress fracture in pelvis and recruitment of Boyd is enough to scare me off

Name: Tristan Xerri
Comment: 124 156 150 168 122 and 109. These were the last six scores of Tristan Xerri in his first season as solo ruck. While no one could have seen this level of scoring coming, the writing was on the wall. In 2022 he averaged 105 in the VFL (including a game with 36 disposals and 27 hit-outs) and finished 2nd in the BnF, despite playing just half the games. 2023 he got his chance but was injured in the first quarter of Round 1, but led the league for points per minute after his two games as solo ruck before Goldy returned to the team. With Goldy gone in 2024, Xerri finally arrived. He ranked 3rd for tackles in the comp (only ruck in the top 24) and 8th in clearances (number one ruck). Of the top five tackling ruckmen at stoppages, he was 50 clear of the next best - that's over two a game (or eight points). Outliers of this extreme could lead to a regression and a better performing Roos team shouldn't be as reliant on their big man shouldering all the load. But tackling and following up is in his nature. He's always done it and it's not going to go away. We could see a period where Xerri is the top scoring player for multiple seasons. Priced at 114 you can take him on, but if you want someone priced over 110 as a captain option, he'd be the one I'd take (unless two value rucks emerge as they did last season).
Short: First season as solo ruck and didn't he deliver - 125 post bye and 141 L5 to be the number one guy, once rucks get to that level they usually sustain it for a while

Name: Harry Sheezel
Comment: Sheezel backed up his Rising Star debut season with a breakout 2024 where he dropped the Rising part. And he did so in multiple roles. He began the season as the distributor off half back as he did in 2023 and after seven weeks was the top player in Fantasy, averaging 126 per game. Roos were 0-5 and decided to move him into the midfield to play a higher impact MID/FWD role, the role he played as a junior. He went from 2% CBAs across the first seven weeks to 47% for the rest of the year. In doing so, his average dropped to 106 in that time. But considering it was a new role with less easy ball, and that a lot of that time was spend forward, a 106 average was amazing - the top mid averaged 111 and that was with 80% CBAs. In the back end of the season he was more mid than forward, and the games he attended 48%+ (which he did in five of the last six weeks), he averaged 117. So he's not as fully priced as his post-bye average suggests and a clear D1 for the season, it's just whether you pay up to start with him and I don't normally start with more than one player priced at 110+.
Short: 5 x 120+ in first five rounds playing in defence, then moved to a MID/FWD role which reduced his output slightly but 109 post bye in that role is still elite

Name: Max Gawn
Comment: Gawn was a popular R1 last season as he was going in solo after a few years of sharing the ruck duties. Come his mid-season bye, he didn't disappoint, averaging 121 and was the number one man in Fantasy. And it wasn't a complete shock, given he averaged 124 in 2020 (the last time he was completely solo) and went over 120 three times in 2023 when he averaged over 90% CBAs. However, his age and carrying the team started to take its toll. He averaged just 96 post-bye as he battled with an ankle injury and looked every bit of a 33-year-old. He and the Dees will be looking to bounce back in 2025 and there will be times he'll look the number one ruck in Fantasy, but the Dees can't afford to wear him out as they did last season and I'd rather start with someone with more upside.
Short: 121 pre bye but started to look tired late, now 33 he's got some left in the tank but his glory days are over, even if he remains a one-man band at the Dees

Name: Lachie Whitfield
Comment: It's crazy that 2024 was the first time Whitfield has averaged 110+ over a full season, given he's had multiple stretches of being one of the best players in Fantasy. However, something typically interrupts his season and impacts his average, so it was good to see him get a clear run at it last season. It's also good to see him back in his natural position, after Leon Cameron played him up the ground in his last two seasons. My hesitation last year was that the Giants had a number of distributors - Himmelberg, Cumming and Ash being the main competitors. In the end, Whitfield averaged the 3rd highest percentage of kick-ins across the league, so he was their clear main man and will likely remain that way. When he's in that role, he's a 110+ Fantasy prospect and while the tag and injury threat will always be there, he's an early favourite for D1 in 2025. For Classic, his price is a bit high for someone with an early bye for me to consider starting.
Short: Career best season highlighted by 124 post bye, that's going to be hard to sustain but he's averaged 110+ when in the right role and not interrupted before

Name: Dayne Zorko
Comment: Zorko entered 2024 coming off two injury impacted seasons where he was subbed off early four times. At 34, many put a line through him thinking his body was shot. However, some new physio techniques saw him overcome his soft tissue worries and after injuries to creative half-backs Coleman and McKenna, Zorko moved to the half back line to give Brisbane some much needed spark. It proved a masterstroke, with Zorko being one of the best rebounding defenders in the game and became the oldest ever All-Australian. I'm confident he will remain in the role, despite Coleman set to return, however his role might not be as prominent. Add the fact he's turning 36, he's a likely regression candidate heading into 2025 and one I'd avoid at that price.
Short: 27 games at a 110 average for a 35-year-old was remarkable, role should stick but Coleman returning and another year older makes him a clear regression candidate

Name: Adam Treloar
Comment: Treloar has been a Fantasy stud over the journey, averaging 104+ seven seasons in a row from 2014 to 2020. He was then struck down by soft tissue injuries, averaging 14 games per season between 2020 and 2022 and averaging less than 100. However, he showed signs at the end of 2023 that he had gotten over these issues, averaging 107 post-bye and 117 in L5. He took that form into 2024, playing all bar one game and ending with a 110 average, the highest amongst the midfielders and winning his first All-Australian blazer. I have been a doubter given his injury history and there were a few nervous moments in 2024, but he certainly proved me wrong. A year older and priced at 110, it's hard not to be a doubter again, especially as a starting option at that price. UPDATE: Set to miss the first two months of the season with a calf issue.
Short: Most expensive mid after a super All-Australian season, but age and injury history makes him a far riskier prospect in 2025 and now missing the first two months with a calf issue

Name: Zach Merrett
Comment: Merrett's 109 average in 2024 made it eight 107+ seasons in his 11 years in the comp, making him one of the best Fantasy players of all time. Adding to the consistency is his ability to go big, surpassing 120 six times in each of his last two seasons. While his output is no doubt impressive, the Dons are aware of their over-reliance on their skipper and would like to spread the load more in 2025. Regardless, history suggests it's best to avoid the top priced mids and instead target someone with more price upside who you think can perform in line. This makes Merrett an upgrade target for me.
Short: 8 x 107+ seasons in his 11 years in the comp is remarkable consistency, Dons don't want to be as reliant on him as they have in the past but he's still a jet

Name: Errol Gulden
Comment: Gulden entered 2024 with the expectation he could be the number one player in Fantasy, following his historic breakout in 2023 where he averaged 118 post-bye and 122 L5. 133 in the pre-season game meant that many were earmarking starting with the 21-year-old with a perfect inside/outside game. However, 69 in the Opening Round caused a change of plans. He still had a great season, finishing the 3rd highest averaging mid, but it didn't have the consistency of 2024. He averaged 133 from Round 10 to 15 and 126 from Round 18 to 20. However, there it also included 10 games of 100 or less (and two more in his three finals). It was a combination of the Heeney breakout, added opposition attention and the inside/outside role, which can be great when things go his way, but 36% CBAs is very low for a top midfielder. He's still so young and the 112 he averaging in 2023 and post-bye should be the baseline for 2025. 28 FEB UPDATE: Went down with an ankle in the practice match and didn't look good. Wait for the results but he could be out for a while.
Short: Slight dip after a breakout 2023 with 10 games 100 or less, has the tools to be the number one player and expecting a bounce back

Name: Sam Flanders
Comment: Flanders was a popular forward option last season after a 139 VFL average and 105 post-bye from 38% CBAs, increasing to 112 in the L5 from 43% once Stewy Dew left in 2023. More midfield time was flagged and it eventuated, averaging 49% CBAs across the first three games. However, it was his move to half back that proved most fruitful, where he averaged 118 from Round 4 to 15. However, it didn't change the Suns' fortunes, and he finished the season back in the midfield rotation and spending time in F50. His score naturally copped a hit, as half-back is a more attractive Fantasy role than inside mid in modern footy. With the recruitment of Rioli and Noble, it appears the Flanders half back experiment is over and he will be used as a MID/FWD in 2025. He's a natural scorer, as we saw in 2023, but priced at 108, it's going to be hard for him to sustain that in the less favourable role. He's kept his defender status which will keep him very relevant this season, however I see him as an upgrade target, particularly given his early bye. UPDATE: Been battling with a back issue since Christmas which has limited his training, never a good sign for someone priced that high.
Short: A natural scorer and when in the cozy half-back role he averaged 118, but finished in a MID/FWD role, where he'll likely spend 2025 with the GC recruits, dropping to 100

Name: Josh Dunkley
Comment: Dunkley has now had two seasons at the Lions, and while he finished 2024 as a top eight mid, it's hard not to feel a little underwhelmed given his high CBA role and scoring history. At the Dogs, he averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 127 in the last half of 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. He's now got the full-time mid role we've been craving but failed to average the 110+ I earmarked him for. He's still a very good Fantasy player given his above average marking (5.6 per game v 4.4 of the top eight mids) and tackle (6.2 v 5.2) ability as well as the fact he's never in danger of a tag. This combination will likely see him average 105+ again and compete as a top eight mid, but I'd like some more upside with my starting squad.
Short: Very solid with elite mark/tackle combo and ability to avoid the tag, scoring is just a tad lower at the Lions than it was when he was at the Dogs

Name: Marcus Bontempelli
Comment: For years, the Bont was far better in real life than he was in Fantasy. However, this all changed midway through 2020 when he went on a rampage to average 124 points in the second half of the season. He spent the majority of his time playing as an inside midfielder rather than splitting his time forward as he did earlier in his career. While his 107 in 2024 was slightly down from his competition leading 117 in 2023, he still looked the best player (in real life and Fantasy) at stages - highlighted by eight games at 117+. He's still in his prime and while the tag risk is there week-to-week given how damaging he is, he's going to be amongst the top few in Fantasy again. 28 FEB UPDATE: Out for 6 weeks. Been a brutal off-season and the Dogs are looking thin.
Short: Best mid in Fantasy (and IRL) over the last two seasons, tag risk is always there but he's on a different level than the rest

Name: Nic Martin
Comment: Martin has had an amazing start to his career after being selected as an SSP in 2022. He was in All-Australian discussions in his 2nd season on a wing and caught the eye of Fantasy coaches when averaging 113 in a 6-game stretch, bucking the trend of what is typically a low scoring position. So when he moved to half back at the start of last season, expectations were high. He delivered, averaging 110 in the first eight rounds and displaying the thirst for the footy we love as Fantasy coaches. But outside of Fantasy coaches, his new role output attracted some criticism - with many suggesting he was far more damaging when playing on a wing than getting cheap touches in D50. Brad Scott obviously agreed, as he moved him back to the wing and a forward-of-centre role after Round 8. While his scoring wasn't as prolific (only one x 100+ score from Round 15 to Round 21), it was still very impressive, averaging 106 in this time including 123 in his L3. His price tag is very high for someone not playing one of the two roles we want - inside mid or rebounding half-back - so he doesn't present as a great starting option, but the defender status and talk of him playing more inside in 2025 means he's likely a top six defender and someone you're going to want at some stage.
Short: Averaged 110 as a HB distributor but moved to the wing/HF mid-season where his scoring dropped a little (106), but still showed a high ability to score - inside role possible in 2025 could see him go higher

Name: Jack Steele
Comment: After averaging 110+ three seasons in a row (including 121 in 2021 with 134 post-bye) and one of the most consistent players in Fantasy, Steele has been the opposite in the last two seasons. A disappointing 2023 impacted by AC and MCL injuries saw him average 99 and appear discounted for 2024. On face value, he was - averaging 107 for the season and finishing as a top eight mid. But he still had periods that brought back memories of 2023, with seven sub-100 scores from Round 6 to 16. The game is speeding up, with less stoppages and tackle opportunities and at times Steele looks like he can't keep up. However, he still showed he can be an elite player in this game, bookmarking that mid-season slump with 121 in the first five rounds and 113 in the last 8, so maybe he was carrying something then. The Saints didn't add to the midfield group over the off-season, despite it being very shallow, so Steele will remain their main man for the 2025 season. He might prove to be slightly discounted at 107, but I'd need to see him pass the eye test first as a few of his games in the last 24 months stick in the mind.
Short: Underwhelming two seasons after three x 110+, the game looks a bit quick for him at times but his role won't change and when fully fit he can still score with the best

Name: Sam Walsh
Comment: After bursting onto the scene and looking like a top-level Fantasy mid for the future decade, averaging 92, 97 and 109 in his first three seasons, Walsh has been underwhelming in the last 3, failing to reach the 109 mark again. There have been a few factors for the regression. A pre-season syndesmosis injury in 2022, off-season back surgery in 2023 and then his back delaying his started to 2024, missing the first four games. Remarkably, he scored 145 in his first game back and averaged 120 in his first 5. He went on to score 110+ in six of his last 14 games, but went under 100 eight times. With his limited pre-seasons in mind, it was an impressive year and if he manages to be fully fit then we could see him have a career best season in 2025. UPDATE: Another pre-season, another injury. Walsh suffered a hamstring injury in the pre-season, and while he's expected to be right for Round 1, I've bumped him down a bit due to missing some important training and concerns about his body.
Short: Hasn’t had a full pre-season since 2021 when he averaged 109 in his 3rd season, if fully fit this year he should return to that level

Name: Zak Butters
Comment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day and since Round 8 in 2023 when he stepped into a full-time midfield role, he's become a star in Fantasy - averaging 107 since. He has the perfect inside/outside blend which makes for sustainable scoring and may improve as he gets bigger and increases his tackle numbers. He can be a nervous watch given how hard he attacks the ball and body for his size and 2024 wasn't without its interruptions. An ankle injury impacted his pre-season, was subbed out (against his will) when on 136 at 3/4 time in Round 17 and finished with cracked ribs in the finals. Teams tend to tag him over Rozee and JHF, but we might see the latter getting more attention this season. I'm confident Butters can be a top eight mid again in 2025, but like the other mids around this price, I'd rather target some more value in my starting squad. 25 FEB UPDATE: Knee injury may see him miss the start of the year. 28 FEB UPDATE: Out for 6 weeks.
Short: Averaged 107 since moving into the midfield in 2023 and despite Ports' low stoppage game style, only self-inflicted injury will stop him continuing

Name: Jordan Dawson
Comment: Dawson broke out in his first season at the Crows, boosting his average by 12 playing as a distributor in defence. He then moved into the midfield in his second season and improved another 13 points to be one of the top players in Fantasy. 2024 saw his first regression in his new colours, dropping eight points to 105. After just two games under 90 in 2023, he had an uncharacteristic six games under that mark in 2024, a lot of those coinciding with Adelaide's poor form and him shifting to different roles. The good news is that outside of these six games, he averaged 118, so he certainly still has the ability to go big. But with the arrival of Peatling and Draper, and the need to inject some more pace inside with Rankine, Dawson's role is a bit unknown given his versatility. If we get confirmation he will return to 70%+ CBAs as he did in 2023 then he could be the under-priced uber premium we are after, but I'd need some role confirmation first. 27 FEB UPDATE: We now have confirmation.
Short: Dropped eight points due to uncharacteristic six games under 90, his versatility hurts at times but if he remains a full-time mid, he should bounce back to 2023 levels

Name: Isaac Heeney
Comment: Not sure if the joke is on us for continuing to think the midfield move was coming for 10 seasons or Horse for taking 10 seasons until actually doing it. 2024 we finally saw Heeney play full time mid, bumping his career high CBA season from 13% to 74%. It worked, with Heeney becoming a star mid of the comp and favourite for the Brownlow for the majority of the year. His scoring tapered off as the season went on and teams became more aware of his impact, averaging 98 post-bye compared to 112 pre. He should only benefit from the experience and is set to back it up in 2025, however now that he's lost his forward status the value isn't there to start with Heeney this season.
Short: The old 10-year breakout, hard to back up that incredible season so feel like we might see a minor regression, but he's now a midfielder and 112 pre-bye average would put him right at the top of top eight mid calcs

Name: Tim English
Comment: Still find it the most remarkable stat of 2024 was that Tim English, the All-Australian ruck, didn't win one hitout battle for the season. The only game where he had the most hitouts on the ground was against the SDK/Blic combo who combined had more than English, when the pair conceded 218 hitouts to 103 in the four other games together. Hitouts have never been his strong suit, but ruckmen normally peak after 25 and both Gawn and Grundy improved their average in the year following their first season averaging 110+. We typically see greater consistency in the top ruck tier than the other positions, which is why English's 15 point regression in 2024 was such a shock. There was a change in the ruck rule where players were able to hold a player out while the ball was in the air which didn't play into English's favour. However, it was the ease he was pushed off the ball that was alarming. I'm prepared to give him the benefit of the doubt that he was carrying something, more than it all being down to the rule change. Sam Darcy is an emerging start and could well spend more time in the ruck this year with English's ability to play forward, but I expect we will see some form of bounce back from English in 2025. UPDATE: Another interrupted pre-season for English, this time an abdominal injury. Sounds like he'll be fine for Round 1 but gives me less confidence in the bounce back.
Short: 2023 AA ruck didn't win a single hitout battle in 2024, didn't look himself, upside is there if he can return to 2023 form

Name: Nick Daicos
Comment: We haven't seen a Fantasy prodigy like him. His only weakness to date has been his ability to handle a tag (Windhager kept him to 61, ANB to 62 (inj), Will Phillips to 68 before being subbed off, James Jordon to 71), but he'll be better prepared for that heading into his fourth season. He's now a full-time mid (CBAs 42% in 2023 to 71% in 2024) so there is no longer the cheap ball in defence, but he's becoming a very good midfielder with 7.7 clearances per game. The tag threat will always be there for the 21-year-old who has two top three Brownlow finishes, but he's a level above and I expect him to push through the 110 mark for the first time in 2025. UPDATE: Missed some training due to a foot issue but now back at it and in no doubt for the Opening Round. Haven't changed my projection on him.
Short: Constant tag threat which is the only thing holding him back from being a 110+ mid, but should be better prepared for it in his 4th season so I expect him to reach that mark

Name: Andrew Brayshaw
Comment: Brayshaw isn't the perfect midfielder in real-life (below average contested and clearance rate), but he is one of the best two-way runners in the game. And for Fantasy, that results in above average marks and tackles, which saw him put up back-to-back 110+ seasons in 2022 and 2023. He fell short of that mark due to a few factors. The introduction of Hayden Young and return of Nat Fyfe into the midfield rotation meant that Brayshaw wasn't the high CBA player which he was in the past, with his CBAs reducing to 70% for 2024. Freo used all their mids in the forward line to add something different and Brayshaw spent his fair share of time there. Young isn't going anywhere but I doubt we see much more of Fyfe. The arrival of Bolton reduces the need for Freo to use their mids forward. I'm expecting Brayshaw to go back to the high-70 CBA %. He was also carrying a niggle in the early part of the season and certainly looked more himself post-bye where he averaged 108 (110 L5). Assuming he's fully fit, I think he'll return to that 110+ level and he has the attributes to be the top mid in Fantasy in 2025.
Short: Regression after back-to-back 110+ seasons, hit that mark post-bye after shaking a niggle and should return to that level

Name: Noah Anderson
Comment: While Anderson continued to improve his Fantasy output (74 to 81 to 98 to 101 to 104), he hasn't earnt a lot of trust yet. His good is great - five games over 120 after crossing that mark four times in 2023 - but his inconsistency has become a frustration - six games under 90 following nine times in 2023. It's what you get from an inside midfielder who gets below average tackle numbers, over three less per game than the top eight mids across the last two seasons. I think he has the ability to become a 110-averaging midfielder, but I'll need to see a boost in tackle ability before being confident enough to jump on.
Short: Improved output every season, just needs to add to his tackle game and can become a top eight mid

Name: Caleb Serong
Comment: Serong backed up his breakout 2023 where he received his first All-Australian honours with another All-Australian season in 2024. He started with a bang, 161 in Round 1 and averaged 113 at the bye. However, such was his domination, he attracted significant opposition attention on the run home, including tags against Connor Nash, Jack Graham, James Jordon, Touk Miller, Tom Liberatore, Toby Bedford and Willem Drew within an 11-game stretch, reducing his average to 89 in those games. If he avoids the tag, then he will go straight back to the 110 level we know he's capable of. However, such is his damage around clearances and standing in the game, I see the tags continuing in 2025 which would make him a risky starting option at that price.
Short: The regular tag cost him from having a 110+ season and unfortunately I think the tags will remain in 2025

Name: Nic Newman
Comment: Pretty crazy that someone who averaged 109 post-bye and 124 L5 in 2023 backed it up with 113 post-bye and 126 L5 in 2024 - and we have no idea how to rank him in 2025! Such is the up and down nature of Nic Newman. A few things did change post-bye. Zac Williams, who led the Blues for kick-ins to Round 8 moved forward in a move that will likely remain. McGovern, who led the kick-ins to Round 17, missed three of the last seven games and he wasn't the only one, with Blues playing depleted for much of the back half of the year. Newman's kick-ins went to 37% post-bye, up from 17% pre. Even with Williams playing forward, they have plenty of options back there, including Saad and Jordan Boyd who they like the ball in the hands of. Priced at 103, which is his career high average, heading into his age 32 season seems a big price to pay as a starting option, despite his obvious ability to exceed it. UPDATE: Unfortunately out for the year with a knee injury, all the best in recovery. Doch could be the man.
Short: 113 post-bye and 126 L5 had appeal, but pre-season knee injury has ruled him out for the season

Name: Luke Ryan
Comment: After four seasons in a row averaging in the 80s, Ryan has averaged over 100 across the last two seasons to be a top six defender in that time. But it hasn't been as smooth as that sounds. He averaged 112 after three weeks, 85 the next four and then went on a 5-week run where he averaged 136(!) to be the highest scorer in the game in that time. Then once many jumped on post his bye, he fell off a cliff, 79 in his next seven with a high of 101. He led the league in kicks in 2023 (2nd in 2024) and in marks in 2024 (4th in 2023), so fair to say he likes a plus 6. But his slow, kick/mark game style attracted criticism from not just non-owners, but the wider football public who believe Freo need to move the ball quicker to give their forwards more of a chance. I think the public are right and with Bolton up forward this season, they will want to get it in quick with less backwards kicks inside D50. Ryan is still going to have his big games such is his ability to generate +6 opportunities, but he's a big price for someone who averaged 91 to finish the year.
Short: Led comp in marks and kicks over last two seasons and 136 avg in five weeks before the bye is something not many can do, but it dropped off late as Freo sped things up which I expect they will try more of in 2025

Name: Jack Sinclair
Comment: It took Sinclair eight seasons to breakout, but since then he's put up a hat-trick of 100+ seasons, the only defender to do so and one of only seven players in the entire comp. He is aided by the dream combo of CBAs and KIs, so he's always involved in the play. Interestingly, he scores his best when he has less CBAs, highlighted by his 113 average in the L5 from 15% CBAs (season low) and 41% KI (season high). There were a few other things at play to start the year which might have explained his 97 pre-bye average. A pre-season calf injury saw him miss the practice matches and Round 1 and when he returned, the Saints had Riley Bonner taking most of the kick-ins and played Sinclair further up the ground. By the end of the season, Phillipou, Clark, Dow and Windhager had moved into the middle and Sinclair stayed in defence (0% CBAs in L3). Despite the rise of NWM who will no doubt take some ball off Sinclair, I think we'll see him spend more time in defence this season which could see him push the 105 mark, making him a clear top six defender with some price upside. 12 FEB UPDATE: A hamstring injury will see him miss four weeks, might be right for Round 1 but not what you want from a premium, so now an upgrade target for me.
Short: Slow start to 2024 with a pre-season calf injury but 110 post-bye when up and going saw a hat-trick of 100+ seasons - he's a gun

Name: Matt Crouch
Comment: Matt Crouch struggled with groin issues, a broken leg and form in the three seasons leading up to 2024 after being a 110+ mid previously. Despite putting up big numbers in the reserves, it appeared the Crows had moved on from Crouch until he reemerged late in the season, averaging 6.4 clearances a game and many thought he played career best football - as previously he's been criticised for being just an accumulator and getting cheap footy. This continued into 2024 with Crouch being a mainstay in the Crows centre bounce lineup, attending 68% which matched his (very low) 68% TOG (where he happed to be the number one PPM player in the comp). And he was good. He averaged 30 disposals and six clearances in the low game time, averaging 106 points before an AC injury put him out until Round 21, putting a stop to what would've been a great bounce back season. By then, the Crows changed up their midfield mix, with Soligo, Berry, Zac Taylor and Dan Curtin all spending time in the middle, however Crouch maintained his full-time CBA role. 2025 will look a little different with the recruitment of Peatling and Sid Draper and the return of Rankine who was missing at the end of 2024. Looks like Laird is one who will move out and it's possible Crouch will see reduced exposure. At that price, it's not worth the risk anyway for someone who might not even be in their best 22 at times in 2025.
Short: PPM gun (number one mid in comp) but low TOG and changing Crow midfield mix might mean less exposure for Crouch in 2025

Name: Lachie Neale
Comment: The two-time Brownlow medallist has been a proven Fantasy scorer in the past, averaging 116 in the first half of 2022 and a league leading 120 in 2020. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams know to put extra attention into him. It's meant his scoring output has been on the decline while the Lions have been on the up, with his focus being less about accumulation and trying to be more damaging with his possessions and the team trying to spread the load a bit more. He did manage to average 108 post-bye which would be enough to knock on the door of the top eight mids. I've seen enough over the last four years to doubt that he can maintain that level of scoring across a full season.
Short: 108 post bye is eye-catching but regular opposition attention makes it hard for him to maintain that level

Name: Toby Nankervis
Comment: Nank backed up his career best 2023 where he passed 87 for the first time with back-to-back 100+ seasons. And it wasn't without duress. He missed the start of the season with a foot injury and was subbed off in Round 19 with concussion, after averaging 118 in the seven weeks prior. He returned to average 101 in the final four games to solidify his standing as a 100+ averaging ruck. The Tigers are going to have it tough this season but that didn't stop him last year, averaging more in losses than wins. The beauty about being a ruck that tackles hard (5.3 per game) is that you don't have to rely on your teammates to score. Outside of the 118 stretch, he's a level below the top two rucks and fairly priced, so I don't see appeal in him as a starting option. However if Marshall spends more time forward and English doesn't bounce back, there's a chance he finishes the year as a top two ruck.
Short: Back-to-back 100+ seasons including seven game stretch averaging 118, he's still a level below the top two though

Name: Patrick Cripps
Comment: Cripps solidified his standing as one of the best players in the game, winning his second Brownlow in three seasons and breaking the all-time record for votes in a season. However, the record-breaking season placed him outside the top 30 scorers in Fantasy. This clearly shows his game style (highly contested, high clearance, low kick-to-handball ratio) which makes him such a good player in real life, but doesn't translate to Fantasy scoring. His career best year would put him in the mix of the top eight mids, however his Brownlow seasons suggest he's a level below those who gather more uncontested marks and kicks. I expect we'll see similar output in 2025.
Short: Average of 101 across his two Brownlow seasons shows he's far better in real life than Fantasy

Name: Tom Green
Comment: After his breakout 2023 where he boosted his average 24 points to 109, it looked like Green was going to take his game to another level when he averaged 127 in the first three games of 2024. It was helped that it was against easy opposition, with West Coast and North being 2. There was then concern when he only exceeded 100 twice in the next 10 games, including a seven in Round 8 when he suffered an early ankle injury. He returned the next game and the fact he averaged just 87 in the next five suggests he wasn't 100%, but he picked up again to finish the season and averaged 109 in the last 10 games. Based on the last two seasons when fit, he's a 109 averaging mid, which is enough to be a top mid in Fantasy. And given he's just 24, there is improvement to come. The early bye is what would stop me from starting him as my M1 as I think he has the upside to be a worthwhile pick at that price, but he might need to be an early upgrade target after his early bye. 18 FEB UPDATE: A calf strain will see him miss the start of the season. I'm still bullish on him, but now an upgrade target post bye and hopefully in Draft you can snag him in the second or third round.
Short: 109 in 2023 and the last 10 games of 2024 after he recovered from his ankle suggests the 24-year-old can return to at least that mark in 2025

Name: Rory Laird
Comment: Laird was a consistent defender who averaged 95-105 for four years straight, before moving into the midfield in 2020 and becoming the best player in Fantasy 2022 with a 120 average. He has dropped 10 points in each of the last two seasons since then, and with the Crows looking to add some speed into their midfield, he found himself back to defence to finish 2024. No doubt the Crows needed to change things up in the middle as they were very one-paced, and with Rankine returning and the recruitments of Peatling and Draper, I suspect Laird's midfield days are done. But that might not be such a bad thing. He was a top six defender in a time where it wasn't as easy to accumulate as it is now. Priced at 99, I don't see the value as a starting option, but I can see him finishing the year as a top six defender and someone we're eventually going to have in our teams.
Short: Looks like his midfield days are over but has been a 95-105 defender in the past, which would be enough to make him a top six defender if that role eventuates

Name: Nasiah Wanganeen-Milera
Comment: The former pick 11, who was described as the best kick at St Kilda from the moment he was drafted, has proven that to be true in his first three seasons in the comp. He averaged 98 post-bye in 2023 then maintained that level for 2024, which has him knocking on the door of the top 6. The Saints try to get the ball in his hands at any opportunity, as they should. Natural improvement should see him increase his scoring again and he's going to be around the top six mark for the next 10 years. Whether he can boost his score to the 100+ average required to be a decent starting selection is the question, as his outside nature and lack of tackles typically makes it hard to sustain 100+ scoring, especially when there's another defender at the Saints going 100+. But he'll get close.
Short: Averaged 98 since half way through his 2nd season, lack of tackles and competing with a fellow 100+ averaging defender at the Saints, but he's going to be around the top six mark for the next 10 years

Name: Hugh McCluggage
Comment: McCluggage has moved from a pure wing to an inside midfielder in recent seasons, attending a career high 61% CBAs in 2024. It hasn't translated to scoring though, as he continues to hover around the high-90 to low-100 mark which he has done so for that past four seasons. I had been waiting to see what McCluggage would produce Fantasy wise once moved inside from his customary wing role, given he played inside when he was in juniors and averaged more points than Tim Taranto. However he hasn't had the boost I was hoping for and his lack of tackle numbers (3.7 per game compared to 5.2 of the top eight mids) make it hard for him to compete with the top 8.
Short: Lack of tackles even now he has a high CBA role means he'll likely remain below the top 8

Name: Brodie Grundy
Comment: A move to Sydney and back to being a solo ruck after a year splitting with Max Gawn saw Grundy improve his average by 21 points per game, however was still a long way from his glory days at the Pies. He started off strong, scoring 118 against Gawn in the Opening Round, but struggled with 10 games under 90 (including three under 70) the rest of the year. It wasn't a complete shock, as he averaged 100 in 2023 when Max missed and 93 in his last season at the Pies. That's a big enough sample size to suggest he might just be a 100-averaging ruck, which is going to leave him a fair way short of the top 2. With an early bye on top, he's not the appealing ruck option that he was last year.
Short: Underwhelming return to the number one ruck role and I've seen enough to suggest his 110+ days are over

Name: Connor Rozee
Comment: After a breakout in 2023, not much went right for the Port skipper in 2024. He averaged 105 through the first six weeks and looked to be in the top eight mid calculations. However, he played just 57% TOG the following week, sitting out with a tight hamstring. He was on 89 at the time and was on track for a monster. He surprisingly (and wrongly) played the following week, only to be subbed out early with the same hamstring on 51 from 51% TOG. He missed two weeks this time and returned with just 43(!) with just 27% CBAs - so clearly something wasn't right. He missed the following week with an ankle which then led to his bye. Unfortunately it was season over for those who held this period. He looked more himself post-bye, averaging 103 (106 excluding Round 24 when he also looked hampered and spent a lot of time on the bench). The good news about a player coming off an interrupted season is they are discounted in the next. Without any natural improvement, we know he's a 103 player which priced at 97 is enough discount to prove a solid starting pick. But if he can get this up to 107+ then he'll be a great starting pick, and I think he can do that in 2025.
Short: Battled with hamstring and ankle injuries in 2024 which led to three injury impacted scores, excluding these he averaged 103 which matched 2023, meaning he should hit at least this level in 2025

Name: Jordan Clark
Short: Breakout in 2024 after always showing signs, with Freo moving it quicker and Ryan taking a lot of the kick-ins it's hard to see him pushing to 100+ but he should keep up his 2024 output

Name: Jarrod Witts
Short: Averaged 89-97 for all six halves (H1&H2) for the last three seasons, shows the consistency but cap of the big Wittler

Name: Darcy Cameron
Comment: Cameron backed up his 82 in his first season as solo ruck with 96 in his second. The 96 wasn't a shock as he averaged 93 to finish 2022 after Grundy got injured and was averaging 92 in 2023 before doing his MCL. He finished strong, 103 post-bye, but that included a 147 against a ruck-less Geelong. He's elevated himself to the second tier of rucks behind Xerri, Marshall and English and he's done it with lower CBAs (71%), with Mason Cox used more than most backups. Cox might not feature as much in 2025 with if we can see Cameron get 80% CBAs, there can be upside there in 2025, but I doubt that will be enough to prove a good starting option. 10 MAR UPDATE: Got a nice matchup after Briggs went down early. He's a starting option as I was bullish on him before (103 post-bye). He's got a hidden price of $1.025m, so he's making cash and might be a nice option until his bye to then grab either a top ruck who has dropped in cash or if Briggs has returned cheaper. Not my first choice ruck setup, but I certainly don't mind the move.
Short: Career best 96 and 103 post-bye when CBAs rose to 78%, should stay that way in 2025 which would keep him as a tier two ruck

Name: Luke Davies-Uniacke
Comment: LDU's Fantasy trajectory was looking very linear - 53 in his debut season followed by 71, 82, 93 and then 97 in 2023. He had his first regression last season when he averaged 96, despite high expectations following his 105 post-bye average in 2023. He is no doubt a better player in real life than in Fantasy, highlighted by his 109 SuperCoach average in 2024 (and 114 in 2023). While he averages the same disposals as the top eight mids, at a better contested rate and more clearances (hence the good SC scoring), he lacks the marks (3.7 per game v 5.2 of the top 8) and tackles (3.9 v 5.2) to push him to the 108-mark required to be a top mid in Fantasy. This is partly due to the extra attention he receives for being North's clear best player for the last three seasons. But with their midfield looking deeper and Sheezel probably taking that mantle, LDU could run free a bit more in 2025 and I expect him to finally break the 100 mark.
Short: His best is more than good enough but career high of 97 in seven seasons shows he doesn't get the reward in Fantasy

Name: Tim Taranto
Comment: Not much went right for Taranto in 2023 after taking the Fantasy world by storm in his first season at the Tigers, which included a 125 pre-bye average. 2024 included a broken wrist which saw him miss eight games, then a concussion in Round 18 when on 86, subbed off with a back injury in Round 20 on 40 (48% TOG). Excluding these injured games, he averaged over 100. It's still below what we know he can do (averaged 115 in 2021 for the 13 games with more than 50% CBAs) but he might not have been 100% for a lot of it given the interrupted run. A full pre-season should help and with the Tigers expected to lose a lot in 2025, we could see his scoring go either way. Regardless, my lower end projections still has him outperforming his price of 96 and best case, he can beat that by 10 points and prove a great starting selection.
Short: Injury interrupted season for the man who led the comp halfway through 2023, expect a bounce back but that might be capped with Richmond's likely struggles

Name: Josh Kelly
Comment: Josh Kelly looked to be a generational Fantasy stud after averaging 113 in just his 4th season then backed it up with 108 then 116 his next two. However, he hasn't been near that level since and averaged in the 90s the past two seasons since Kingsley took over as coach. The emergence of Tom Green and Finn Callaghan, along with the use of Bedford as a tagger, has seen Kelly spend more time on a wing. His CBAs have continued to drop over the last two seasons: 62% H1 2023 to just 17% H2 2024. And I think he stays on the wing going forward, which means the chance of Kelly returning to a premium midfielder is unlikely. 10 MAR UPDATE: Backed him his solid CBA role in the pre-season to be second for the Giants behind Finn. We know he can score when given CBAs, but with Finn locked and Bedford still tagging, is he the one to push back to a wing when Green returns? I've bumped him up a lot but still couldn't start with him myself after what we've seen in recent years.
Short: Spending less and less time inside and scoring has reflected that, the hopes of Kelly being a 110+ mid again are over

Name: Josh Daicos
Comment: 20 FEB UPDATE: Looks to be moving to a HB role, which a player of his natural scoring ability in a more favourable role will only mean good things. Mid-only at that price I still wouldn't start, but could well challenge the top 8 defenders if he gets the DPP, so bump him up in draft.
Short: Improved his average to 95 which makes it back-to-back 90+ on a wing, not many can do that and shows how hard it is to score as a mid without CBAs

Name: Jye Caldwell
Comment: Former pick 11 finally broke out in 2024 with a super impressive 94 (105 post-bye) following a hattrick of 70+ seasons. I always had hope and I'm glad Scott finally gave him the time in the middle, 45% CBAs for the season with 64% post-bye. That should be the minimum heading into 2025 and with another preseason under his belt, a 105 which he did post-bye could be on the cards. That would make him a great pick at that price, but the early bye adds too much risk on what would likely be a very unique move anyway. Still one to monitor early in the year. UPDATE: He has off-season surgery on his hip which isn't ideal for a player with such low ownership. That combined with the early bye makes it too tough for me.
Short: Finally broke out after teasing in the past, 105 post-bye could be sustained with CBAs likely to stay

Name: Max Holmes
Comment: Holmes is a future star and who had already broken out IRL, but had his Fantasy breakout in 2024. After starting his career on a wing, he started 2024 as a distributor off half back and excelled, averaging 99 pre-bye. He still spent some time in the midfield, attending 23% centre bounces, but this increased as the season went on - 37% post-bye, 44% L5 and 58% in the finals. Geelong view him as their future midfield star, so I expect those numbers to remain high, despite the addition of Bailey Smith in the trade period. His scoring reduced as his CBAs increased, such is the nature of the modern half back role compared to the inside mid. However, Holmes should only improve with more time spent in the middle and while I'd rather him back in the half back role, he should still produce numbers that will have him around the top six mark.
Short: A future star (if not already) who had his Fantasy breakout in 2024, scoring dropped a bit when playing more inside but natural improvement should see him push the top 6, even if he loses the HB role

Name: Dan Houston
Comment: Houston has moved to Collingwood after putting up some great Fantasy numbers in Port's system. He's shown a high ceiling, scoring over 120 four times in 2024, three times in 2023 and five times in 2022. However, he's also shown inconsistency, going sub-90 10 times in 2024 (12 times in 2023 and 10 times in 2022). Port defenders play a high scoring system, a lot higher than Collingwood. However, Collingwood defenders may not chip it around as much as they aren't filled with great kickers, so possibly this will change with the arrival of Houston. I'm excited to see what he can produce at the Pies (especially if he gets some midfield time as rumoured), however I wouldn't be taking a punt on him until I see how he settles into the role.
Short: Move to the Pies might not help as their defenders score less than Ports, but he has the attributes (12 games over 120 in last three seasons) and rumoured midfield time also adds interest

Name: Matt Rowell
Comment: It's been a rocky ride for Rowell after bursting on the scene to average an adjusted 111 in his first four career games after averaging 124 at under 19 level. He's since battled injuries (shoulder, knee) and form, but the last two seasons established himself as a consistent inside mid, leading the league in tackles and pressure acts two years in a row and top six in clearances. Unfortunately, this hasn't resulted in decent Fantasy scoring. He plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his 59% contested rate (top eight mids 40%) incredibly low 1.4 marks per game (top eight mids 4.4). He is purely focused on his role. This means his scoring is capped, only nine scores over 100 and three over 120. Unless we see a distinct change in his ball hunting and spread, I think he'll remain around the 90-100 mark, which isn't enough to consider in Fantasy.
Short: Despite leading the comp in tackles 2nd year in a row, 1.4 marks per game is going to make it hard for him to put up any score of note

Name: Chad Warner
Comment: Warner is an emerging star of the comp, if he's not there already. He's one of those players who is more damaging in real-life than in Fantasy, showcased by his 23 Brownlow votes last season, after 16 in 2023 and 12 in 2022. That's a lot of votes for someone who has just averaged over 90 in that time. He did manage 102 pre-bye which was a career high, but struggled with just 85 post. Given his goal kicking ability (1.4 per game in 2024), he does spend some time at half forward and doesn't get the 80%+ CBAs the top Fantasy mids see. He also often cops opposition attention, such is the damaging nature of his game. So while I think he can get to a 105+ level one day, he doesn't do it the conventional way which makes him a hard one to rely on.
Short: Back to back 93 seasons which feels low compared to the impact he'd had in that time, but maybe he's one of those who will always be better IRL than Fantasy

Name: Touk Miller
Comment: After a league leading 122 in 2021, Miller has regressed three seasons in a row and bottomed out in 2024 to average 93. It's been on the back of multiple injuries, with Miller dealing with hamstrings, a torn meniscus and a broken wrist in the last two seasons. The question is whether his less prominent midfield role (61% CBAs compared to the 80% he averaged when at his peak) is due to these injury interruptions or he is slowly being phased out, with young guns Flanders and Will Graham getting exposure in 2024. It was probably the right call given Miller is now 29 and unlikely to be in their starting midfield when they push for a premiership. However, they aren't stacked with mids and if he got back to a 75%+ CBA mid, he could be the perfect underpriced premium, but with an early bye and what we saw in 2024 (42% CBAs post-bye), I'm not willing to take that punt.
Short: Pushed out of the midfield in recent seasons (42% CBAs post-bye) and unless we see that get back to 75+, it's unlikely we see him become a premium again

Name: Hayden Young
Comment: After moving into the midfield at the end of 2023, Young made a permanent move last season and proved to be the big bodied, damaging mid that Freo have been crying out for. He made the All-Australian squad and recently signed an extension to be the longest contacted player in the comp. However, he finished the season averaging 93, which wasn't much more than his prior two seasons when playing half back. He's still so young and will certainly benefit from his first full season in the middle, however I'm thinking he might be one of those players who is far better IRL than in Fantasy. UPDATE: A hamstring injury isn't ideal just before the season starts.
Short: A move to the middle was a success, but didn't result in much of a scoring boost and might be one of those who are far better IRL than Fantasy

Name: Bailey Dale
Comment: Dale had an interesting season. Bevo was up to his old tricks and started Dale as sub in Round 5, where he came on last and scored 14. He then went on to average 111 in his next nine matches, so maybe Bevo was a genius after all. Post-bye was similar to what we've come to expect from Dale in that half back role, a high 80s average which he's done for the last 3. Priced at 93 could be seen as a discount considering it includes his sub game, but based on a large sample size, that's about his capability in the half back role.
Short: A nice stretch of 111 in nine games following his sub game, but returned to the high-80s scoring we now expect from him in the Dogs' half back role

Name: Dylan Moore
Comment: Moore is the definition of a high half forward. He is one of only two forwards in Fantasy who have averaged over 78 in each of the past three seasons (Jeremey Cameron the other) and his lowest season is 10 points more than that benchmark - such is how good he has been in his role. There was the thought he would make the natural transition to the midfield and this began at the end of 2022 where he averaged 101 post-bye from 42% CBAs. However, he's remained as a forward since and considering how good he is in his role and the depth of Hawks midfield, he will likely remain as a high half forward. What helps him is the number of quality small forwards at the Hawks, so not only does he not have to play the typical small forward role (Watson and Ginni have that covered), he also avoids the best small defender. Moore had glandular fever in the preseason last year which explains his slow start but finished with a bang - 105 post bye. That's a high level to maintain for someone who gets only a handful of CBAs, but he's done it for long enough now for it to seem sustainable. There's a bit more value this year in the forward line, combined with his early bye, so he might not be a starting option, but he'll be high in the order as an upgrade target given he's a certain top six forward.
Short: Locked in his customary high half forward role where he's averaged 90 over the last three seasons, that's enough to make him a top couple forward in 2025 even without the CBAs

Name: Darcy Parish
Comment: Parish has displayed attributes of a top-line Fantasy asset - he is a genuine ball magnet and with all the attention going to Merrett, he's never in danger of a tag. This has seen him average 106+ twice in the last four seasons. However, 2024 things didn't go to plan and was his lowest output season since his full-time midfield move in 2021. He missed the first three games of the season with a hamstring injury and then 10 weeks in the middle of the year with a calf. It's not the first time he's dealt with soft tissue injuries and is a big reason why the 2021 All-Australian's numbers have dropped off since. It could be easy to say that if he can regain full fitness, he could be the underpriced mid we're looking for. However, the knock on Parish for a long time was his ball use, the damage of his possessions and his size. In his absence, Jye Caldwell and Sam Durham stepped up and looked great, both finishing top five in the B&F. I think they have both gone past him and while Parish will still have a role to play, I doubt it will be a 80%+ CBA one needed to boost him back to the 105 mark. 12 FEB UPDATE: In doubt to play Round 0 due to a back injury. Not a good sign but could open up the door for Tsatas.
Short: Been a ball magnet in the past and injuries impacted him last season, if he gets back in the main midfield mix he could end up a great value pick, although Durham and Caldwell appear to have leapfrogged him

Name: Kieren Briggs
Comment: After his impressive breakout in 2023, Briggs started slow in 2024. Word is he came back from pre-season out of shape (see Toby Greene's B&F speech) and it showed, averaging 83 pre-bye. He got going later in the year, averaging 100 post-bye and 102 in the finals. That's the level he should hit in 2025, however with the early bye and other value rucks around, he's not being considered as a starting option. Will be a very handy one for draft. 10 MAR UPDATE: Injured early and will miss until after his bye. I'm targeting him in Round 5 or so when he bottoms out as I was bullish on him heading in.
Short: Took a while to get going after his 2023 breakout but when he did he averaged 100 down the stretch which he will look to maintain in 2025, making him a 2nd tier ruck

Name: Reilly O'Brien
Short: He'll likely be a high-80s ruckman again and potentially less if they hand over the reins to Thilthorpe

Name: Elliot Yeo
Short: Ranked 6th amongst mids for PPM but TOG has always been low given injury history who I doubt it gets high enough to challenge the top 8 - will miss the first chunk of the season with knee and ankle injuries

Name: Ollie Wines
Short: Got a midfield and scoring boost in 2024 but hard to see any more value in him now he's 30 and the young guns taking over

Name: Christian Petracca
Comment: Petracca's 2024 finished in Round 13 when he suffered a horrific body blow. He was on just 51 at the time, which means he enters 2025 priced as cheap as he's been since moving into the midfield in 2020. However, it wasn't his only low score of the season. Petracca had eight games under 90 (60%) as he spent a lot more time inside 50 due to Melbourne's forward woes. We talk about CBAs a lot in Fantasy circles, however Petracca's history shows why we are always chasing that magic 80% mark. After a dominant 2021 which saw him finish as a top eight midfielder, he dropped his CBAs from 79% in 2021 to 62% in 2023, including 56% post-bye. It was 54% before going down in Round 13. They won the flag and Trac the Norm in 2021 when he averaged 79%, so the Dees are best with him naturally drifting forward from the middle without having to be positioned there. But if he remains at the 50% CBA mark, it's going to hard for him to average the 100+ needed to be a decent pick. Add on the fact his coming back from severe internal injuries means we'll need to see how he looks in the pre-season games before making a decision on the Demon star. UPDATE: A broken rib at training is a worry given his history, he's still on track to play Round 1.
Short: Horrific injury finished season early, if he can fully recover he's a highly discounted premium but role (reduced CBAs three years in a row) and injury concern add some risk

Name: Jason Horne-Francis
Comment: JHF backed up his impressive first season at the Power where he polled 16 Brownlow votes with 19 in 2024. His 16 in 2023 came from just 18 touches per game, which impressively highlighted the impact he has in a game, had me concerned that he might not have a Fantasy game in him. He tore some games apart with his clearance work and penetration inside 50 from stoppages but you don't get extra points for that in Fantasy and what he lacked was easy possessions. However, he boosted his average by 20 points per game in 2024 and included six games with 107+. He's been likened to Dangerfield since day one and Danger took four seasons before he averaged over 71, so he's ahead of him at the same stage. He also never had a full pre-season before last year, so he's still building his tank which will hopefully lead to some more outside ball. He's going to be a star, if he's not already, so more attention is going to come his way. But I think he can handle it and with forward status this year, he's a chance to finish as a top forward in 2025. 1 MAR UPDATE: Butters out means he might get more attention, but he's also going to spend more time inside. Been the player of the pre-season and he's now a starter for me.
Short: Showed he has a Fantasy game in 2024 when before he was purely an impact player, heading into his 4th season we're going to see him improve again and be a top three forward

Name: Liam Duggan
Comment: Duggan has been a consistent Fantasy defender, averaging 87 over the past five seasons. It's on the back of a unique CBA and KI combo, where he joined Fantasy guns Harry Sheezel, Sam Flanders, Jack Sinclair and Tom Stewart as the only players to average over 10% in both categories over the season. Interestingly, he scored much better in the weeks he was didn't play in the midfield. In the 11 games he had 0% CBAs he averaged 101. In the 10 games he attended centre bounces he averaged 75. I doubt he'll be required in the midfield as much in 2025 following the recruits and the young guns emerging, which could see him playing as a full-time defender with the potential to average 100. If that occurs, he really puts his hand up in a position that's looking tough to fill. A big watch in the pre-season. 1 MAR UPDATE: Playing pure mid which is a surprise and not a good thing IMO. Passing now.
Short: Averaged 101 in games he didn't have CBAs so if he returns as a full-time defender in 2025, he could be a great pick

Name: Blake Acres
Short: Become a great winger but wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in Fantasy, so this is the best he'll be

Name: Lloyd Meek
Comment: Meek moved to Hawks in 2023 in search for more opportunities after being behind Darcy and Jackson at Freo. It didn't work out in his first year, playing 16 matches but was behind Ned Reeves all year. It looked like 2024 was going to be much the same story when he played VFL in the first two weeks. He got his chance in Round 3 and didn't look back, playing every game since and Reeves playing just the two more. He is their ruck for the future and we typically see rucks continue to improve after their first breakout. 90 is his benchmark in 2025 which will make him be a 2nd tier ruck. 10 MAR UPDATE: Gave Grundy a touch up in Round 0 and set to generate some cash. With his bye and other options, I'm still not considering him as a starter.
Short: 7 years of playing back-up, got his chance in 2024 and emerged as one of the best rucks in the comp, can push his average into the 90s to be a 2nd tier ruck

Name: Tom De Koning
Comment: TDK broke out in 2024, going from a 3rd tall forward / ruck with potential to a modern day athletic ruckman. The Blues preferred Pittonet as their number one ruck in 2023, with TDK playing second fiddle. However, he got his chance to be the sole ruck in 2024 due to Pittonet's injury and he took it with both hands. In the 10 games he played as solo ruck, he averaged 99. In the seven games playing alongside Pittonet, it dropped to 72. Interestingly, Carlton went 9-1 in games where TDK was solo ruck and 4-10 in games Pittonet played. I can't see Pitt playing in 2025 unless TDK is injured, which means he should have his first full season as solo. If he can average 100 he will prove a great selection and I think he's certainly capable of that. 24 FEB UPDATE: No Pitt to start the year. Lock and load for me with the nice early run.
Short: Averaged 99 as solo ruck which he'll do full-time in 2025, giving him a lot of upside

Name: Tom Stewart
Comment: A good as Tom Stewarts career has been (5 x All-Australian), he's always seemed to let Fantasy coaches down - highlighted by the fact he's yet to ever average 100+, despite having long stretches of being a top defender. He averaged just 80 through the first 13 games last season and unlike 2022 (concussion) and 2023 (knee) where he went down in the first quarter early in the season, it wasn't injury related. Max Holmes' emergence off half-back took some ball away from him but it was the constant opposition attention that got him in the end. It forced Chris Scott's hand who moved the star defender into the middle in what was one of the positional moves of the season. From 0% CBAs until then to averaging 73% the rest of the way, before being injured in Round 24. It resulted in an average of 107 - he was around the ball, tackled, but also drifted back and still got his customary cheap marks in defence but avoided the opposition attention. If he continues with that form in 2025 then he's obviously discounted. However, Geelong have strengthened their midfield, so it's possible/probable that he'll move back to defence. He also has an early bye, shared with many other discounted defenders. It's also not the first time he's come into the season 'discounted' and seems to find a way to stitch up those who start with him. He's just a watch for me and maybe someone to consider post his early bye.
Short: Averaged 107 when moved into the midfield mid-season, however an early bye, injury history and role uncertainty still makes it a risky play despite his cheap price tag

Name: Tom Liberatore
Short: A gun inside mid in real life, but just one season above 100 once in 14 seasons shows his Fantasy game is limited - add to it his concussion struggles in 2024

Name: Jack Viney
Short: Averaged 113 post-bye in 2023 when Oliver was out which gave hope for 2024, but dropped to 87 despite Oliver and Trac missing a lot - he's too inside for Fantasy

Name: James Sicily
Comment: Sicily's ability to find space and accumulate marks and kicks as a key position defender is remarkable, which led him to a 105 average in 2023 to be the 2nd highest averaging defender. It didn't all go to plan in 2024 as he dropped his average by 16 on the back of Hawks being better (less ball down back + quicker movement once they had it), injuries (dislocated his shoulder multiple times and required off-season surgery) and some time spent forward. Those three factors remain in 2025 plus there's the addition of Barrass and Battle in the off-season, which could see Sicily play forward more in 2025. The early bye also makes it tough so he's not in my starting calculations, however it he does remain as a defender, then he'll be freed up to play a rebound role and could be in store for a big season. In 2023 he averaged 114 with fellow key defender James Blanck in the side and 91 without... 10 MAR UPDATE: Was looking and scoring great to half time then finished the game forward. We expected this to happen, so now seeing it in a real game makes it too risky for me to do now, despite his obvious upside.
Short: Addition of Barrass and Battle could see him play forward in 2025 but if not they may well help him return to the rebounding defender he was in 2023

Name: Karl Amon
Short: Got the half back role we wanted after finishing 2023 with 121 in L5, but only managed an 87 average with Hawks speeding it up

Name: Ed Richards
Comment: Ed Richards transitioned from the half back line to inside mid in 2024 and displayed attributes that he could be a star midfielder. He's always had pace and being able to use it to break away from stoppages proved a weapon for the Dogs who have a relatively slow midfield. In terms of his scoring, the midfield move is a positive one as he was always behind Dale for distribution. He averaged 71 in the first four games before the move, where he averaged 91, excluding Round 11 where he was concussed in the 2nd quarter when flying on 62. This will be his first season training as a midfielder and with the experience from last year, he should improve again. Unfortunately, he's lost his defender status and as a mid-only at that price, you'd want him to average close to 100 to prove a successful starting pick. While I have him pushing into the 90s, I think he'll fall just short of that mark. UPDATE: Treloar out means I think he'll get a CBA boost to 70%+, which could see him get close to that 100 mark. Super unique and probably not one I'd do, but I won't talk you out of it.
Short: Averaged 91 as a mid and could've been higher if not for injury, 2nd season playing there he should improve again especially given he should see more than 57% with Treloar out to start

Name: Tim Kelly
Short: Never averaged 100 due to his below average marks (2.8 per game v 4.4 of top 8) and tackles (4.9 v 5.2), priced 13 below his 2023 season so some value there but WC are less reliant on him than they were then

Name: Brent Daniels
Comment: Daniels is a genuine star and began to get some recognition in 2024, making the AA squad. In Fantasy, he's always scored more than the average small forward as he pushes up to the stoppages and his 72 average in 2023 was an indication of this. However, he improved that by 11 points in 2024 thanks to three scores over 115 in his last seven weeks, including a 171 (29 touches, seven marks, 13 tackles and three goals). We are quick to remove poor scores from averages, but if you consider the 171 as the outlier, Daniels averages 79 for the year which is closer to the level I think he's at in that role. He is effective in stoppages and provides something different, so there is a chance he sees more CBA action in 2025 (14% L5 after 2% in 2025). If this happens, he can push his average up over the 90 mark as Dylan Moore does, but if not, I don't see enough upside to consider starting with.
Short: Best 'small' forward in the comp and his 171 showed he scores better than the average small forward, but unless he gets a boost in CBAs it's unlikely he'll push into the 90s

Name: Jai Newcombe
Comment: After averaging 105 in the L5 of 2023, I had big hopes for Newcome in 2025. 127 in the pre-season game only increased my hopes, which made his 69 average after the first five weeks even more disappointing. He got going after this, winning Hawks' B&F and finishing with 24 Brownlow votes. However, he only averaged 90 points per game following Round 5, which was still below his 2023 average and well below the top eight mids. I can put it down to two things. Newcombe has below average tackle numbers (4.4 v 5.2 of the top 8) which is a shock given he set the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. The Hawks also play a very quick game style, which results in low scoring for their midfield - ranked 13th in the comp (WC, Rich, Geelong and Dees the only ones worse in 2024). It makes me question whether he can push his average to the 100s, which he'll need to do to make him a successful starting pick. Age is on his side but I'm less bullish on Newcombe than I was this time last year.
Short: Very underwhelming start but got going late - 90 after Round 5 and 118 in finals, he'll outperform his price but Hawks' low scoring style and a few mouths to feed will make it unlikely he consistently averages 100+ required

Name: Jordan Ridley
Short: A nice kick-mark game has meant he's been a high scoring defender for periods (108 to start 2021, 2x 120+ in 2023 and 3x 110+ in nine games last year), but soft tissue injuries and defensive roles have meant he hasn't done it consistently and he's already had one this pre-season

Name: Oscar McInerney
Short: Averaged around the 80-mark since being the number one ruck, that's a level below the top ones

Name: Willem Drew
Short: A regular in Port's midfield but plays a team-first role

Name: Lachlan Sholl
Short: I never like a wing with MID-only status, but has now cemented his spot in the team and shown a decent Fantasy game

Name: Gryan Miers
Short: Remarkable 2024 to average 87 in a genuine small forward role, I think that's going to be hard improve on or the very least sustain

Name: James Rowbottom
Short: 2nd in comp for tackles and got a CBA bump in 2024 despite the new additions, however still failed to average 90 due to his lack of outside game

Name: Jarrod Berry
Short: Always highly rated at the Lions and injuries have held him back, yet to get the inside role required to get a boost in scoring and looks settled on the wing

Name: Andrew McGrath
Short: A move to defence for the former number one pick hasn't resulted in any improvement in scoring and is a long way from the 97 he averaged as a mid in 2020

Name: Dom Sheed
Short: A foot injury then hamstring cost him his 2024 season, but even before then he was being pushed out of the midfield to make way for the kids, hit 90 multiple seasons but I don't expect that to happen again - out for the year with an ACL

Name: Jeremy Cameron
Short: Scores better than the average key forward, and averaged 100 L5 2024 (96 pre-bye in 2023), both would make him a clear top 6, but it's too hard for a key forward to sustain that level for a full season

Name: Mason Redman
Short: 3 x 85+ seasons but hasn't come on as a top six prospect as I expected with plenty sharing the distributor role at the Dons

Name: Daniel Rioli
Comment: Much was made of the high price Gold Coast paid for Rioli in the Trade Period, however since moving to defence in 2022 he's been one of the best running defenders in the comp. He averaged 94 post-bye (97 L5) in a struggling Richmond line-up where he shared the kick-in and distribution duties with Jayden Short and Nick Vlastuin. I was shocked to see just 12% next to his name. Gold Coast have been searching for a distributor for a few years now, trialling a number of players including Sam Flanders, Connor Budarick, Rory Atkins, Lachie Weller, Alex Sexton, Joel Jeffery and Wil Powell. The only one who has excelled in the role was Flanders, however he has now moved into the midfield, leaving Rioli to likely take up the number one distributor mantle in 2025. He's had a knee injury in the pre-season and the early bye isn't great, but I wouldn't be surprised to see Rioli challenge the top six defenders come the end of the season.
Short: A move to GC should see him be the number one distributor, a role he's never had fully before and I wouldn't be surprised to see Rioli challenge the top six defenders come the end of the season

Name: George Hewett
Short: Yet to match his terrific 2022 season and while he finished 2024 strong (105 L5 and 108 in finals), the vest is always a risk given Carlton's midfield strength

Name: Jack Crisp
Short: Once a high scoring defender, Crisp has averaged sub-90 since moving into the midfield, so unless we see him move back full-time, he's not going to be relevant as a mid-only

Name: Sam Durham
Short: A breakout 2024 after moving inside from his wing, looks to be their big bodied mid of the future and can improve again but with plenty others racking up points at the Dons, I doubt he pushes the high-90s required

Name: Mitchell Hinge
Short: Backed up his breakout '23 where he averaged 91 post-bye with 88 pre-bye in '24, may not get it all his way now with Laird playing defence (as he did to finish 2024 and Hinge averaged 68 L5) and Cumming taking distribution

Name: Mason Wood
Short: Backed up his 2023 season to average over 80 again, but 11 games under 90 (13 in 2023) shows how inconsistent the wing role can be

Name: Zac Fisher
Short: Had his chance in 2023 playing in the fruitful half-back role for the Roos and was okay at times, averaging 111 in a 5-game stretch mid-season, but may have lost that role to Caleb Daniel and likely on the fringe in 2025

Name: Jacob Hopper
Comment: There was a bit of hope for Hopper leading into 2023, following a trade to the Tigers who lacked midfield depth. However, he's been impacted by injuries in both seasons. When on the park he still falls well short of other midfielders with regular CBAs. He's the reason why you can't rely on pure inside midfielders for Fantasy, as they don't get enough easy possessions and marks (3.7 per game) to take their Fantasy game to the next level. Unless we see a bump in tackle or mark numbers, his scoring in Fantasy is always going to be capped.
Short: Injury prone inside mid with low tackle and mark numbers, resulting in a capped Fantasy game and yet to average over 92 in nine seasons

Name: Colby McKercher
Comment: All the talk of the 2023 draftees was about Harley, but the Fantasy coaches had their eye on the player taken second, Colby McKercher. The highest scoring draftee in this crop, McKercher put up huge numbers in the U18 Champs, averaging 32.5 disposals and six marks for an average of 131 across his four games. His Coates Talent League numbers were also great, managing to hit the scoreboard frequently for 12 goals from nine games and averaging 29.4 disposals and 112 points. His debut season wasn't all smooth sailing though. We all hoped he would step straight into the ‘Sheezel role’, and while he did start in defence, he was also used as a mid at times and injured himself early on just two in Round 5. It was after this where he moved back to a genuine half back role, and from Round 7 to 9 he had 24 kick-ins, after taking just five in the first six weeks. He averaged 99 in these games, however developed a stress fracture to his foot which saw him miss the next seven weeks. He returned in the same role, taking over five kick-ins in each of the last seven games for an average of 94. He's eventually going to be a midfielder and like we saw with Sheezel, that could happen as soon as this year. There is also talk of him playing on a wing. In the short term, we'd rather him stay in defence and while Daniel is expected to take up a lot of the kick-ins, any talk of McKercher playing back there would be enough for me to lock him into my starting team.14 FEB UPDATE: Sounds like he's more wing/HFF than the HB role we hoped. Sounds like he's going to have a great season still, but not the juicy role we hoped.
Short: The highest scoring player in the draft, didn't go all his way in his debut seaosn, but averaged 95 in the 10 games with 5+ kick-ins, if he settles in defence this year he can go close to a top six defender, just the risk is he plays wing

Name: Will Ashcroft
Comment: Ashcroft had all Fantasy coaches excited when he entered the league following a 118 average at under-age level. He didn't disappoint, averaging 83 in his first season before an ACL injury cut it short. He returned in Round 16 and didn't miss a beat, averaging 112 in the last three matches of 2024 before an impressive finals run which included 30 touches and a goal (109 points) in the GF to take out the Norm Smith. He did this off an ACL, so now heading into his first full pre-season, Ashcroft is poised to take his game to the next level. He's no doubt going to be a star of the comp and he has the attributes to be a Fantasy stud also, with his ability to generate uncontested marks (5.2 marks per game v 4.4 of the top eight mids) along with his natural ball-winning ability. His tackle count (2.5 per game v 5.2 of the top 8) will improve as he gets more time in the middle (27% CBAs in 2024, increased to 43% in finals).
