The Lions generally score quite low in Fantasy for mids, highlighted by Lachie Neale who won a Brownlow with a sub-100 average and Josh Dunkley who is averaging 10 points per game less in than when he had the same role at the Dogs. I think he can push the high-90 mark in 2025 which would be enough to make him a good starting pick, however the early bye makes it harder. A lot comes down to his Round 0 performance which will help make the decision for you.
Short: Showed what he can do returning from an ACL to average 91 in L5 and finals (including a Norm Smith), a full-preseason and more opportunity he's poised to breakout, just how high can he go in a low-scoring Lions midfield

Name: Nick Blakey
Short: Career best 80 in the running defender role, his lack of slow/cheap footy will likely mean he won't ever challenge the top 6

Name: Trent Rivers
Comment: Rivers was a regular in the Dees defence since debuting in 2020 but it took until last season for him to move into the midfield where he was a Fantasy stud as a junior. He only attended CBAs in one game before the bye, but was a regular post, averaging 65% CBAs and only dipping below 50% once. It was obviously fast-tracked by Oliver and Petracca missing, but I can see him maintaining that role even with them returning in 2025. He'll have to play 4th fiddle though, with Viney the other regular in the Demons midfield. In the past, the 4th mid for the Dees hasn't averaged much (Sparrow/Jordon/Hames/ANB all averaging less than 73 in 2023 when playing the 4th banana), but they never had the natural Fantasy game of Rivers. I can see him maintaining his finish to 2024, which might be enough to make him an okay starting selection, but will have him only a few points short from challenging the top six defenders. FEB 22 UPDATE: Could not have been more impressive in the match sim. Led Dees for CBAs and I think he could be top 3 for the year, overtaken Viney and possibly see more than Trac if he rests forward. No early bye I now have him above Perryman as a nice discounted player to plug into the backline while the top end guys (hopefully) come back in price a bit. 2 MAR UPDATE: First look with Oliver and Petracca and was underwhelming, 30% CBAs and just the 61. Easy to be reactive but hard to start now.
Short: Got his chance in the midfield post-bye without Trac and Oliver and averaged 89, if he can keep the role with those two back we should see him sustain that level

Name: Harry McKay
Short: Gun key forward who got a boost in scoring while playing backup ruck, but I doubt he can improve on his 82 given he averaged 70s when he won a Coleman

Name: Luke Parker
Comment: Parker is as tough and consistent as any player in the AFL, which is why it was a shock to me he fell out of favour at the Swans last season. After a delayed start to the season after having surgery on a broken arm and a suspension in the VFL, Parker played largely forward and was even the sub when returning to the senior side. It led to an off-season move to the Roos who are crying out for someone of his calibre. The only thing is the Roos aren't short on midfielders, so there is a chance the 32-year-old will play more of a leadership role and see now more midfield time than he did last season. However, if he is in Clarkson's midfield plans, he could prove to be a to be a top six forward in 2025 - he has averaged 90+ in each of the 10 seasons prior to 2024. Unfortunately, he's not priced on his 66 2024 average as he played less than 10 regular season games, so he comes in priced at 82 which isn't enough discount to warrant a starting selection, unless we see a clear full-time mid role in the pre-season. UPDATE: Training heavily with the mids and with Wardlaw expected to miss the first chunk of the year, he's the like-for-like replacement. Price still a bit high for a 32-year-old and I've got five 'premium' mids ahead of him for attractiveness (Macrae, Smith, Daniel, Sanders), but he's probably next in line if you have your doubts on the four or wanted to start five premos. 1 MAR UPDATE: I would've liked to have a look at him before Round 1. Not sure I could go in blind.
Short: Now at the Roos after falling out of favour in Sydney, averaged 90+ the 10 seasons prior which would be enough to be a top 6, age is a factor but if he gets consistent CBAs he's a smoky top six - unfortunately not discounted as much as he should be

Name: Xavier Duursma
Short: Career best season after moving to the Dons, wingmen typically top out in the mid-80s so I doubt he has much more improvement in him

Name: Jordon Sweet
Comment: Sweet moved to Dogs to Port after being stuck in the VFL behind English for three seasons where he was putting up some massive scores, including 125 in his last six matches of 2023. So when the trade was made which saw him move to Port, a team who just lost their ruck (Lycett), we all thought he'd be the perfect R2 for us. However, shortly after the move, Port also added Soldo who was given the first crack at the role. He got a chance in Round 6 where he played alongside Soldo and scored 60 before being subbed out after 59% TOG. He then went in solo and managed 96 against Marshall and 88 the round after, before missing the next week with Covid and surprisingly not returning the week after. It wasn't until Round 15 where Port made the call that he was their number one man and he went on to play the next 10 matches and finals. He averaged 84 in that time, which was impressive but not enough to catch the eye for Fantasy. There was a 120 there but that was against Freo's back-up ruck, so while I think he will improve again with the experience, I doubt he can push into the high-90s required to be a good starting pick.
Short: Took a while but finished 2024 as Port's number one ruck, I think the role sticks and based off VFL form and finals he can push his average into the 90s

Name: Nick Vlastuin
Short: Always shown a scoring ability but never done it consistently enough, Rioli leaving might open up more distribution but doubt we see him average more than he did in 2022 given Richmond's likely struggles

Name: Jason Johannisen
Short: Hamstring tendon cut his year short where he was averaging 86, which is the mark he's been at since returning to defence in recent seasons, sadly he has done his hammy again to start 2025

Name: Will Setterfield
Short: Former pick five can certainly score - 92 in 2023 and 99 in 2024 but from only 14 games combined as injury and selection have kept him out, will likely be on the fringe again

Name: Tom Mitchell
Comment: Of current players, Tom Mitchell has been the best Fantasy player of all. He was in his own league in 2017 and 2018, averaging 127 and 128 before missing the entire 2019 season with a broken leg. Since then, he hasn't reached those heights. You could put it down to the recovery, then being in a team that fast-tracked a rebuild and experimented with younger players through the midfield. A change of clubs gave me optimism that we might see the return of the Pig. However, I underestimated how 'team-first' they are at the Pies and Mitchell bought into that mentality. He averaged 93, three fewer than he did when pushed out of the midfield at the Hawks and then 78 last year which was cut short with a foot injury. He started sub once and was subbed out twice in those six games, so he's found himself on the fringe at the Pies. The foot injury has flared up in the pre-season and he's been in a moon boot. Sadly, the Pig days are over.
Short: Former Fantasy stud is now a role player at the Pies and their 'team-first' mantra means his pig days are over, foot injury has also impacted his pre-season

Name: Jayden Short
Comment: Short was the number one defender in Fantasy up until in Round 7, 2022, averaging 107. He then moved into the midfield and his output has been down ever since. He has returned to his natural position in defence, however his scoring hasn't been as high as it was in the past due to injuries (scored a 25 in 2023 which impacted his average and 11 last year) and Rioli moving to defence and becoming Richmond's preferred rebounder. Removing those injured scores, Short has averaged 89 over the past two seasons, so he hasn't been as bad as it looks. Adding to this, Rioli moved to the Gold Coast in the off-season, meaning there should be more ball for Short in 2025. The only concern is that Richmond are going to be bad, so their total team points are likely to be the lowest in the comp. Can Short manage a 90+ average if the team is scoring less than 1300? If there's a position that can, it would be in defence given the amount of ball being back there. Just look at the scores of the Kangaroo defenders in their recent seasons. I'm confident he can get back into the 90s which would make him a good selection at that price.
Short: A top defender in the past has his chance to bounce-back with Rioli leaving, Tigers' likely struggles a concern but that could also provide an opportunity

Name: Harry Himmelberg
Short: Hasn't hit the heights he did post-bye in 2022 (110), averaging 83 when playing in defence since and with Whit taking all the distribution, it's likely the level he'll stay at

Name: Jeremy McGovern
Short: Reminded the football world how good he is with an All-Australian season, but that only resulted in a 80 average (career best) which shows the limited scoring of key defenders

Name: Christian Salem
Comment: Salem has had three poor seasons after being a consistent defender who always hovered just below the top 6. He's had excuses. In 2022 he injured his knee in the first minutes of Round 1 on 3, forcing him to miss the next 10 games. In 2023, Salem has been placed on a modified training program in the pre-season due to a thyroid concern. In 2024 he injured a hamstring on five which impacted his average. However, even when he was fit in the last 36 months, he hasn't been the main distributor. Steven May takes a crazy amount of the kick-ins, and Salem took just 9% of them last year (7% post-bye the prior season). However, this increased to 27% in the final three rounds, the most it's been in that time. It netted a 96 average which is back to the level he was in 2021. A full pre-season and maintaining the kick-in role could see him bounce back in 2025 but I think I like Short a bit better around the same price.
Short: After experimenting in the midfield/forward to start 2024, Salam returned to defence but still looked a long way off the 90+ averaging defender he's been in the past

Name: Bailey Scott
Short: 102 post-bye in 2023 caught the eye, but never got the half back role in 2024 and scoring/inconsistency reflected that of the wing role, only hope is if he moves to defence this year

Name: Jordan De Goey
Comment: De Goey burst into Fantasy relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae has played him as a pure mid since, however he's never met those scoring heights consistently, averaging 82 in that time. It been a mixture of both the Pies' low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. It's working IRL, where he's a genuine star of the comp, so I doubt we'll see the 100+ De Goey (or even 90+) again under McRae. UPDATE: Currenly dealing with an injury that has impacted most of his pre-season.
Short: Career best of 86 despite averaging 47%+ CBAs in each of the last four seasons, he's far better IRL than Fantasy

Name: Izak Rankine
Comment: Rankine is a gun small forward who always had hopes of moving into the midfield, and we saw the start of it in 2024 with immediate impact. He provided the Crows with much needed pace in there, and generated discussion of him potentially being one of the best players in the comp. This was a week before he had 30 disposals (16 contested), eight clearances and a goal against the Pies, however injured his hamstring in the final minute which halted his momentum. In his second game back from injury, he had 27 touches (14 contested), six clearances and two goals and the discussions started again, before he was suspended for four weeks for his hit on Starcevich who had a defensive role on him. He missed the final game after being concussed in Round 23. Amongst the interrupted season, the Crows found the line-breaking, goal kicking midfield they've been starved of. In the five matches Rankine attended over 40% CBAs, he averaged 94. Adelaide's midfield mix is set for a shake up following the off-season acquisitions of Peatling and Draper, however he still remains their most dangerous option and I'd expect him to maintain his CBA level of 40% in 2025, which could see him push his average into the 90s and become a worthy top six option. 27 FEB UPDATE: Most CBAs for Crows in pre-season a great sign. It's happening.
Short: Got his chance in the midfield and shined before injury and suspension derailed his season, averaged 94 when 40%+ CBAs which you'd think he maintains in 2025

Name: Patrick Dangerfield
Comment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the 2nd best player in Fantasy. He's now 34 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 16 games last season at just 71% TOG. That, combined with his MID-only status, means he is not an option this season, despite being priced 43 points below his career high.
Short: 4 sub-90 seasons in a row suggests the past Fantasy-stud is well past it in Fantasy now, despite still having impact on field

Name: Ed Langdon
Short: Outside wingman finished 2024 strong with 84 post-bye (90 L5), so there's some value there but not as a MID-only with no CBAs - despite Melbourne saying he might play inside

Name: Scott Pendlebury
Comment: After 11 seasons in a row averaging at least 98, Pendlebury has now gone sub-90 four years in a row. While still playing a great role IRL, he's finally slowing down from a Fantasy perspective. He still plays a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 66% of their centre bounces. At 37, I'm waiting for him to step back and possibly get DPP at some stage during the season, but he keeps getting it done.
Short: 4 years in a row sub-90 and his first sub-80 shows he's finally slowing down

Name: Justin McInerney
Short: A handy utility who spent time in defence, forward and even inside in 2024, but plays mostly on a wing and most of the play goes through the Gulden wing instead

Name: Alex Neal-Bullen
Short: Showed a bit of a Fantasy game in his early year but been a valuable defensive forward in recent years, I doubt he sees mid minutes after the move to the Crows but worth keeping a watch

Name: Luke Jackson
Comment: Despite being very young in ruck terms, Jackson has the attributes to be a top-line Fantasy ruck. In his first season at Freo, he surpassed 100 six times, and averaged 64% CBAs in those 6, including a monster 149 when he had 88%. He also had six sub-70 games, and averaged 19% CBAs in those 6. In 2024, he surpassed 100 four times and averaged 77% CBAs in those and eight sub-70 games averaging 29%. Fair to say he can score when playing as the number one ruck, but when forced to spend more time forward, he scores like a key forward. Freo have signed Sean Darcy for the long-term and hope to have him on the park more in 2025, so it's hard to see Jackson having an avenue to consistent scoring unless Darcy goes down again. There is every chance this can happen based on Darcy's injury history, but for now Jackson isn't an attractive starting option. 6 FEB UPDATE: Darcy is set to miss the start of the season. If he goes into Round 1 solo, he's no doubt an attractive option in the forward line, priced at 79 when he averages 94-99 in that role. However, those who did it last year needed an exit plan and we saw Freo ruck Reidy in Round 24 and kept Jackson forward, so I don't think I'd do it. Despite him having a very strong pre-season from all reports. 13 FEB UPDATE: Looks like they'll head in with Jackson starting forward, then spending time in the ruck but also inside mid. Been Freo's best player in the pre-season so far and I can see him being an improver this year - just the role uncertainty means I'd still find it hard to start him.
Short: Had enough chances to ruck solo and managed 94 in those games (99 in 2023) but it was his 67 average when playing second ruck (77 in 2023) which is concerning given Darcy is back fit

Name: Tom Powell
Comment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powell’s first season, which is why it was great to see him getting his chance in the midfield in 2024 following two disappointing seasons. The former pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year. After a strong pre-season, Powell played every game in 2024 for a 79 average. His role was still up and down though. When he attended 50%+ CBAs, he averaged 90 and showed some great clearance work. He also had a game playing half-back, where he scored 122. In his other games, where he averaged just 30% CBAs, he averaged 61. I think he can play and he's shown he can score in the right role. However, with Parker and FOS adding to their midfield and Daniel set to play the half back role, I'm not sure where that puts Powell in 2025, so I'm not interested in taking a punt unless I get confirmation of a 50%+ CBA role or a half back one. UPDATE: Wardlaw injury might see Powell get that bump after all. Nice praises coming for Powell from North over the pre-season and he's a genuine breakout candidate. Not one I'd start with given unknown and uniqueness, but one I'm certainly watching. 14 FEB UPDATE: Their best in the practice match. Big season in coming. Still hard to do banking on natural progression though.
Short: Finally displayed the talent he showed in his debut season, North's midfield is now getting pretty deep so hard to know what role Powell will play in 2025

Name: Liam Baker
Comment: Baker did a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He excelled at all of them, but a career best average of 79 reflects how hard he has been to trust in Fantasy given he plays a team-first approach and a variety of roles. He's much better than the 79 suggests (87 pre-bye in 2024 with 44% CBAs) and a move to West Coast might see him finally settle in a role and become a more consistent Fantasy scorer, but I'm not prepared to take that risk without seeing it in a few games first.
Short: He can play multiple roles and does all to great effect, however he's been hard to trust as it changed week-to-week at Tigerland, if he settles into a HB or midfield role at WC he could prove a forward smoky

Name: Jack Bowes
Comment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns, where he played predominantly in defence. He looked to arrive in 2021, averaging 95 in the first half but has battled with injury. He arrived at Geelong in 2023 and since then has very much a role player, playing back, wing, on-ball and forward. He's also been used as sub a few times given his versatility and Geelong's depth, with three games with less than 50% TOG in 2024 (4 in 2023). He's underpriced if you remove these games and no doubt he's a natural scorer, however it's hard to see his situation changing following Geelong's off-season additions so it's too risky for me.
Short: A natural scorer with a nice history but since arriving at the Cats has been very much a role player, including seven games as sub in the last two years, so he's too hard to trust

Name: Kane Farrell
Comment: The booming left footer has become a regular for the Power since Amon left in 2022, playing 44 games in the last two seasons. His scoring has slowly improved - 60 pre-bye 2023, 72 post, 76 pre-bye 2024 and finished with 81 post. The opportunity is there in 2025 with Dan Houston leaving, who had the second most kick-ins (80) last year behind Farrell (85) with Burton third (59). Houston has only missed two games since 2022 which Farrell has played. Farrell scored 97 in one of them and then was on 51 last year before doing a hamstring and was subbed off after just 35% TOG. VERY small sample size, but it's logical that Farrell should benefit greatly without Houston. Can he boost his average to the 90 mark and prove a good starting selection? Houston is a better player but he averaged above 90 three years in a row in the role Farrell will likely take up. He hasn't shown much of a Fantasy game to date which brings some doubt, but if you're looking for a unique defender and a cheap price, I think you can do a lot worse than Kane Farrell. UPDATE: Has had an interrupted pre-season due to a hamstring, managed to play a quarter of a recent match sim but will working his way back. Not the ideal news for someone of his low ownership percentage, so I've knocked him down slightly but still got a big watch on him in the pre-season games.
Short: A regular now with 44 games in last two seasons, poised for more opportunity with Houston leaving

Name: George Wardlaw
Comment: There has been limited exposed form for Wardlaw over the last three years, but what we have seen has been outstanding. He was limited to just four games in his draft year due to hamstring injuries but of those, was best on ground in Round 1 and BOG again in the AFL Academy game. He was on a modified pre-season program and didn't debut until Round 10, but it was one of the better debuts you'll see - 16 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 63% TOG. He backed it up in Round 13 with 22 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 70% TOG and 22 touches and seven tackles from 68% in Round 16. However, he was a late out Round 17 and subbed out in Round 18 and then played just the one more game for the year where he again had nine tackles in 55% TOG. In all he finished his debut season with eight matches at just 60% TOG. Following his first full pre-season, he increased his TOG to 73%, but his PPM didn't change so it only yielded an average of 78. He wins 49% of his touches contested (top eight mids 40%) while only averaging 19 touches per game. To me he looks more like an impact / inside player and will need time to build his endurance and grow his game to average mid-to-high 20 touches. It will come, but with the Roos' midfield depth, I don't think they will be in any rush and it might be another 12 months before we see this future star really breakout in Fantasy. UPDATE: Another hamstring injury is a big worry, really deserves some luck.
Short: Plenty to love about Wardlaw and the way he plays, question is if he has a Fantasy game to match his elite inside work, unfortunately he's injured a hammy again

Name: Connor Macdonald
Comment: MacDonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder, his 121 average at NAB League was second only to Nick Daicos. He's obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and managed to play 65 games in his first three seasons. So far, he's been limited to a small forward role. I expected him to see some midfield time last season, however it never eventuated, averaging just 1% for the year. However, he showed great improvement over the year, despite the limited role, averaging 69 pre-bye, 92 post and 97 in his L5. In a year that's short on forwards, a 97 average for a forward priced at 78 would prove a great starting pick. He can obviously score (had 37 touches and 126 points in his one VFL game in 2023). However, I doubt he can average 97 across a full season if he remains as a pure forward. CBAs in the pre-season matches and Round 0 are the key, but Mitchell seems pretty set on his blue collar mids.
Short: A natural scorer (2nd to Daicos in draft year) but stuck in a forward role, 92 post-bye is impressive but I'd need to see CBAs in pre-season before taking the punt

Name: Sean Darcy
Comment: Darcy managed just 12 games last season, three of which he lasted less than 50% TOG and another he missed the rest of the season after. It's been the story for the last few seasons as he's struggled to stay on the park. He's heading into his age 26 season, so he should be at his peak as a ruck. Following his 2021 season where he was talked about as a potential All-Australian ruck (even with a knee injury in the pre-season and a PCL injury mid-year impacting what could've been a higher average), he hasn't been able to do a full pre-season. He broke a thumb, had sore groins and then an Achilles injury saw him miss the start of the 2022 season, he then missed the practice match in 2023 after dealing with some Achilles tightness. In 2024 he missed the first five weeks with a knee injury, and then proceeded to miss six more due to other injuries. Off-season knee surgery will limit his pre-season again, but he got onto it early this time so hopefully he can complete more than he has done in the past. The reports are that he's in good shape, however Freo will likely take a cautious approach, especially as they have Luke Jackson who is more than capable in the ruck. He's averaged 95 across the last two seasons when you exclude his injured games, and that's without a pre-season. The risk is there, but I think he can manage that level if he can get through which would make him a great starting pick. The risk is reduced with the best 18 rounds early in the year, so if he looks the goods in the practice matches (noting he missed practice matches in each of the last three seasons), then I'd be confident enough to start him. UPDATE: A trip to Doha in Jan was unexpected and I'm not sure what to make of it. Has he had a setback or was it always part of the plan and will he now come back stronger? I guess the pre-season game will tell. 6 FEB UPDATE: So he's getting surgery on his ankle and will miss the start of the season. Cross him off your starting plans. Might still come at good value in draft.
Short: Just 12 games last year with multiple injuries, hasn't had a full pre-season in four years and coming off knee surgery, but if you can handle that risk there is obvious upside give he's averaged 95 in last two years without injured games

Name: Jarman Impey
Short: Averaged 79 across last two seasons but with all the other Hawk defenders taking distribution (just 3% KI for Impey), it's hard to see that improving

Name: Massimo D'Ambrosio
Short: Terrific first season for the Hawks to be one of the best wingers in the comp, averaged 82 post bye (90 L5) which is about where the best wings cap out

Name: Clayton Oliver
Comment: Oliver was the Fantasy midfielder prototype - high game time (86% from 2020-2023), high CBAs (85%), high tackles (top 20 each season) and always around the ball (averaged over 30 touches per game). It resulted in him being one of the most consistent midfielders, averaging above the 110 mark the majority of his career. It's why his 2024 season came at such a shock. His off-field troubles were much documented but he also had on-field ones - broken finger, broken ribs and PCL surgery. Fair to say nothing went right. He's back training hard over the off-season and news coming out of Melbourne is that he's back on track. Unless something pops up from now until Round 1, that's enough to make him my first picked in 2025.
Short: Much documented struggles in 2024 saw him average 78 after averaging 113 the four seasons prior, clear bounce-back candidate with reports he's back on track

Name: James Worpel
Comment: After averaging 97 in just his 2nd season and backing it up with another 97 in his 3rd, Worpel genuinely forgot how to football - averaging 79 in his 4th season and dropped another 27 to average just 52 in his 5th. With all the young mids at the Hawks (Ward, MacDonald, Newcombe, Day, Mackenzie, Nash, even more Moore), I thought we wouldn't see him much again. However, he backed up his 67% CBAs in 2023 with 68% in 2024 and was part of a very tight and strong midfield group that includes Newcombe, Day and Nash. Regardless, his inside nature means his scoring is capped at the 85-mark anyway, and he won't be Fantasy relevant anymore.
Short: A regular CBA midfielder for the Hawks who plays an important CBA role, however he's no longer the high scoring one we saw early in his career

Name: Mitch Duncan
Comment: For the majority of his career, Mitch Duncan has been one of the few outside midfielders who are capable of scoring 110+ in Fantasy. He takes above average for marks and a high kick to handball ratio. The risk with Duncan is that he's now over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries in the past. We know Geelong aren't afraid to rest players, even if named. With the off-season additions, I wouldn't be surprised to see him outside their 22 at stages in 2025. For that reason, I’d prefer to start with safer options in defence, despite knowing he has the ability to be a top 10 defender.
Short: Displayed a favourable Fantasy game in the past, but now well over 30, had his share of soft tissue injuries and might struggle for games in 2025

Name: Lachie Ash
Comment: Not many half-back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. He dropped nine points per game in 2024 after an impressive 2023 and that might have to do with Whitfield's amazing season where he dominated the rebounding and distribution duties at the Giants. I still think Ash will be a top six defender in time, but I think 2025 will be too soon while Whitfield is still doing his thing. 10 MAR UPDATE: A 125 in Round 0 and in calculations now due to the lack of defenders and his hidden price of $839k, he's going to prove a nice cash maker. However, a bye in Round 2 might undo some of that and I'm less keen than others on starting him in Classic.
Short: He'll likely be a top six defender one day, but while Whitfield is still doing what he does, I think Ash will need to bide his time

Name: Matthew Kennedy
Comment: Kennedy has a decent Fantasy game about him, however, has long been behind a number of players for midfield spots at the Blues. After back-to-back 80+ seasons in 2020 and 2021, Kennedy averaged 94 from 58% CBAs in 2022, including a season high of 122 from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids. He didn't get over 100 once in 2023 and CBAs dropped to 34%, dropping his average to 70 on the back of four sub-50% TOG games due to being sub. It was much the same story in 2024. He averaged 90 from 14 games when he had 25%+ CBAs, including a season high 134 in Round 22 when the Blues were dealing with injuries and he managed 56%. However, in his other games he averaged 57 from just 12% CBAs and found himself sub multiple times. He moved to the Bulldogs in the off-season where he should see more opportunities, although they do run a deep midfield also. They play in Round 0, so we'll get a good look at Kennedy's role and scoring before having to make a call, but I have the feeling he might surprise a few. UPDATE: Treloar out the start the year might see more mid time to Kennedy than expected, I do think Sanders will slot in to be the fourth in line at the Dogs and Kennedy fifth, which would be enough to see him challenge the top six.
Short: Hope to see more midfield time now at the Dogs, where he's averaged over 90 multiple times in the past which would make him a forward smoky, Treloar missing early gives him a chance

Name: Stephen Coniglio
Comment: Cogs is a Fantasy stud who has two x 110+ seasons and others around the 100 mark, so his 72 average in 2024 from a full-time midfield role is certainly an outlier. He dealt with multiple injuries, subbed out twice in the regular season and once in finals with a knee injury, a shoulder (twice) and a horrific facial injury. Despite the struggles, he still maintained a full-time midfield role, sitting second to Tom Green for CBAs. Despite being 31 this year, he's proven over the years he can score when in the right role. Callaghan is expected to increase his usage but Peatling leaving will open up some opportunity, so Cogs may maintain his level. If so, he's a clear under-priced midfielder. The Round 0 game will be a good opportunity to see his role and scoring to make the call on starting him less risky.
Short: Horror 2024 which included knee, shoulder and facial injuries, clearly underpriced if fully fit but his 70%+ CBAs which he's seen the last two years might be in danger

Name: Jake Soligo
Comment: I've always liked the way this guy goes about it, so I was glad to see him get more midfield opportunities in 2024 after just 9% post-bye in 2023. He had a delayed start to the season due to a pre-season ankle injury and started sub in Round 1. He slowly built into it with 17% CBAs in his first two games before ramping up to 65% until the bye and playing a key role in the Crows midfield. He looked the goods, averaging 97 for five weeks from Round 4, before slowly reducing his impact and his CBAs also reduced, down to 48% post bye. He didn't score over 100 after Round 8 and certainly didn't look the same player. He had two sub impacted games, so removing those he averaged 81 on 57% CBAs for the year. That's a nice progression for a third season but I'd want to see more before banking on a fourth-year breakout, so one I'd rather trade in to than start with, particularly with Dawson, Crouch, Rankine, Draper and Soligo all demanding inside time in 2025. 13 FEB UPDATE: Might be the one to push out to a wing in 2025. Bumped him down a bit.
Short: A mini breakout in 2024 where he averaged 97 for five weeks from Round 4 but failed to go on with it, another year in the system should help but Adelaide's CBA mix is now looking deep

Name: Finn Callaghan
Comment: There has always been a lot of buzz for the former pick 3, and he has been pretty good without completely announcing himself, in both real life and Fantasy. He spent more time inside in 2024 after mainly being on the wing in 2023, but the scoring didn't follow suit boosting his average from 73 to 76 on the back of 43% CBAs (2023 22%). I'm excited to see what he will produce with a full pre-season under his belt (his first two were impacted by his foot and last year his shoulder kept him out of Round 0), and still bullish on his long-term prospects of being a top-end Fantasy asset, but I doubt we'll see the 20-25 point jump this season that he'll need to produce to be a good mid-pricer.10 MAR UPDATE: Gee he looked good. Led GWS for CBAs and that's going to remain, even when Green returns. That's the role change needed to push him to a 100 average and make him a good pick at that price. The issue is the Round 2 bye, is he worth getting for the cash gen? His hidden price is $821k, so he's going to make some money on the way. I still favour those mid-pricers without the bye though at this stage.
Short: High hopes for the former pick three but foot and shoulder injuries have held him back, chance to breakout with a full pre-season but I'd need to see a few games first before being confident

Name: Jesse Hogan
Short: Amazing season IRL, winning the Coleman and Giants' B&F, yet only averaged 78 which shows how hard it is for KPP to score in this game

Name: Ben Keays
Comment: Keays has shown he can score in this game when in the right role. He averaged 108 in 2021 and backed it up with 106 in the first half of 2022, attending 80% of the centre bounces across that time. However, there was a clear role change mid-season and Keays has since spent more and more time forward, 55% in H2 2022, 34% in the L5 2022, 30% H1 2023, 20% H2 2023 and 6% L5. In the three games he scored over 100 during 2023, he averaged 49%. His season high of 129 last year came from one of the three games he attended centre bounces. So there's no doubt he has the capability. The CBA trend isn't in his favour though, and with the Crows now having a number of players who are ahead of him in the CBA pecking order, I think we'll see Keays maintain his forward role in 2025 and not be the top six forward who plays in the midfield that we're after.
Short: No doubt can score when in the right role, but locked into a forward role now where he won the B&F last year, and with the new additions to the Crows' midfield I doubt we see him there again

Name: Oliver Florent
Comment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 90% of the games since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 to 0% in the last two seasons, where he settled on a half-back flank. Normally a natural midfielder-turned-defender is a recipe for high scoring, but with Blakey, Lloyd, Roberts and Mills taking the majority of the distribution back there, Florent's scoring has remained around the 70 mark.
Short: After looking like a future midfielder with 52% CBAs in 2020, he's now purely a defender (0% CBAs in 2023 & 2024) in a side with a lot of mouths to feed back there

Name: Jase Burgoyne
Comment: Burgoyne was one of the stories of 2024, establishing himself in Port's lineup and being a very handy asset on the wing. He was sub twice early in the year, but went on to average 81 outside of those, 89 in his last seven H&A games and continued to average in the 80s during the finals, which included two games that Port were dominated in. These scores are up there with the best wingers in the comp, and his 81 SANFL average (105 in his draft year) shows that he can certainly score. If he remains in the wing role, it's hard to see how he can score enough to make him a viable mid-only starting option. There is the chance he spends more time down back, where there's a vacant position left by Houston and where he scored 104 v Hawks in the final. If this happens, I see a lot of upside and he could prove a great pick. But role and natural improvement is not something I'd be prepared to punt on in my starting squad, so he's more just one to watch in the early rounds.
Short: Broke out to average 89 to finish the season, if he can move the  HB and take Houston's role he'll prove to be a great pick, but if he remains on the wing it's hard to see enough upside even with natural development

Name: Jake Waterman
Short: Always scored above average for a KPF, but I doubt it gets much better than 77 in an All-Australian season

Name: Alex Sexton
Short: A very unlikely relevant player last season, moving from a regular goal-sneak to half back distributor to average 90 pre-bye, but with Rioli and Nobel arriving I can't see that repeating again

Name: Sam Docherty
Comment: Doch is a Fantasy Hall of Famer - multiple 110+ seasons as a defender, including a career high average of 117. However in recent times, he's been dealt with some horrible luck, including doing his third ACL in Round 0 last year. He miraculously recovered to play in the finals, so he's good to go for the 2025 season. However, there are still some question marks. Prior to the knee injury, Docherty had been playing midfield/wing. He averaged a career high 22% CBAs in 2023, which increased as the Blues went on their winning streak in the second half of the season. He maintained his role in Round 0. His scoring is less prolific playing in the midfield than half back, so we certainly want to see him move back behind the ball to make the decision to start a lot easier. If not, with MID-only status, you'd want him to average mid-90s to prove a good starting selection which is a big ask for someone with the injury history of Doch. Until we see his role in pre-season, it's going to be hard to declare Doch as an absolute lock, despite the obvious discount he comes with. UPDATE: Newman out for the year gives greater chance of Doch moving back, meaning he's going to be very hard to pass up. 28 FEB UPDATE: Bumped down a bit after seeing him in the pre-season game, out of my starting calcs despite the soft first up match up.
Short: Former Fantasy stud who recovered from a 3rd ACL in Round 0 to play a final, obvious discount on what he can do but body, role and age add a lot of risk, Newman out helps the role chances

Name: Jy Simpkin
Comment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in Fantasy. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 by another seven points to 95 points per game and 105 post-bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, despite increased CBA minutes, but still managed a respectable 96. Since then, nothing has gone right. In 2023 as he battled with multiple injuries - a hand injury and two concussions - which saw him have three games with less than 50% game time (7, 23 and 48) and drop his average by 20 points per game. Removing those games he averaged 86, which is still a level below his best, but it's hard to hit peak form if you miss regular games for injury. It was a similar story last year, with Simpkin on the end of a significant concussion in the practice match and missed Round 1. He also tore a tendon in his finger in the first practice match and was forced to wear a glove for the first two months of the season. He then missed four games from Round 8 with a quad complaint, but returned to post a season high 132 from a then season high 65% CBAs, after averaging 35% until then. But once again, injury hit and he missed the following week with hamstring tightness. He played out the rest of the year averaging 84, mixing his time between forward and the midfield. With forward status, he can certainly contend with the top six and average 90+ if he maintains a 65%+ CBA role. However, with the Roos increasing their midfield depth, I feel like we might see Simpkin spend more time forward in 2025 which will limit his scoring. I just want to confirm his mid/forward split in the pre-season but I'm a bit more confident in the other forwards playing a better role. UPDATE: Wardlaw going down could see Simpkin getting the midfield split we want from him, a big watch in the pre-season games but he's shaping up as a strong starting option - we how have a few to pick from in the forward line!
Short: Was trending to be an elite Fantasy midfielder of the comp before stagnating in 2022 and multiple injuries over the last two seasons have impacted his average, but has he missed his midfield opportunity now?

Name: Matt Roberts
Comment: Roberts was one of the most advanced and prolific accumulators from the 2021 draft, averaging 33 disposals and two goals in the SANFL Under-18s. Since then, he's always been on the radar but it's always hard for kids to get a run in the mature Sydney team and in his seven career matches prior to last season he was predominantly used as sub. However, a move to half-back saw him play regular football last season, playing 23 games. He started strong (83 in first seven games) but tired in the middle period where he was rested for a game and used as sub on multiple occasions. Then he got on a roll, averaging 104 in the last seven rounds of the season (108 in L5). He's a natural scorer and the end to 2024 gives hope that he has another level to go in 2025, however with Blakey, Lloyd and possibly Mills all demanding their share of distribution, it's hard to see how Roberts will sustain a 90+ average which you'd want from him at that price. Not to say he won't reach that level in the future, I just don't think 2025 will be it. UPDATE: Mills playing mid might open up some more ball for Roberts. Lets see how he goes in Round 0. 28 FEB UPDATE: have to bump him after that pre-season effort. All eyes on Round 0 after not being that keen before. 10 MAR UPDATE: 104 in Round 0, not the kick-in role but got a lot of receives from them. In a year I can't find a defender I like, he's now locked for me. His 'hidden' price is about 807k so he's worth it on that value alone.
Short: Always been a scorer at lower level and a move to defence saw him do it at AFL (104 in the last seven of the H&A), a few to feed back there for the Swans so hard to see him entering top six level - for now anyway

Name: Jake Lloyd
Comment: The premier defender in Fantasy for 2019 and 2020, Lloyd has slowly reduced his scoring in the last few seasons and finished 2024 with 79 - his first season below 90 for eight years. Once the Swans' primary distributor, he's now handed over those duties to Nick Blakey and Matt Roberts. Based on recent form and role, it's hard to see him suddenly becoming relevant in Fantasy again, despite his 105 average during the 2024 finals series.
Short: First season in the last eight that he hasn't averaged 90+ shows he's transitioned to a role player from the gun accumulator

Name: Steven May
Short: Handy scorer for a key defender (helps that he takes 50% of the KI - not many full-backs do that) but not enough to make him relevant

Name: Sam Darcy
Comment: He showed signs early in his career that he had something special, but the former pick two announced himself to the comp in 2024, playing 21 games and displaying an extraordinary contested marking ability. You'd assume the 204cm will eventually end up as a ruck, and I had my doubts that he could become Fantasy relevant until then. However, he ranked 8th amongst forwards for points-per-minute in 2024 and got better as the season went on, including a 20 disposal, nine mark and seven goal effort in Round 23. As good as he is, I can't see him challenging the top 6, or even boosting his average by enough to be a worthy selection, unless we see him spend more time in the ruck. Given his prestigious talent, the Dogs are going to treat him carefully and I believe it might be a few years before we see this transition occur. Once it does though - look out.
Short: Come on a lot quicker than expected - and without a heap of ruck time - could be the best player in the comp one day and his Fantasy game should continue to grow

Name: Josh Treacy
Short: Freo have found one here in Treacy, with the 2020 rookie selection shaping as one of the best key forwards in the comp, his tackle and marking ability will mean he will score better than the average KPF, but still not enough to be relevant

Name: Bailey Williams
Short: Showed promise averaging 80 in just his third season, but never took the next step and now a MID-only now coming off a sub-70 average post-bye on a wing

Name: Darcy Wilmot
Short: Aggressive runner and wonderful kick, has improved his output every year since debuting and shown enough that he may be a premium in time, however behind Zorko and Coleman in distribution so will have to bide his time

Name: Miles Bergman
Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: 9 marks and 27 touches in the pre-season. No kick-ins though and everyone feasted against the Saints. Could well be the winner of the Houston trade but I'm not prepared to make the call before Round 1.
Short: Former first rounder played every game the last two seasons and highly rated internally, might get his chance with Houston gone but only gone over 90 eight times in 81 career games so I'd need to see some consistent scoring first

Name: Zach Guthrie
Short: Now a regular for the Cats and every now than then puts up a big score due to his high marking nature, but certainly not enough to be a premium in Fantasy

Name: Travis Boak
Short: 36-year-old has been a gun in the past - IRL and Fantasy - but will again play a mentor role at the Power

Name: Dylan Shiel
Comment: 25 FEB UPDATE: The HB role is real and he was everywhere in the pre-season game. However, I'd need to see something similar (102+) in Round 0 before taking him seriously, as a MID-only priced at 75 and JS doubts make it a tough one.
Short: Been out of favour for a few years now, talk of him taking a half back role which would help but hard to have much confidence in the now 32-year-old

Name: Elijah Hollands
Comment: Hollands never got his chance at the Suns after being drafted pick 7. He managed 118 late in 2022 and looked to have locked away a wing but managed just nine games the following season. After missing the start of the season with suspension, he went on to play every game as a high half forward with some time in the middle. His scoring was strong given the role, averaging 75 for the year and five games over 90. He's a talent and one day will likely become a premium midfielder, however he'll have to bide his time as a role player given the strength of Carlton's midfield.
Short: Became a regular in his first season at the Blues, a clear talent but will likely stay as a role player with the talent in Blues' midfield

Name: Wil Powell
Comment: The highly rated 25-year-old has had his fair share of injuries in the last few seasons. A beautiful kick and found his spot on a half-back flank and showed some great signs in 2023, including just one score under 89 in his last seven. He started 2024 well, averaging 93 in his first three, but then dropped his output after the early bye as Flanders and Sexton took all the distribution. After missing five weeks into his bye, he was underwhelming to finish, averaging 76 post-bye and 66 L5, considering Flanders and Sexton were both out of those roles. Hardwick has always had high scoring half-backs in his system, but the arrival of Rioli and Noble will likely shut down any chance of Powell taking part of this. It's likely he'll become an intercepting defender and not a distributing one, which isn't great for Fantasy, unless we see him move up the ground where he played as a junior.
Short: Disappointing season after emerging as a star (IRL and Fantasy), hoping for a bounce-back but that might be hard with the arrival of Rioli and Noble

Name: John Noble
Short: Been a solid high 70s, low 80s defender at the Pies when in the right role, should get more opportunity at the Gold Coast who score higher than the Pies, but I doubt it will be enough to make an impact in Fantasy

Name: Bradley Hill
Short: Remained in the 70s since moving to the Saints, a long way from the 94 averaging winger he was at Freo, there was a 150 in there but other than that he's become very underwhelming

Name: Will Day
Comment: The 2019 pick 13 had an injury impacted start to his career but broke out in 2023 in his first season as a midfielder, averaging 95 points per game and winning the Hawks' B&F. More impressively, he was more impactful IRL than his Fantasy 95 average suggested. He displayed a great balance of inside ball winning ability and tackles with outside run and marks. I was excited to see how he was going to back it up given he was still so raw and only had one year playing in the middle, however a pre-season foot injury saw him miss the first six weeks of the season. He was scratchy in his return, with a big loss to the Swans, where he scored 47 from 64% TOG. He backed it up with 58 and 85 in a clear sign as to why we don't like interrupted pre-seasons. He then got going, averaging 91 for a 10-week period before scoring just 40 from a full game in Round 21 and then was subbed off 'tactically' in Round 22 on just 36, a clear sign that he wasn't 100% (he did cop some heavy collisions in the month prior). His season ended the following week when he injured his collarbone on just 8, leaving him with a season average (and priced at for 2025) of 74. I have no doubt he is a 90+ midfielder on what I've seen when healthy, so as long as he gets through the pre-season, he's someone I'd be looking to start with - even with his early bye, he'll have four price rises before it anyway. 10 MAR UPDATE: The 4 price rises are going to be significant following his 129 in Round 0. The concern is the tags which will no doubt come now, but he's locked due to the cash gen (hidden price $811k) and how good his looked doing it.
Short: Nothing went right in 2024 after a breakout 2023 where he averaged 95, I have no doubt he can return to that level as long as he's healthy which he wasn't last year

Name: Callum Mills
Comment: Mills has had a shocker 24 months. After back-to-back 109+ seasons possessing the perfect marks/tackle combo we crave in Fantasy, nothing has gone right since. In 2023 he dropped his average by a massive 25 points per game on the back of being forced to play a key defensive role early while many of the Swans' key backs went down (averaged 12% CBAs from Round 4-6, including 0% in Round 5 and averaged 84 in that time) and then popping a calf in the first minute of Round 9 when he just started building in the midfield (47% then 63% CBAs in Round 7 and 8, scoring 110 in the latter) when on 3. He returned in Round 15 when Swans beat WC by 171 and was subbed off just after half time on another low score, so the 84 season average had legitimate excuses. So when you see he averaged 14 points less than that in 2024 makes you really question things. It started on Mad Monday 2023 where he injured his shoulder and then suffered a calf injury just as he was nearing a return, meaning he missed the first 17 weeks. He returned in Round 18, scoring 44 from 62% TOG (0% CBAs), then missed the following week after pulling up sore. His defensive attributes and versatility has always been a burden for him in Fantasy, often shifted to be the loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. But never key defence. He played the final five games, averaging just 59 in the next three (25% CBAs, sub 70& TOG for two of them), but finished with 91 and 107 playing a pure defensive role. He maintained this role in finals where he averaged 75 before a hamstring injury saw him miss the prelim and GF, an indication that his body just wasn't right. Looking at it now he's still just 27, so he should be in his prime. But his role is still very much an unknown, particularly with Dean Cox now in charge. If he returns to the midfield I can see him being a knockout pick at that price and he'll enter with a chip on his shoulder. If he plays in defence, I'm not so sure. Swans have Blakey, Lloyd and Roberts who take a lot of distribution. We saw Mills average 84 in the role in 2023, albeit a more lockout one, and 91 in his four games to finish last year in the role. As a defender, a high-80s average at that price should prove to be a good selection. Fortunately we get to see what he does in the Opening Round, both scoring and role, before having to make the call. But if he scores less than 80 in a defensive role, I think I'd wait til after his Round 3 bye. UPDATE: Great pre-season and playing pure mid in match-sim, I've bumped him up a bit. 24 FEB UPDATE: Foot injury will see him miss the start of the year.
Short: Once one of the Fantasy elite (back-to-back 109+ in '21 & '22), but had a shocking 24 months with injury, sounds like he's back fit and shaping in a midfield role, making him a perfect bounce back candidate and a top six chance

Name: Harry Perryman
Comment: Perryman had always been a reliable wing/midfielder for the Giants, averaging 85+ for the three season to 2022 and slowly spent some more time inside (including a season high 114 from 51% CBAs in the first game after Leon left). He started in the opening centre bounce of 2023, however injured his hamstring in the opening minutes on 2, forcing him to miss the next four weeks. He returned in Round 6 and had CBAs in his next five games, averaging 84 from 52%. However, he moved back to defence after Round 10, seeing CBAs in just one other match for the season, averaging 70 for the games he didn't get CBAs. He played 21 games last year, exclusively in defence, with no CBAs and an average of 73. He now finds himself at Collingwood on a big deal and likely to find himself in a prominent role, whether that be in defence (without Whitfield taking all the usage) or inside mid. Both have upside and I'm interested to see where he plays and how he scores in the Opening Round as he could be a smoky at that cheaper price. 20 FEB UPDATE: Looks set to be in that full time mid role and getting nice praise from the players. I'm getting bullish on him and think he can push his average into the 90s which would make him a great pick at that price.
Short: Likely to take up a more prominent role at the Pies, has averaged 88 when given CBAs in the past so there's some upside there if he gets midfield time

Name: Charlie Curnow
Short: Only averaged 80 in his back-to-back Colemans years shows the game isn't suited to key forwards

Name: Brayden Fiorini
Short: Obvious Fantasy ability with 132, 138 and 135 VFL averages in the last three years, just unlikely to have the role or even play at AFL level

Name: Callum Wilkie
Short: Scores above average for a key defender (87 post-bye, 85 in 2023) and might see more with Battle leaving, but I can't have key defenders in my team

Name: Conor Nash
Short: The Irishman has been top three for CBAs two years in a row, so no doubt is rated internally and plays an important defensive role, but I doubt he's going to ever be a Fantasy scorer

Name: Ivan Soldo
Comment: Soldo has played backup to Nank for his entire career, playing just four full games without Nank and put up scores of 107, 103, 85 and 72. So I had high expectations when he moved to Port who were looking for their next ruck. It didn't start off great when he missed a big chunk of the pre-season due to a finger injury, but still got first crack at the number one mantle in Round 1. He averaged 83 through five rounds before a knee injury kept him out of the next five weeks. He then returned in Round 12 but was dropped after Round 14 to Jordan Sweet and never featured again. Sweet was great in the finals and it appears he has established himself as Port's number one ruck heading into 2025, so the outlook doesn't look great for Soldo.
Short: Two games after Round 7 and looks like Sweet is Port's preferred ruck, but he's no slouch if he ever gets his chance

Name: Josh Battle
Short: Key position player with above average scoring ability for his role, but not enough to make him a relevant Fantasy player

Name: Lachie Weller
Short: Recovering from his second knee recon and while he's scored okay as a defender in the past (multiple 80+ seasons), there are a few back there for the Suns these days so he might not get it all his way

Name: Jack Ginnivan
Short: Great first season at the Hawks, 122 was an outlier (31 touches, five tackles and two goals…) but he's a pure small forward so it's hard to see him improving much on that

Name: Shai Bolton
Comment: Bolton is a genuine star of the comp IRL. However, he's yet to match those Fantasy figures given the high impact nature of his game. He looked to be a midfielder when he attended 82% CBAs post-bye 2020 for an 88 average. Since then, he's spent more time forward and with great impact, averaging an incredible 3.5 shots on goal in the last three seasons. He's done this while the Tigers have struggled which makes it even more impressive, and a move to Freo could provide upside based on opportunity alone. However, Freo have been crying out for a dangerous small forward and have plenty of midfielders on their books so I can't see him getting the 53% CBAs he saw last year, and while there might be some upside there, I can't see him getting back to the 87 he was at in 2023. UPDATE: A calf niggle in the pre-season will see him miss some training.
Short: Star IRL, can score in Fantasy when he gets mid time but now at Freo who are crying for a forward and have plenty of mids, so hard to see that happening

Name: Hunter Clark
Comment: The former top 10 pick averaged 84 in the second half of his 2nd season and was heavily involved in centre bounces. He hasn't come on from there, failing to average above 80. He’s also had a shocking run of injuries. He got his chance in the middle last year, attending 47% of the centre bounces in his 11 matches, however the scoring didn't follow suit. I hope he gets a proper crack at it but for the time being it's hard to have any confidence in his body, role, position in the team and scoring.
Short: Has ability but battled with injuries his whole career and now lost the defender status that always kept him relevant

Name: Toby Greene
Comment: Greene had a down season, averaging just 72 after being above 80 in four of his past five years. He has the potential to be a top six forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. I would love to see him return to that role as the Giants midfield isn't as strong as it was and it might free him up a bit, as we saw with Heeney last year. However, he's remains one of the more dangerous forwards in the comp and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 80-mark in that forward role, but unless we see an unlikely role change, there not enough upside to consider in Classic.
Short: Been a prolific midfielder in the past but now a 90% forward, coming off a down year and while I'd love to see him spend more time inside like we saw Heeney do last year, I doubt that will happen

Name: Steele Sidebottom
Short: Now a 34-year-old wingman who did average 83 post bye on the back of a half back role and some time inside tagging, but it's hard to see any upside from the past Fantasy gun

Name: Jeremy Sharp
Short: Elite runner who made the most of his second chance at Freo where he made the wing his own, hard to see much update though given the pure outside role

Name: Ned Moyle
Short: Been waiting in the wings as a backup ruck to Witts, had a few chances the last two years and looked good (plus a 115 VFL avg) but looks like Witts still has some time left

Name: Shaun Mannagh
Short: A VFL star who took a while to find his spot in the Geelong side, but when he did he was awesome, 83 post bye in a forward role and doesn't look like going anywhere, will need mid-time to improve enough to be considered in Fantasy this year though

Name: Oliver Dempsey
Short: 2024 Rising Star went from a small forward to a dynamic wing, hard to know what role he'll end up playing but he's a talent, tough to see scoring upside as a wing or even if he goes back forward though

Name: Adam Cerra
Comment: We began to see the best of the former pick five in 2023. The natural on-baller, who averaged 115 in NAB League, 10 more than ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team, scored over 130 three weeks in a row from Round 6 to Round 8. He went on to surpass 110 five more times in his next eight games, before injury struck and he missed four of the final six matches. Unfortunately, injuries have been a theme of his career. He played just 13 games last season, never playing more than five full games in a row due to recurring hamstring injuries. Cerra has now suffered five hamstring injuries in 12 months. He went overseas in the off-season to get to the bottom of the issues. If he's fully fit, he's no doubt a highly discounted option. However, even when fit in the past and putting up those 100+ scores, he was always had some low ones in there, such is the nature of playing as the 4th mid behind Cripps, Walsh and Hewett. He had 12 games under 90 in 2024 (from 13) and 11 in 2023. Picking a player at this price, you really need them to average in the mid-90s, so it's going to be hard if he keeps scoring below that mark. He was trialled off the half back line at the end of the season, but it's hard to know if that is a long-term thing or a way Carlton were trying to look after his body. I've always been a Cerra man and seeing him priced at 73 might be too much for me to pass up, but there are obvious risks that come with it. Looking forward to seeing his role in the pre-season. 28 FEB UPDATE: He's looking good.
Short: 5 hamstrings in the past 12 months has stagnated his career when looking like emerging early 2023, comes with obvious risk but if he ticks boxes in the pre-season he could be worth it

Name: Connor Idun
Short: One of the best restrictive small defenders in the comp, but not in a scoring friendly role

Name: Dion Prestia
Comment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his Fantasy potential, failing to play 10 games in 2020 and 2021, playing less than 50% gametime three times in 2022 and just 13 games in 2024. The injuries might have caught up with him and he's not the player who averaged 100 in 2019. He's very cheap but he'll need a 90+ average to make him a great pick, and I can't see that happening based on his low output and lack of games he's played.
Short: Once a premium but soft tissue injuries have caught up with him

Name: Callan Ward
Short: The evergreen 34-year-old still gets it done, but finally moved from the CBA rotation (1% post-bye, 52% pre) and with mid-only status, he's not one for Fantasy

Name: Jack Macrae
Comment: Macrae was the most prolific Fantasy scorer from 2018 to 2021. However, you wouldn't think that after watching him the last three seasons. Even in his good seasons, when he didn't get the inside role, he looked a shadow of himself. Unfortunately, it has been this way for the last 36 months - from 78% CBAs in 2021 to 64% in 2022, 36% in 2023 and bottoming out at 12% last season (0% post-bye). From the outside, it appears that the Dogs wanted more pace in there and didn't want to sacrifice Bont or Libba, and preferred to pair them with Richards and Treloar. He moved to the Saints in the off-season, who ironically also have a slow midfield, however they don't have the depth of the Dogs and it appears Macrae will step straight into an inside mid role. The question is does he still have it in him? At times last year I think the game had passed him but I do have to remind myself he looked similar in his glory days when pushed out of the middle. He also managed a 129 last year in a game he had 34% CBAs and averaged 146 in his VFL games last year. So he might not be at his peak, but he looks a very safe selection at this price and as a forward. 22 FEB UPDATE: I've now got him as a tier 1 forward, expecting big things.
Short: The hype player of 2025 and for good reason, arrives at the Saints and set to play midfield where he's been a stud in the past and as long as get gets those midfield minutes, even the lower estimates would put him as a top three forward

Name: Tom Atkins
Short: Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in Fantasy

Name: Cameron Guthrie
Comment: Guthrie was a low-key gun Fantasy scorer in 2020 and 2021, averaging 105 across that time. He hasn't reached those heights since and battled with injury the last two seasons. He's now 32, playing for a team who notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30. I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there, despite his discounted price.
Short: Former gun who has been injured the past two seasons and now 32 playing for a team who likes to rest players, it would be hard to do despite the discount

Name: Jamie Cripps
Short: Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for Fantasy scoring

Name: Brayden Maynard
Short: Always been on my radar for more midfield time one day, but doesn't look like that will happen and scoring has been capped in the 70s as a defender

Name: Adam Saad
Short: Far more damaging in real life than in Fantasy and career best of 83 is a long way off top 6

Name: Kyle Langford
Short: A pure forward now after teasing as a midfielder in 2021 and 2022, can't see him moving so unlikely to be Fantasy relevant again

Name: Tanner Bruhn
Comment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, so after settling with a forward role at the Giants, it was expected he would get his chance at the Cats who, despite being the reigning premiers, were pretty light on in the middle. Since arriving he's played as a full-time mid (49% and 57% CBAs) but his TOG has been very low (63% and 61%), meaning his scoring hasn't taken the leap expected. His points-per-minute and scoring at VFL level suggest he can score, but he would need a jump to 80% TOG to boost his average to the 90s, which I very much doubt we see. Will always be on the radar due to his draft position and VFL numbers, but I'm going to need to see a large body of work first.
Short: Two years of decent CBAs but TOG has remained capped resulting underwhelming scoring, surely it gets a boost this year but with a few coming in it's not certain

Name: Marcus Windhager
Comment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. After an impressive debut season, Windhager was made to work for opportunities in his second season. A broken hand in the pre-season match saw him miss Round 1 and then start as the sub in Round 2. He was sub in three of his first six matches before being dropped to the VFL. It's here that he showed his scoring power, scoring 98, 157, 91 and 120 in his four matches. This shouldn’t come as a great surprise considering he scored over 110 twice in three games at the level in 2022. He was back in the senior side in Round 13 and didn't miss a game after that. He moved to half-back in Round 17 and played there for the final nine games of the season, averaging 79. He was back in the midfield last year with 59% CBAs but his scoring didn't pop as expected. He had a few excuses, breaking his hand early in the pre-season game and wore a glove for the first few weeks and then hurting his hamstring and didn't play after Round 17. In his absence Phillipou looked great in the middle and the off-season recruitment of Macrae might push Windhager to the outer again in 2025. Still a watch on him due to his VFL numbers and tackle ability, but as a mid-only at that price it's a hard sell.
Short: Has had Fantasy hype his whole career and got the midfield time we all wanted last year (59%) and scoring didn't pop and might find it harder this year with Macrae and Pou

Name: James Trezise
Short: Defender picked up in the mid-season draft, averaged 76 in the VFL and won the VFL B&F, hasn't looked a scorer at the top level

Name: Archie Roberts
Short: Played the last four games and looked good, averaging 85 and showed he might be one for the future, but his 77 VFL average suggests the 85 might have been an over-performance

Name: Logan Evans
Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: looked great in pre-season game but it was v Saints and Port have plenty there.
Short: A revelation after being picked up in the mid-season draft and looks a player, 40% KI in finals when Houston was out might be a sign of things to come but hard to see him bettering his 70 in 2024 by much

Name: Mitch McGovern
Short: A few seasons on the park now and despite surprisingly taking a lot of the kick-ins, his scoring appears capped at 70 - hammy in the pre-season

Name: Zac Bailey
Short: Better in real life than Fantasy, especially if he remains in this forward/mid role and based on his CBA trend, the mid role isn't coming

Name: Connor Budarick
Short: Hardwick teased us this time last year when declaring him his 'Jayden Short of the Gold Coast', but he went on to play eight games and with Rioli and Noble arriving he's going to find it hard

Name: Sam Switkowski
Short: Small forward who has been used in spurts in the middle, but scoring is still capped at sub-70

Name: Lawson Humphries
Short: As impressive as any debutant in 2024, playing the final 11 matches and looking well beyond his years (17 touches at 84%), Cat defenders always score above average and no reason why he won't average over 70 again

Name: Patrick Lipinski
Comment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski when he arrived at the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the pre-season game and then scored 117 from 48% CBAs in Round 1. However, he didn't go on with it has been completely pushed out of the midfield since, attending just 4% in the last two seasons for an average of 68. The way the Pies look like structuring up, I doubt Lipinski will get back in the middle in 2025.
Short: No longer getting the CBAs which made him relevant in 2022

Name: Josh Worrell
Short: Key defender who is yet to become a regular

Name: Mark Blicavs
Short: Such a unique player who can play anywhere, settled as an inside mid who takes some ruck contests but upside isn't there unless he’s unleashed as a full-time ruck, which I doubt will happen

Name: Lachlan Bramble
Short: Played 24 in his first season at the Dogs and provides some nice run, but well behind the others for distribution

Name: Darcy Tucker
Short: Played most of the games since arriving at North but scoring limited on a wing/HB role, might find it harder for games in 2025 with the new additions

Name: Tom Papley
Short: One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for Fantasy, despite the fact he takes CBAs of those that are relevant

Name: Marc Pittonet
Short: TDK overtook him last year as their number one ruck and I can see that trend continuing

Name: Brennan Cox
Short: Turned into a pretty good intercept defender IRL and shown a ceiling with Freo's high mark game in defence (2 scores over 120 in 2023), but a season average of 70 isn't enough to consider

Name: Jack Scrimshaw
Comment: Scrim has a Fantasy game that I thought would see him be a top six defender before his career is done. However, he's now 26 and yet to average over 80. His teammates have scored well in a similar role, and I think have moved past him, so I'm now less bullish.
Short: I was a fan of the former top 10 pick but he just hasn't delivered and now just looks like a regular defender

Name: Taylor Adams
Comment: The man who has averaged 113+ twice in his career at the Pies significantly dropped in role and output, which saw him move to Swans at the end of 2023 for more opportunities. The Swans certainly aren't short on midfielders, and unfortunately the move didn't go as planned. He missed the first month of the season due to injury, which has also been a recurring theme over his career. On return, he saw some CBAs, but never hit 50% for the year and finished at 29% for a season average of 68. He was subbed out and started sub in the back half and eventually missed out on selection completely during the finals. It's hard to have any confidence in Adams' body, role or even spot in the team heading into 2025, however a new coach may give him more chances inside than the previous one, especially with Luke Parker (33% CBAs) leaving, but I'm not holding much hope for the now 31-year-old.
Short: A move to the Swans for more midfield time didn't eventuate, finding himself out of the team and reducing his CBAs and average, new coach might change things up but signs aren't good for the former stud

Name: Cam Rayner
Short: No doubt more of an impact player than an accumulator, got the CBA bump in 2024 but didn't lead to a scoring boost which may never come

Name: Nick Haynes
Comment: 28 FEB UPDATE: McGovern hammy is only going to help his cause, I've bumped him up but I don't think I could do it, despite that 2024 VFL average staring at me.
Short: At his best, the interceptor could score in the 80s, but hasn't been that way for a while now and I doubt a move to Carlton will change that, although Newman out and a 119(!) VFL average last season gives a bit of hope

Name: Sam Draper
Short: Rucks take time, but Draper is yet to average 70 in eight seasons, averaged 86 in four games as solo but Scott likes to play the two rucks, so scoring will remain limited unless named solo

Name: Harley Reid
Comment: He was the most hyped player to ever enter the league, but Fantasy coaches had their expectations in check given he was clearly in the boat of a high-impact player which doesn't normally translate to Fantasy. He averaged 51 in the first three weeks but then clicked into gear, averaging 80 in his next 3, including a 27 touches and a goal effort against Richmond. He was arguably best on ground in two of those games and showed that he might be a scorer after all (not many players get 27 touches as a mid in their 5th game). However, West Coast oddly rested him the next week and it halted his momentum. He averaged 62 in the next four but then got going against the Saints, having 13 touches in the second quarter (49 points) to be on 65 at half time. He was heavily tagged after half time and took his frustrations out on a tackle which saw him suspended. Post bye there were less highlights, but he did manage a career high 99 points in Round 23 on the back of 26 touches and three behinds (imagine if he kicked straight). He's had a very interrupted pre-season and missed all work pre-Christmas, so he'll likely have a slow start. I doubt he'll be a relevant player in Fantasy this year, but I no longer think he'll just be an impact player. He's going to be a premium Fantasy player in time given how good he is.
Short: 67 average isn't eye-catching, but Reid was every bit as good as advertised, interrupted pre-season may keep him limited in 2025 but natural progression should see him continue to improve

Name: Brodie Kemp
Short: Now a regular in the Blues back-line but scoring appears pretty limited

Name: Ryan Byrnes
Short: His 101 VFL average in 2022 hasn't translated to the AFL as he's spent most of his time as sub or on the wing

Name: Cameron Zurhaar
Short: We've been waiting for the strong forward to make a 'Petracca' midfield move, but a CBA drop in 2024 means the Roos now just see him as a forward

Name: Will Hayward
Short: Talented forward but hovers around the 60-mark every season

Name: Billy Dowling
Short: The highest Fantasy averaging player in his draft year got his chance in 2024 but limited to a forward role, a natural scorer but of all the names floated for mid time at the Crows he's not one of them

Name: Kysaiah Pickett
Short: Very good footballer but scoring limited as a small forward, but he's an impact player - even with the boost in CBAs his average remained sub-70 - suspended to start the season

Name: Jake Stringer
Short: Disappointing last three seasons after a career best 2021 - move to GWS might open up some opportunities but form, fitness and role too hard to predict - fitness looks good, now to see role in Round 0

Name: Sam Clohesy
Short: Won the most promising young talent in the VFL in 2023 as a rebounding half-back and got his chance on a wing in 2024, scoring reflected the less favourable role

Name: James Harmes
Short: Moved to the Dogs for more opportunities but they never came, they lost a few on the off-season but I doubt Harmes is in their midfield plans

Name: Ryan Burton
Short: Hasn't come on after averaging 84 in year 2, might get more of a chance with Houston leaving but I haven't seen enough

Name: Heath Chapman
Short: Former pick 14 is locked into Freo's back six playing important roles on talls and smalls, I can see him one day moving into the midfield but in the short term will likely continue in the defensive role

Name: Rhys Stanley
Short: The Cats' ruck is always a lottery, but I think they will now move past the now 34-year-old Stanley

Name: Darcy Wilson
Short: One of the more impressive draftees, playing every game and on the wing and HF, junior numbers and running ability suggest he's got another level to go but if he remains on a wing it's going to be hard to improve his scoring much

Name: Rory Lobb
Short: Was actually very impressive as an intercept defender to finish the year, role should stick so his 70 post-bye average is realistic

Name: Max Michalanney
Short: Backed up his impressive debut season taking more of a distributor role and even saw some CBAs (67% in Round 14) so it might be a sign of things to come, but it will likely be a few years before we see him take the Fantasy leap regardless of role

Name: James Aish
