Short: Versatile role player who found himself on the outer at the end of the season, named sub multiple times and Freo might have moved past him

Name: Ben Ainsworth
Short: Former pick four averaged 70+ four seasons in a row before last, the medium forward role is a tough one for scoring, despite his nice marking game

Name: Jack Ross
Comment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (93 in 2024, 113 in 2023, 116 in 2021) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, he finally got a crack as an inside midfielder last season, attending 32% CBAs, and his scoring was underwhelming. You'd think he gets another chance in 2025 with all the exits but I'm not holding hope.
Short: Some high scores at VFL level, got some opportunity inside last season (32% CBAs) but scoring was underwhelming

Name: Ryan Lester
Short: Always been a very good defender, so it was nice to see him get some recognition last season, however he's never been a Fantasy relevant one

Name: Archie Perkins
Comment: The number nine pick of the 2020 draft has played an 79 games in his first four seasons and showed some x-factor early in his career around goal and in the air. He's even seen some inside time, 46% CBAs pre-bye last season, however his scoring and general output has been underwhelming. He just doesn't look like a big ball winner and going off the post-bye role, the Dons look like they've moved past him in the middle for the likes of Caldwell and Durham. He might breakout one day, but I doubt it's in 2025.
Short: Former pick nine been underwhelming to date, averaged 79 pre-bye on 46% CBAs before falling out of the CBA rotation completely to finish the year, no forward status makes it a hard sell

Name: Tom Sparrow
Comment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 65 from 38% CBAs in 2024, 67 from 46% CBAs in 2023 and 63 from 32% CBAs in 2022. He's obviously highly rated given the opportunity he's getting, however I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 75 with the big boys back in 2025.
Short: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game

Name: Jacob Weitering
Short: Genuine key defender

Name: Hayden McLean
Short: Key forward/ruck who doesn't see enough ruck time to be relevant

Name: Blake Hardwick
Short: Swingman who spends time locking down in defence or providing a target up forward, neither role is attractive for Fantasy

Name: Jack Graham
Comment: Given Graham's elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on, especially after averaging 84 from 40% CBAs in the last five of 2021. However, he's gone backwards ever since, even when he got CBAs last year (career high 37%) it only led to a 65 average. He now finds himself at West Coast and I'm yet to hear what role he's set for, but based on his last two years I'm not getting too excited. UPDATE: On the back of the Yeo injury, it's looking very likely that Graham will get a prominent midfield role for West Coast to start the season. He's never seen more than 37%, so if he can hit 60%+ then we could see a career best season from him, or at least until Yeo is back which is all you'd need at that price. I'm still a bit gun shy though and would need to see some scoring power in the pre-season games before pulling the trigger. 1 MAR UPDATE: role was there but scoring power wasn't. Hard to start I think but role a big tick.
Short: Hasn't come on after averaging 84 in L5 of 2021, new club gives some hope especially now with Yeo out for a bit, but based off last years scoring even when given midfield time, I'll need to see it first

Name: Jeremy Howe
Short: Ignore the discount to career high (which was four games in the 16-min quarters), he plays a more defensive role nowadays

Name: Luke Nankervis
Short: Managed 20 games last season playing in defence, scored 111 in a game but other than that his scoring was limited

Name: Peter Wright
Short: Key forward who was on the outer last season

Name: Josh Rachele
Comment: The former pick six had a disappointing 2024 after emerging as a future star in his second season. He averaged 47% CBAs for the first six rounds of his second season and averaged 92 points in that time. Surprisingly, he averaged just 12% CBAs for the rest of the season (64 Fantasy points) and that dropped to 7% in 2024 (1% post-bye). Crows have a number of players being talked about for midfield roles in 2025 and Rachele hasn't been one of them, so he's likely to maintain his small forward role which isn't conducive for Fantasy scoring. The question is whether he will ever get into the midfield or if the Crows just see him as a forward. I thought he showed a nice point of difference when he was in there in 2023, so he's always going to be someone I keep my eye on. Unfortunately I don't think he'll get the chance to shine this year.
Short: Very disappointing 2024 and completely lost any midfield role after averaging 92 from 47% CBAs in the first six rounds of 2023, looks like Crows just see him as a forward now

Name: Tyson Stengle
Short: Small forward who averaged 71 in his AA year and dropped a bit since then

Name: Jamie Elliott
Short: Very good small forward IRL, dealt with some injuries last season but never been a Fantasy option

Name: Mac Andrew
Short: Arrived last season to show he's going to be an absolute star IRL with incredible intercept ability, unlikely to be much of a Fantasy asset though

Name: Brodie Smith
Short: Has been on the decline the last few years and might struggle for games this season

Name: Bailey J. Williams
Short: Been the main ruck the last two seasons but only averaged 70 in that time, I think Flynn takes the role off him this year

Name: Tom Cole
Short: A reliable defender but scoring is capped at 70

Name: Mattaes Phillipou
Comment: The 2022 draft is looking like a special one and the player taken at pick 10 could end up as good as any. Phillipou has all the attributes of a modern-day player - a big body, high leap, booming kick and a goal kicker. And in his final four games of 2024, when thrown into a greater midfield role, he showed an accumulation game which we knew he had given he averaged 123 in his draft year. He finished with scores of 117, 93, 96 and 119 and missed games in between, which would've halted some momentum. The Saints are screaming for a dynamic, big-bodied mid and the Pou is the guy. I'd be very surprised if he doesn't have a full-time midfield role in 2025 and on what we've seen, he could push the top six forwards from a very cheap price. UPDATE: He'll sadly miss the first half of the season with a stress fracture in his leg.
Short: Averaged 106 from his four games when thrown into the middle, a massive scorer in juniors and that full-time mid role should come this year - sadly he'll miss the first half of the year with a stress fracture

Name: Toby Conway
Short: Young ruck developing nicely in the VFL (averaged 100, up from 75), looked good in his five AFL games and should become the Cats' number one ruck this season, but who knows with the Cats - out indefinitely with a back issue - SDK stocks up

Name: Ryley Sanders
Comment: We were as excited about Sanders as much as any other draftee last season on the back of his 108 in juniors (138 in champs) and then dominating the pre-season matches as a midfielder. However, it didn't eventuate. He was controversially subbed on in his debut on 68 (55% TOG), still more than 11 of his teammates who played a full game. He then averaged 82 in his next three games (40% CBAs) and looked like he was away. Not on Bevo's watch. He was subbed out the following week (39 from 42% TOG) and then started sub the following week (scored 22 from 24%), before being dropped to the VFL. He was a level above in the VFL, averaging 116 in seven games. He went on to play eight more games for the season at AFL level, but only averaged 65, spending a lot of time forward which helped him get forward status this year. Who knows what Bevo will do with him this year. The Dogs do have plenty of mids (Bont, Libba, Treloar and Richards the likely main 4), but I can see Sanders being the 5th in line and if anything happens to one of the four, Sanders will be ready to make the most of his opportunity. UPDATE: Something has happened to one of the four (Treloar out for the first two months) and Sanders appears to be the man to step up. Genuine starting option now and a nice replacement for Phillipou, if you're hesitant he's always one you can get after you see his Round 1 role like we did with Oliver, Taranto and Worpel in their second seasons, but I think I'd have the confidence to start. 14 FEB UPDATE: They were missing Bont and Libba, but pure CBA role in first practice match. All good signs so far. 28 FEB UPDATE: Bont out to start only helps his CBA chances, I'm in.
Short: Pick six of 2023 looks a future stud (108 in draft year, 116 in VFL last year and 92 in pre-season) but never got a proper go at it in his debut season, who knows with Bevo but if he gets a mid role could prove a great pick

Name: Jayden Laverde
Short: Key defender with limited scoring

Name: Jack Billings
Comment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 99 points per game, including 106 in the last half. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 61 in 2023 from just three matches. He moved to the Dees for a change of fortune, and things looked good with 140 in his second game. However, he never matched that effort and saw himself relegated to sub multiple times and out of the team.
Short: Reduced his average every year since 2019 where he was a top six forward, a change of clubs didn't help

Name: Mitch Georgiades
Short: Great to see him back playing good footy but as a key forward, he's not a Fantasy option, even with a lot falling on him with no Dixon or Marshall in 2025

Name: Harris Andrews
Short: A gun full-back of the comp but not a relevant pick in this game, unless your draft settings value spoils

Name: Paddy Dow
Comment: The former number three pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver constantly at AFL level. His numbers at VFL level have been good, 97 in 2022 and 111 in 2023. It was always hard getting regular games in the midfield at the Blues given their depth, so a move to the Saints seemed a positive one. However, a knee injury in the pre-season delayed his start and he went on to play the 10 matches with decent midfield exposure - 65% CBAs. However, the scoring wasn't there. Starting to lose hope.
Short: We've been waiting for a breakout and the move to the Saints didn't result in one, despite career high CBA numbers - will miss start of season with injury

Name: Tom McDonald
Short: Back in defence, scores best as a forward but that was a long time ago

Name: Mark Keane
Short: A career average 50 is about expected for the Irishman in his defensive role

Name: Riley Garcia
Short: Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level despite having more chances last year, highly rated but hard to see where he fits

Name: Tim Membrey
Short: Scored higher than the average forward in the past but doubt he gets back there even with another chance at the Pies

Name: Jake Bowey
Short: Showed flashes of scoring potential, particularly in his second season when he scored 125 in Round 2, but just hasn't done it regularly enough

Name: Jamarra Ugle-Hagan
Short: Been teasing for a few years now and certainly showed signs of why he was taken pick one in 2020, reckon he could rip the comp apart this season, but breakouts for key position forwards aren't enough in this game - will miss the start of the year with personal issues

Name: Oliver Hollands
Short: Hard running former pick 11 has made the wing his own since arriving at the Blues and a shift to half back to finish the year (86 L5) gives some hope of a up-tick in 2025, especially with Newman now out - pre-season watch

Name: Jayden Hunt
Short: Had a career year in 2023 as a mature body in a young struggling team but pushed up the ground a bit since then and scoring not as good

Name: Lachie Schultz
Short: Gun pressure forward pushed his average to 79 in his last season at Freo, looked a long way off that last year

Name: Riley Thilthorpe
Comment: Thilthorpe has been a slow burn since being taken with pick two of the 2020 draft. It was always going to be the case being a tall forward, but he's slowing increased his ruck time while giving ROB a chop out. He's looking very big and strong this pre-season and ready to explode. I wouldn't rule him out of having more chances in the ruck and potentially taking over as the number one option come season end. This would be a big call as while no star, ROB has been serviceable. But if it occurs, we might see a nice 20+ point bump to his scoring. I doubt it will be enough to make him a worthwhile selection, but let's see how he goes in the pre-season matches.
Short: Been a slow burn but he's looking big and strong, could see him even progressing to the number one ruck this season, which would bring about a nice boost in scoring

Name: Aliir Aliir
Short: Gun intercept defender better in real life than Fantasy

Name: Bailey Banfield
Short: Big ball winner in the WAFL and as a junior but often in the defensive forward role at AFL level which just isn't a scoring option

Name: Jaeger O'Meara
Short: Yet to average over 100 in his 13 seasons, out of the CBA completely last season and pushed to a wing which didn't suit and I don't see a way he gets back in

Name: Matthew Johnson
Short: Has impressed in his first two seasons playing at the level, but hard with Serong, Brayshaw and Young being a tight rotation which will likely stop him from a breakout, but Fyfe stepping back should help

Name: Taylor Walker
Short: Evergreen forward scores above average for a key forward and for a 34-year-old, but not the ideal combo in this game and age is starting to catch up with him

Name: James Peatling
Comment: Peatling has generated a lot of buzz this pre-season and for good reason. The 2020 mid-season draftee has always been a ball winner at VFL level, where he's averaged over 90 four years straight including 120 last season. He also saw regular games at AFL level, with a career high 19 in 2024. Six of those was as sub early in the year, however he began getting midfield opportunities when their mids were out and then became a midfield regular by the end of the year, attending 63% CBAs in the L5 games. His 62 average doesn't tell the full story. Removing the six games he was sub, his averages boosts to 83. Then if you just include the games he attended 60% or more CBAs (i.e. a full time mid role), he averaged 99. He moved to the Crows in the off-season but not without demand from other teams, so you'd think the Crows gave him a strong sell of a midfield role. There are a lot of names being thrown around for their midfield mix in 2024, but with Laird moving out I feel like Peatling will become their defensive midfielder given his elite tackling ability and an average of 60%+ CBAs is on the cards. All you need at his starting price is a high 80s average, which he's proven he can do at both levels. I'm liking him as a mid-priced pick. 27 FEB UPDATE: With Rankine having more CBAs than expected (and looking great) and Crouch still well and truly in the mix, Peatling saw 42% CBAs which is much lower than hoped. I'm still keen though and I dare say many will jump off as a result.
Short: 4 straight seasons of 90+ at VFL level (120 last year), averaged 83 in non sub-games in 2024 (99 in six games over 60% CBAs), now at the Crows who have a few mids but feel like he will get even more opportunity

Name: Nathan Broad
Short: Genuine role player in defence who has capped out in the 60s

Name: Bodhi Uwland
Short: Quickly became a favourite of Hardwick's, playing 21 with some great defensive roles, scored 124 in a game which shows he can score but for now he's limited to a lockdown

Name: Eric Hipwood
Short: A key position player who averaged 71 post-bye 2024 thanks to a 140 in the mix, but certainly doesn't do it enough to be relevant

Name: Jack Lukosius
Comment: Lukosius returned to the forward-line in 2022 after looking great as a running defender the year prior to average 86. His Fantasy output felt it, averaging 64, 72 and 61 since. He now finds himself at the Power and if they keep him as a forward, then you can rule him out of Fantasy calculations. If he moves back to defence, where he showed shades of a young Lachie Whitfield, then he could come into calculations. 142 in his one VFL game last season shows he has it, so just got a quiet watch on him. Marshall getting injured in the pre-season probably adds to the likelihood that he plays forward though.
Short: Averaged 86 in 2021 when used as a distributor down back but settled as a forward in his last two seasons at the Suns, interesting to see what the Power will do with him

Name: Cody Weightman
Short: A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the Fantasy scorers though

Name: Corey Wagner
Short: Mature age draftee found a home at half back in his second season, playing the last 10 games at an average of 67, a bit of upside there if he keeps the dashing role but still behind Ryan and Clark for distribution

Name: Kade Chandler
Short: Has become a regular for the Dees, but small forward role isn't conducive to scoring

Name: Joel Freijah
Comment: 27 FEB UPDATE: Could not have been more impressive in the pre-season, albeit no Dale there. Such an awkward price and one I'd rather trade in to after a few weeks, but bumped him up again for draft.
Short: 13 games in his debut season as a wing/half back, moved well and could have a future, but scoring will be capped in the outside role, might get a slight boost with JJ missing to start the year - HB role looks locked and great in first game without Dale though

Name: James Jordon
Comment: 28 FEB UPDATE: Made the most of his extra midfield responibilities with all the injuries in the pre-season, I'm not overreacting but he's worth watching in Round 0 given scoring at VFL level (120 in 2023). Maybe we were a year too early!
Short: Moved to the Swans and landed in a pure defensive tagging role, so he didn't hit the scoring heights he did in VFL or when given CBAs at the Dees

Name: Taylor Duryea
Short: Back playing most weeks after being in and out of the side in 2022, but playing in a far more defensive role than he did when he averaged 86

Name: Zac Williams
Comment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and Fantasy coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 106 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After a string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He then did his ACL in the 2023 pre-season and missed the entire year. He entered 2024 as a bargain pick, however he again disappointed, averaging 63 in the first nine weeks and found himself injured at times also. He then moved to a small forward role in Round 10 and remained there for the rest of the season, averaging 59 in the role (65 excluding his injured game). He's expected to keep the forward role, so we finally have a pre-season where I won't be talking him up.
Short: Injury prone speedster has always been on the Fantasy radar after averaging 106 in the second half of 2019, but moved to a small forward role to finish 2024 and averaged 59 in that role

Name: Jack Higgins
Short: The junior stud with Rockliff-like NAB League numbers has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level (0% CBAs in last three seasons) and hard to see that changing

Name: Noah Balta
Short: Can play forward, back, and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least scoring-friendly role, defence, out for the first month with suspension

Name: Nick Bryan
Comment: A back up ruck to Draper who has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and averaged over 107 the last two VFL seasons, showing his potential. Draper has been the clear choice for number one ruck at Essendon, but some feel he's had his chance and Bryan playing the last four games of 2024 might be a sign of things to come. He's not an option for Classic but worth bumping up in Draft and hope he gets picked. 25 FEB UPDATE: 97 from 58% TOG in the pre-season game, Scott looks fixed on playing the two rucks but if he ever gets his chance solo, he's a genuine option in the ruck.
Short: Been third in line behind Draper and Goldy but VFL numbers are impressive (116 in 2023, 107 2024), so he hopefully gets his chance

Name: Matt Flynn
Comment: Flynn played 33 games in eight seasons at the Giants and never played more than 12 in a season. He's always competed for the ruck role, so moved to West Coast in 2024 in the hope to be their number 1. It didn't work out as he would've hoped, with a hamstring tendon in the pre-season and then an ankle injury meaning he only played the four games in 2024. He's now fit and ready for a proper crack at it. We've had a decent look at him in the number one ruck role when he's had the opportunity at the Giants and he's averaged around the 70 mark and 90s at VFL level. I think he'll get the number one gig, however I doubt he will score enough to be a worthwhile selection in the ruck in Fantasy.
Short: A move to West Coast last season to have a proper run at number one ruck didn't work out with managing just the four games, he's fit now and might surprise a few

Name: Charlie Comben
Short: Was great in a key defender / intercept role last season and great to see him play regular games, role not conducive to scoring though

Name: Jack Buckley
Short: One of the best key backs in the comp, but far better in real life than in Fantasy

Name: Jaspa Fletcher
Short: Impressed in his first two seasons on a wing and now a regular at the Lions, some big wraps on him but going to be a slow burn unless he moves inside

Name: Luke McDonald
Short: Former top 10 pick who in the back end of 2020 looked like bursting out (seven week stretch averaging 121 with three 150s), but been a role player ever since and bottomed out in 2024 with a 60 average

Name: Jackson Mead
Short: Good scorer at SANFL level but stuck as a small forward in the AFL, despite seeing some CBAs in 2024 it didn't result in much of a scoring boost

Name: Conor McKenna
Short: Been a decent running defender in the past, but with Zorko taking over, Wilmot coming through and Coleman returning, he's certainly going to take a backward seat

Name: Aaron Naughton
Short: Gun key forward but scoring will always be limited, even with JUH out for a bit

Name: Alex Davies
Short: Fell out of favour but hasn't shown much scoring even with CBAs

Name: Reuben Ginbey
Comment: Ginbey was one of the few shining lights for West Coast in 2023. He was thrown in the deep end playing inside mid for a team who struggled most weeks, but it was a clear sign they have big wraps on the kid. He showed a great tackle ability (5.9 per game, in line with the top eight mids) and contested possession rate (46.4%, above that of the top eight mids), however struggled to win the ball outside the contest (13.7 disposals and 1.5 marks per game). However, he didn't come on as we all hoped in his second season and eventually moved to the backline to finish the season. While his scoring was limited (52 in the L5 when 0% CBAs), he did look a lot better. He will likely maintain that role for this season and I can see him improving a bit with confidence and natural progression, but as a mid-only he's certainly not one I'm considering starting.
Short: Big bodied mid who didn't come on in his second season as we all hoped, moved to half back to finish the year and while scoring was still limited (52 in L5 when 0% CBAs), he certainly looked better

Name: Todd Goldstein
Short: Played more games than I thought he would at 35, but now it's Draper and/or Bryan time, so I doubt we see much of Goldy on-field

Name: Jake Riccardi
Short: A fringe KPP who has put up some big numbers in the VFL playing in defence, but largely used as a forward at AFL level and scoring is limited - suspended to start the season

Name: Nat Fyfe
Short: Six years of injury impacted seasons, so it was good to see him play 22 last season, showed signs of getting back (37 touches and 118 in R7) but by the end the game looked past him, pre-season knee surgery will put him back further

Name: Chayce Jones
Short: Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and the wing at AFL and scoring hasn’t been there consistently

Name: Kai Lohmann
Short: Became one of the best young small forwards in the comp in 2024, but in the role he's not going to be a scorer

Name: Rhylee West
Short: Found a spot as a defensive small forward, but I doubt we'll see him in a midfield role which is where he'd need to be to score

Name: Mabior Chol
Short: Surprised plenty in his first season at the Hawks but as a key forward, his scoring is limited

Name: Callum Ah Chee
Short: Former pick eight had a career best year in 2024 and got going when it mattered most in the finals, but even his scoring there wasn't enough to gain interest in Fantasy

Name: Will Phillips
Comment: Was said to be the premier midfielder and the most ready to play from the 2020 draft pool. Phillips for Oakleigh averaged better numbers at the same age during the finals than Matt Rowell and Noah Anderson. However, he didn't look it in his first season, averaging 44 in his 14 games. He then missed the entire 2022 season due to glandular fever, but completed a full pre-season in 2023. He got enough opportunity, 16 games at 62% CBAs, however, didn't take the jump I was hoping he would. He only played the 11 games in 2024 and was limited to a tagger. The Roos' midfield developing nicely, I wouldn't be surprised to see Philips on the outer in 2025.
Short: Highly credentialed junior but just hasn't shown it at AFL level, found a role as a tagger during 2024 but the excess mids at the Roos may have overtaken him

Name: Jake Kolodjashnij
Short: Solid defender but best season average is just 59

Name: Rory Atkins
Short: He can certainly score with a very favourable +6 game (over 100 three times in 2023, 123 in VFL last year), a strange move to Port in off-season and I doubt he's the man but could take Houston's role

Name: Josh Weddle
Short: Impressive in his first two season and no doubt a player for the future, still don't know where he'll finish up (defender, forward or even inside mid) but while he's still developing I think he's going to be more impactful IRL than Fantasy

Name: Mitch Lewis
Short: Gun key forward coming back from a knee injury

Name: Judd McVee
Short: Debuted in 2023 and played every game since as a shutdown defender, very highly rated and interestingly moved into the midfield to finish the year as a taste and due to injuries, expect him to return to defence in 2024 though but worth a watch

Name: Caleb Windsor
Short: Hard running wing was very impressive in his debut season, showing a great running ability including a burst of speed, scoring limited in his role though, may transition inside one day but don't think it will be 2025

Name: Sam Berry
Comment: Sam Berry looked like he was the future of the Crows' midfield, playing prime midfield minutes in his second season over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. He led the comp in tackles per game, which was a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season. However, he has been in and out of the side since. The Crows looked to add some more speed and dynamic movement in the middle, with Soligo, Dawson and Rankine taking time away from Berry. That meant Berry spent a lot of time as sub (7 games sub 50% TOG in 2024) or playing SANFL. He did get another go to finish 2024, averaging 66% CBAs post-bye, the same amount he had in 2022. However, with Peatling arriving and talk of Rankine spending more time inside, I can see Berry being on the outer again.
Short: Always teased since averaging 84 in his second season, but been a victim of Crows needing to go quicker inside, got back in there to finish the year and averaged 73 post-bye, but new additions might make it tough

Name: Joel Jeffrey
Short: Medium forward who moved to defence in 2024, scored okay in the role (70 pre-bye) but dropped away to finish the season and doubt he keeps the role with Rioli and Noble arriving

Name: Logan McDonald
Short: Key forward in his 5th season so should keep improving, but from a very low base

Name: Jimmy Webster
Short: Role player in defence for the Saints but never taken his game to the next level in Fantasy

Name: Tom Barrass
Short: Key defender now at the Hawks, career best of 68 though

Name: Will Hoskin-Elliott
Short: Moved back forward in 2024 and scoring reflected that

Name: Brody Mihocek
Short: Not quite a key position player but scores like one

Name: Charlie Cameron
Short: Star small forward but scoring limited to the 60s

Name: Darcy Fogarty
Short: Become a decent forward after many wrote him off, but key forwards aren't what we're looking for

Name: Jordan Boyd
Short: Emerged in 2024 showcasing his elite kicking ability, scoring limited though

Name: Will Graham
Short: 17 games in his debut season and saw some heavy CBA minutes, obviously highly rated but find it hard to see him getting as much opportunity when all their first-choice mids are back

Name: Liam Ryan
Short: Small forward so scoring is limited

Name: Brady Hough
Short: A great season as a lock-down defender and has displayed a nice kick-mark game in the past, however his distribution duties didn’t receive an uptick with Hurn's departure and I think he'll be limited to lockdown role again

Name: Elijah Tsatas
Comment: Tsatas arrived at the Bombers with high hopes following over 33 disposals and seven marks a game throughout his NAB League campaign. A pre-season injury meant he wasn't available to start the season and then was forced to work hard for his spot, despite the Bombers' woes. He played seven VFL matches and had more than 30 touches in two of them. He came in for the final four games of the year and looked okay without being amazing, limited to a forward and wing role with little inside action (15% CBAs) His second season wasn't what he would've wanted either, playing just the seven games (four as sub) at AFL level and didn't attend a centre bounce, despite his stoppage game being a strength of his. In the VFL he averaged 102, up from 92 in 2023, and included a 148 to finish the year. The knock on him is his kicking, but in his third season, the Dons have to give him a crack. I'm watching with interest, however mid-only and priced at 58 (discounted on his 2023 average not 2024), means he's not a starting option. UPDATE: been dominating match-sim and turning heads at training, shaping to play in the Opening Round where luckily we won't have to make a blind call on him before Round 1. If he avoids the vest and sees 40%+ CBAs, then he's a genuine starting option. However, I've got Peatling and Doch over him for the better mid-pricers. Parish out only helps the situation. 14 FEB UPDATE: Full time mid role in practice match and delivered. Bumped him up again, but still a tricky price tag in this format. 25 FEB UPDATE: 31 touches in the pre-season match. Only 88 points due to his low marks and high handball numbers, but looks locked into an inside role with Parish out. Outperformed Peatling in the pre-season. I still rather Peatling but a 80+ score in Round 0 may make him the safer bet.
Short: Former pick 5, just 11 games in first two seasons, mostly as sub, but VFL (102) and junior (115) numbers suggests he's a scorer if ever given the opportunity, but kicking and midfield depth holding him back

Name: Bailey Smith
Comment: After nine rounds in 2022, Bailey Smith was the best player in Fantasy. He was playing an unprecedented time on ground while getting decent CBAs in a stacked Bulldog midfield and used his elite run to average 118. His season then derailed after being suspended for headbutting Zach Tuohy and then a club-imposed suspension saw him miss five of the next six weeks. He never hit the early season heights when he returned, averaging 93 post bye. His CBAs then dropped in 2023 to 31% (20% post-bye) as he spent a lot of time forward. His season high CBA game (75%), he scored 121 but never saw that number again. It was enough to give him forward status for 2024 before an ACL injury ruled him out for the entire season. A lot happened in that 12-month period and he found himself to Geelong in the offseason, a club who is in need of a CBA midfielder. After missing 2024, he gets a 30% discount on his 2023 average of 83 (well down from his 2022 average of 104), meaning he's priced at 58. He's also retained the forward status so you can pick him in a forward, a line where there aren't many players who can average over 90. Given all this, he's the easiest pick of the season.
Short: Forward status: tick, new club with midfield opportunities: tick, significant discount to his ability (46 points less than his career high): tick

Name: Cam Mackenzie
Comment: The pick seven of the 2022 National draft was one of the most hyped rookies leading into last season after he scored 92 in the pre-season match, second highest for the Hawks, from a juicy midfield role. And after 75 from 52% CBAs in R1, it looked like he was going to be one of the rookies for the season. However, never went above 30% after that, and despite a 94 in R3, he quickly found himself out of the Hawks' best 22, playing as sub in R5 and dropped after R6. He then played as sub a further three times and played twice in the last eight rounds. His VFL numbers were encouraging in that time, averaging 93 for the season but had two scores 119+. He entered 2024 with some hope of a breakout, however that never happened, finishing with an average of 58 from 25% CBAs. His season high score (82) came from his season high CBAs (64%), which happened to be his last game of the year. He averaged 108 in his two VFL games in a sign that he's ready to take the leap. Unfortunately, he's lost his forward status and also has the early bye. A slight watch in case he pumps out a bit Round 0 score, but I think he will need some time before a big breakout given the tight midfield rotation at the Hawks.
Short: Former pick 7, passes the eye test but yet to get the full-time mid role needed to take the next step, could happen this year and we'll find out early in Round 0

Name: Lincoln McCarthy
Short: Small forward who before last year had a clean bill of health since moving to the Lions, however scoring hasn't changed in that time and nothing to say it will

Name: Toby Bedford
Short: Moved from a small forward to a tagging role mid-season and to great effect, scoring (65 post bye) didn't spike as the CBAs (77%) did though given his pure defensive role in there

Name: Zak Jones
Comment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half-back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 89 highlighted by a 151 and 123 in consecutive weeks. He hasn't hit those heights since though, averaging 65, 55 and 57 in the last three seasons and never playing more than 13 matches. I've always liked him in the middle and thought he still had some decent footy in him, however he had a fair chance last year and didn't take it, and I feel like the Saints might have moved on from him now.
Short: Struggled to stay on the park in recent years after back-to-back 89s, had a few chances last year and scoring was a long way off that level

Name: Mitch Owens
Short: Serious talent who does it in an unconventional way, had a down year last season and where he wasn't required to do as much chop out in the ruck, logic says he improves in his fourth season but the role is tough

Name: Liam Henry
Short: Was a wing at Freo and scored okay at times, but used more as a forward for the Saints prior to injury and wasn't scoring great

Name: Caleb Poulter
Short: At his second club and same story being on the fringe and limited to a wing role, both not great for Fantasy

Name: Jacob van Rooyen
Short: Emerging key forward who has displayed a great set of hands, has future star all over him but unlikely to be a Fantasy one

Name: Jeremy Finlayson
Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: Hmm. I reckon there are 6 players I've listed as a potential Houston replacement and Finlayson would've been 44th on that list. He moved to defence and looked great, albeit against the Saints who gave the Port backs plenty so it's not the best read. 13 marks and even some kick-ins. I can't fit in another forward so I'm not starting, but like we've done with Ziebell in the past, we can always jump on after one or two weeks if he looks like this in the real stuff.
Short: Dropped off last season after two years 69+ talking a second ruck role, that's not needed now with a genuine ruck at the Power and if he plays he'll be limited forward

Name: Matt Guelfi
Short: Hard working half-forward but a role player for the Dons and might find opportunities limited again this season - injured to start the year

Name: Darcy Byrne-Jones
Short: Now a defensive forward after being a reliable 70/80s defender, hasn't been good for his Fantasy output and even if he switches back his upside isn't enough

Name: Shannon Neale
Short: Athletic ruck prospect with a booming kick, showed some great flashes in 2024 and looking very fit now but unlikely to be a Fantasy relevant player

Name: Harry Morrison
Short: Fringe wingman who is MID-only, not a Fantasy option

Name: Oscar Allen
Short: Injury impacted season after finishing 7th in the Coleman in 2023, even then he averaged 64 shows how low key forwards score in this game

Name: Lachlan Cowan
Short: A fringe defender who doesn't have much distribution responsibility

Name: Wayne Milera
Comment: Another season, another injury. 2024 didn't start great with a pre-season hamstring and then a knee injury keeping him to just three matches. He's been injured in three of the last four seasons after looking like a rising star in 2018 where he averaged 93 in the last five games. When he was moved back to half back in 2023 he started to look back to his best, averaging 83 in the L5 games. His body, role and position in the side is all too much to take a risk on, but if healthy and in the half back role, he could outperform his price by 25+ points.
Short: Hasn't had a decent run at it his whole career, pre-season hamstring issues then a knee injury cost him his 2024 season but 83 in L5 of 2023 shows he can score if healthy

Name: Paul Curtis
Short: Great tackler and don't argue on him, just not a scorer as a medium forward at AFL level and doubt he gets mid time despite his pressure

Name: Josh Ward
Comment: The former top 10 pick has been on my radar ever since his finish to his debut season (89 post-bye). However, even following the departures of Tom Mitchell and JOM, he hasn't seen the same inside opportunity since. The Hawks run a tight rotation of Day, Newcombe, Nash and Worpel, and their combined finishes in the B&F over the last two seasons show Sam Mitchell is very happy with their output. Day out to start the year didn't even help, with Ward's H&A CBAs were a career low. He played the first five matches at 23% CBAs, but played just one of the next 11 (0% CBAs) as Day returned from injury. He managed just four more games before the end of the season, but played both finals when Day was out and finally saw some midfield time, 60% CBAs for an average of 77. It's going to be a tight squeeze again in 2025 and starting Ward would be a genuine punt. The breakout will come at one point though, whether this year or next, so keep him on your radar. Back-to-back 108 averages in the VFL shows he still certainly has it.
Short: I wrongly picked a breakout two years ago following 89 post-bye in his debut season, hasn't hit the CBA level since and limited to a wing and VFL but he averaged 108 there the last two years and I still have hope

Name: Jake Lever
Short: A gun intercept defender but you don't get extra Fantasy points for intercepting

Name: Bobby Hill
Short: Small forward, better in real life than in Fantasy, as showed by his impact in the 2023 finals series

Name: Isaac Cumming
Comment: There is plenty of hype around Cumming this season after moving to the Crows following two disappointing seasons. In 2023 he dropped his averaged by 23 points, which was amazing given there was no injury and he was heading into his age 24 season, meaning he should be in his prime. Cumming averaged 91 in 2022 and his breakout 2021, quickly becoming the Giants' number one distributor down back as Leon played Ash on the ball and Whitfield up forward. Kingsley came in and put things straight, with Whitfield and Ash back in defence and later Himmelberg who moved back to finish the season. This pushed Cumming up to a wing, which as we know isn't a good thing for Fantasy scoring. A pre-season calf issue followed by a hamstring injury kept him on the sidelines until Round 16 in 2024 and then another hamstring strain saw him miss GWS' last five games of the home and away season before he returned for the finals. The hope is he moves back to the half-back line at the Crows or even if he plays wing, priced at 56 he should beat that by at least 20 points. The concern is his body as he's already had a hamstring injury this pre-season. As a mid-only there is also the risk he doesn't get DPP. However, if we get an indication that he's fit and playing in defence, I think he's going to be hard to pass up at that price. 13 FEB UPDATE: Sounds like he'll be more wing than half back. Less keen.
Short: A move to the Crows in the hope he can return to his 2022 form (91 average), hamstrings have been an issue of late as well as moving from defence, if he can get the half back role and healthy could be a smash pick

Name: Jack Gunston
Short: 33-year-old general forward who certainly doesn't score as he did in the past

Name: Brad Close
Short: Role player who has been great for Geelong after being picked up in the Rookie Draft, but not one for Fantasy

Name: Ben Long
Short: A move to the GC gave hope he could become a consistent scorer of the half-back (82 in the L5 of 2022 at Saints), but settled in a defensive forward role at the Suns which isn't a role for scoring

Name: Peter Ladhams
Short: Grundy's arrival has squashed any hope of Ladhams getting more regular games, despite showing a nice scoring ability in the VFL in the past (102 in 2022)

Name: Nick Watson
Short: Super debut season, if he kicked straight his average could've been high 60s which is remarkable for a small forward, especially a young one, going to be a star but in that role will be hard to score in this format

Name: Nick Larkey
Short: Been a star key forward in a struggling side but certainly doesn't score enough to be Fantasy relevant

Name: Brandon Walker
Short: Found his spot as the lockdown small defender at Freo but doesn't take much of the distribution

Name: Sam De Koning
Comment: The former first round pick burst onto the scene in 2022 where he played 23 games and won a premiership as a tall, key defender. Obviously a young, tall, key defender isn't going to be Fantasy relevant, and SDK averaged just 48 points in 2022 and 2023. He maintained that average for the first half of 2024 playing in the same role, before being introduced into the ruck, a position Geelong have been lacking for the last few years. While still very raw and displaying a low hitout win rate of 29% (far worse than Stanley 41%, Blit 37% and Conway 34%), he was able to showcase his athletic ability around the ground which led to a nice boost in Fantasy scoring. In the five games where he attended 40 or more ruck contests, he averaged 87. In the other 15, he averaged 45. His brother TDK took til last season before breaking out with his 88 average. He started the year 24 years of age. SDK will be 24 at the start of 2025. So if there is any indication of him playing in the ruck in 2025 (not holding my breath knowing Chris Scott), he's going to provide great value as a defender priced at 55. 13 FEB UPDATE: Conway injury news should lead to SDK starting ruck. Bumped him up a bit again. 25 FEB UPDATE: Was monstered by Draper/Bryan combo in pre-season and many will jump off now, I'm still selecting as long as he's named solo in Round 1 and scores okay in Round 0.
Short: Key position defender was introduced into the ruck in 2024 and when he was there he scored great (87 v 43), the Cats' ruck setup has been impossible to read the last few years but if he emerges as their main ruck he has a ton of value as a defender

Name: Jade Gresham
Comment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He teased us when introduced into the midfield in 2019, averaging 91 in the second half (100 in the last five), but managed just 14 games the next two seasons. Ross Lyon kicked him out of the midfield and played him as a forward, averaging just 22% CBAs post-bye of 2023 and 7% in the L5. A move to the Dons and their pretty one-paced midfield gave hope that he would be used in there a bit more. However, he managed just 1% CBAs (career low), so it looks like his role is limited to a pure small forward now.
Short: A new team saw him spend less time in the middle (just 1% CBAs) and now looks purely limited as a small forward

Name: Mark O'Connor
Short: Genuine role player, either in defence or as a tagger, and scoring has never been relevant

Name: Rhyan Mansell
Short: 38 games in last two seasons but averages in the 50s

Name: Jack Henry

Name: Ben Miller
Short: Settled as a key defender at the Tigers and certainly not a scorer

Name: Jacob Wehr

Name: Ben McKay

Name: Beau McCreery
Short: Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for Fantasy

Name: Oskar Baker

Name: Nik Cox

Name: Darcy Fort

Name: Lachlan Murphy

Name: Cooper Lord

Name: Willie Rioli

Name: Blake Howes
