Name: Harry Sharp
Short: VFL scores are good (85 and 89 last two years) but played just six games after moving across from the Lions, which is the most he's played in four seasons

Name: Lachlan McNeil
Short: A classic Bulldog role player in the forward line, unlikely to become Fantasy relevant

Name: Jack Payne
Short: Genuine key back and scoring is relatively capped

Name: Thomson Dow
Short: Career high 17 matches in 2024 with decent CBA opportunities (56%), always looked pretty good around stoppages but just doesn't score enough for Fantasy, even limited to mid-70s at VFL level

Name: Sam Taylor
Comment: 10 MAR UPDATE: Of all the players to get an update this pre-season, I didn't expect to see this guy in there. He scored 118 in Round 0, which means he has a 'hidden' price of $589k, up $60k from his starting price. His hidden breakeven is around the single digits, so he's poised to go up again. Let's say he scores 50 which he’s averaged before, he'll go up approx. $100k after Round 1. We are struggling for defenders and normally we hope to get $100k over 4-5 weeks from our rooks, so this could be a free ticket to cash gen. It would also allow a look at SDK (how much ruck does he play) and even Freijah alongside Dale. There is certainly merit to the move. He's not cheap though and if that extra coin means taking it off a player you like in other positions, I wouldn't do it. If you've got the cash there to spend in defence and can't settle on someone, then I'd do it. It's a nice little sub-plot to start the season.
Short: One of the best defenders in the comp, however he still won't be Fantasy relevant

Name: Max King
Short: Will be a star key forward someday, but scoring isn't there

Name: Liam Jones
Short: A very good defender but a pure lockdown who won't score great in this game, will miss the first chunk of the season with a hamstring injury, opening up the door for Busslinger to debut

Name: Henry Hustwaite
Short: Defensive-minded inside mid with high handballing numbers, looked good last pre-season with decent CBA numbers but only managed the four games, all as sub, 91 VFL average a good sign but Hawks bat very deep

Name: Noah Answerth
Short: Spent time on a wing in 2024 but mainly used as a lockdown defender

Name: Dylan Williams
Short: Broke in as a defender in 2023 but limited to just five games in 2024 as he was overtaken by a few, no Houston might given him a chance but there are plenty who can play that role at the Power

Name: Keidean Coleman
Comment: Coleman moved to defence in 2022 after averaging 109 in the role at reserve level in 2021. He showed he has the makings to be a star defender of the future, but injures stopped him from a full breakout. The story was much the same in 2023. He was concussed in Round 1 on 57, forcing him to miss Round 2. He returned to average just 61 in his next nine to the bye, looking a shadow of the player that broke out a year earlier. He was so far out of form that he started as sub post-bye, which is where he scored his 23. After that, he was quoted saying "I just thought to myself to back myself. That’s when I play my best footy, when I’m just out there, playing freely and playing on instinct". And he did. He averaged 90 in his last seven matches, which included another injury (eye) which saw him sit off just after half time and miss two more matches. He then went to another level in the finals, averaging 102, including a best on ground performance in the prelim and 22 disposals to half time (over 100) in the GF. We were all ready to pick him last year, before he unfortunately did his knee in Round 0. He's made a full recovery and ready for 2025, coming in even more discounted at a 51 price tag. There are a few red flags such as an ACL recovery (do they rest him early fresh off a flag), fighting with Zorko for distribution duties and a Round 3 bye, but if he can manage over 80 in Round 0, which I think he can, then it's worth taking a punt on all of those. UPDATE: Sounds like he's touch and go for Round 0, so I think we need to plan our teams without him. 12 FEB UPDATE: Suffered a setback with his recovery and may miss the first month of the season. Cross him off the list.
Short: Was in calculations last year after 95 in L2, 102 in finals in 2023 before an ACL injury in Round 0, a few risks come with that but he's now even cheaper this year

Name: Harrison Petty
Short: Key utility who is said to play in defence in 2025, but neither forward or defensive role has been good for his scoring

Name: Lachie Fogarty
Short: Been on the radar since his elite junior numbers (124 average in NAB League) but limited to a forward role at AFL level and always on the fringe

Name: Liam Stocker
Short: Former first round pick, drafted as a midfielder but settled as a defender at AFL level, Saints have plenty who possess the ball back there so his scoring is typically capped

Name: Mason Cox
Short: 34-year-old key forward who backs up in the ruck, unless something ever happens to Cameron he's not going to be Fantasy relevant

Name: Brandon Zerk-Thatcher
Short: Genuine lockdown tall defender

Name: Charlie Ballard
Short: Reliable key defender but unlikely scoring will change

Name: Cooper Sharman
Short: Sharman has an impressive set of hands and becoming a regular for the Saints, playing as a 3rd tall which makes it tricky for consistent scoring

Name: Caleb Daniel
Comment: Daniel has felt every bit of 'Bevo' in the last two seasons, as has been used as a defender, inside mid and forward, getting dropped along with being sub or subbed off (8 times in 2024). Of all the positions, he does his best from a Fantasy point of view playing as a half-back (was a borderline top six defender from 2019-2020). However, the fact he hasn't had defender status for the last two years shows how little he has been used there. An off-season move to the Roos is expected to see Daniel return to defence, a role that he's not just consistently averaged over 90 in, but one that other players have excelled in at the Roos (Hall, Ziebell, Sheezel, McKercher, even Fisher at times last year). He's younger than you think (28), so unless something surprising happens and he loses the half-back role, I can't see him averaging less than mid-80s which priced at 50 and as a forward makes him an automatic selection. If things go well and he is the primary user off half back, he can certainly exceed that mark and finish as a top six forward that we keep all year.
Short: The gun defender of the past comes in with MID/FWD status which tells you everything you need to know about Bevo but he is expected to return to his distribution role following a move to the Roos where he's averaged 90+ consistently

Name: Bayley Fritsch
Short: His 74 average was when he played further up the ground, however he's limited to a 50-60 average while in the forward role where I expect him to remain

Name: Dougal Howard
Short: Key defender whose career best was when he took 60% of the KIs, that won't happen again so he'll remain around the 50-mark, will miss the first three months with a shoulder

Name: Matthew Cottrell
Short: Rallied strongly since being delisted and re-rookied but averaging in the 50s & 60s isn't what we're after

Name: Ned Reeves
Comment: Meek arrived in 2023 but Reeves proved the hardest ruck for opposition players to ruck against and was the preferred option for most of 2023, playing 21 games. He then started in 2024, however Meek quickly overtook him and Reeves finished with just the four games. Reeves is a very strong hitout ruck, but struggles to impact around the ground and it appears that the Hawks are going to continue with Meek as their main man going forward.
Short: Meek took his spot and it doesn't look like changing outside of an injury

Name: Aidan Corr
Short: Lock-down defender never averaged more than 65

Name: Robbie Fox
Short: Now 31 and always seems to be on the fringe at the Swans

Name: Seth Campbell
Short: Showed some great signs after debuting in 2024, the Tigers might have found one but as a small forward it's unlikely we'll see him get much of a scoring bump

Name: Jye Amiss
Short: Promising key forward who was a bit down last year, he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good Fantasy options

Name: Alex Pearce
Short: Frequent injury concerns earlier in his career, however genuine key defenders don't score well

Name: Elliott Himmelberg
Short: Key forward struggled to cement a spot at the Crows and now at the Suns, I doubt we see that result in much of a score bump

Name: Esava Ratugolea
Short: A move to the Power saw him play career high number of games, but the key defensive role kept his scoring sub-50

Name: Tom Brown
Short: Emerged as a future gun defender with a very impressive kick, his scoring will rise a bit but I doubt it will be by enough to be relevant

Name: Joe Richards
Short: Mature aged pick from the 2022 draft who was playing local footy, looked great in his nine games as a small forward and now finds himself at the Power where I think he'll get regular games but not much of a scorer

Name: Nick Holman
Short: Definition of a role player up forward for the Suns, and certainly not worried about scoring Fantasy points

Name: Finn Maginness
Short: Elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL over the last few years, Hawks dropped the tag last year though and he scored well at VFL level, but doubt he ever gets an attacking role at AFL

Name: Thomas Berry
Short: Has averaged well at lower levels but a genuine small forward at AFL and scoring is limited

Name: Michael Frederick
Short: Hard running forward is a regular at Freo, but role isn't great for Fantasy

Name: Matthew Owies
Short: Small pressure forward who was surprisingly not offered a contract at the Blues after being a regular, now at West Coast but scoring is limited in the role

Name: Joel Amartey
Short: Outside his nine goal, 131 point effort, he's a low scoring key forward

Name: Sam Powell-Pepper
Short: The high-pressure small forward is returning from an ACL, nice discount from career high but that's when he was getting midfield minutes

Name: Ben Hobbs
Comment: I liked what I've saw from Hobbs in his first two seasons, which makes his 2024 season even more disappointing. He had 15% CBAs in his debut season and 35% in 2023, increasing as the season goes on. I certainly expected this to continue, however an AC injury in the pre-season saw him have a delayed start and he just never got going, in and out of the side and when playing, limited to a forward role. His season high of 99 came from his season high 12% CBAs and he ticked along nicely at VFL level averaging 107. However, Caldwell and Durham were the young players who got more midfield time and didn't disappoint. There is a bit of a logjam of mids at the Dons but I still believe Hobbs' time will come. He's one I've got my eye on in the Opening Round and might prove a big differentiator to the popular forward picks. 25 FEB UPDATE: Big score in pre-season game but was a bit sloppy with his disposal. We get a free look in Round 0 but a good sign nonetheless.
Short: Very disappointing season with career low scoring and CBAs following a AC injury to start, will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future

Name: Sam Sturt
Short: Crafty medium forward but output is limited when playing forward at AFL level

Name: Darcy Moore
Short: Star key defender in real life, output was well down in 2024 both IRL and Fantasy but even if he bounces back to 2023 levels he's not enough value

Name: Jack Petruccelle
Short: Speedy small forward saw some consistent CBAs in 2024, however certainly hasn't looked a scorer

Name: Arie Schoenmaker
Comment: A tall defender but plays more like a rebounder due to his elite kick and with that has always been a great Fantasy scorer - 100 in his draft year and 90 in his first season at VFL. He played the four games in his first season, which is pretty good considering his size and age. A lot has opened up for him to play a lot more in 2025. Bonner has been delisted, Battle left to the Hawks and now Howard is expected to miss the first three months with a shoulder injury. That means Schoenmaker should be a regular in defence for the Saints this season and with his natural scoring power, he makes for a very interesting mid-priced option in defence. Any other year I'd probably wait and trade into him after seeing some decent scores, but with the premium defenders all fully priced and a lot of the value ones with an early bye, I can certainly see merit to starting Schoenmaker if named Round 1 and a short-term flyer.
Short: The slider of his draft and after a delay getting started he showed off his lovely left foot kick in four AFL games, should see more in 2025 with no Battle or Bonner and could prove some sneaky value

Name: Changkuoth Jiath
Short: Injuries have kept him off the park plenty of times in the last two seasons, played as a wing when healthy and output far less than when he was an attacking half-back

Name: Anthony Caminiti
Short: Played 33 matches after being overlooked in the 2022 draft and showed plenty, trialled as a defender at times last year but likely continue as a forward in 2025, a 21-year-old key forward so won't be relevant in this game

Name: Bruce Reville
Short: Mature age cat-B rookie played 12 games in 2024 and showed some great signs with a lovely kick, Lions bat deep though so the winger will likely be on the fringe again

Name: Daniel McStay
Short: Key forward returned from an ACL to play five games, comes in slightly discounted but update is capped based on his career high average of 64

Name: Braeden Campbell
Comment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 96 in his second game. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a player of the future. However, he's played 23 matches in each of the last two seasons and averaged just 60, and that's excluding the six games he was sub in 2024. I think it will be a while before he comes Fantasy relevant with Roberts, Blakey and Lloyd controlling things down back. Still keep an eye on him if he starts to play down back. He scored a 140 in one of his two VFL games in 2024 which is a great sign for the future.
Short: Elite kick and has talent, but yet to show much in the scoring department so far - his hope is to move into defence rather than wing but the Swans are well stocked back there

Name: Luke Pedlar
Comment: Former pick 11 battled with injury in his first few seasons at the Crows but played 21 in 2023 and looked the part with his strong body and skills. He was used primarily as a small forward, but was introduced to the midfield with 13% CBAs across the season, being preferred in there over the likes of Rachele and Soligo. However, he was limited to just four games in 2025 before a shoulder injury at SANFL level cut his season short. There's a lot of talk about what the midfield makeup will be at the Crows in 2025 with the arrival of Peatling and emergence of some young guns, so Pedlar might find it tough again for opportunities in 2025.
Short: Another of the young Crow fwd/mids who have shown enough to suggest they will be future guns, however form and injury kept him to just four games in 2024 and their midfield depth might make it hard for him again

Name: Dylan Stephens
Short: Moving to the lowly ranked Roos didn't help the former pick five get much of a bump, likely to take a wing role if he makes their best 22 but I have doubts he does

Name: Xavier O'Halloran
Short: Wing/forward who has had his opportunities but has never scored well enough, although his VFL average (115 up from 86 in 2023) is promising and with Perryman and Cumming leaving, he might have first crack at the wing

Name: James Borlase
Short: Cat-B key defender played 10 games in 2024 with Murray missing the first half, certainly not a scorer

Name: Kamdyn McIntosh
Short: Outside wing who has typically averaged in the 60s, that dropped to 47 last season but as a MID-only he's not going to be an option

Name: Dane Rampe
Short: Gun key defender but is now 34 and finding it a bit harder these days

Name: Jhye Clark
Comment: Drawing strong comparisons to Joel Selwood in his draft year, Clark is a strong inside mid with clean disposal and widely valued leadership traits. He was the second highest averaging player during the U18 Champs, going at 105 points per game and earning himself the Vic Country MVP. He also averaged 119 in his last four NAB league games of the season. So when he made his debut as sub in Round 9 2023, it was highly anticipated. He didn't disappoint, laying five tackles and getting six touches in just over a quarter. However, a foot injury forced him to miss the rest of the season. He was named in Round 1 and played 15 of the first 17 games, however featured as sub in four of those and didn't set the world on fire in the others . He finished in the VFL where he did have two games over 125, however again was a bit underwhelming. The Cats notoriously take their time with their kids and provide plenty of opportunities to their senior bodies, so it might be a while yet until we see Clark become a regular midfielder for Geelong.
Short: Pick eight from 2022 draft played just one game in his debut year (five tackles in 25%) due to a foot issue, so was good to see him play 15 in 2024, scoring limited though as Cats aren't the best team for young kids

Name: Shane McAdam
Short: Small forward whose first season at the Dees was marred by injuries, even when fully healthy though his scoring is limited in the role

Name: Jacob Koschitzke
Short: Moved to Richmond from the Hawks last season and will certainly find it harder for opportunities as a forward for Richmond in 2025

Name: Maurice Rioli
Short: Pressure forward but role will always limit his scoring

Name: Will Brodie
Short: Hasn’t got back into the side since Round 7 2023 after a breakout 2022, Young moving in the midfield and the evolution of Johnson, Erasmus and NOD might mean Freo have moved past him

Name: Brandon Starcevich
Short: Gun small defender, often takes the opposition's number one medium forward, not a role for producing decent scores

Name: James O'Donnell
Short: Emerging tall defender certainly not a Fantasy scorer

Name: Lachlan Sullivan
Short: Mature age with nice VFL numbers, got his chance with 10 games in 2024 and looked okay, might find it hard fitting into a full strength Pies midfield though

Name: Harvey Thomas
Short: Played an impressive 22 games after being taken at pick 59, showed some tricks as a small forward (including a game with 100), but while in the role he's unlikely to score consistently - suspended to start the season

Name: Andy Moniz-Wakefield
Short: Debuted in 2024 on the back on improved VFL numbers (98 average up from 68), likely on the fringe again though

Name: Ryan Angwin
Short: Former first rounder is a nice size and moves well, however scoring has never been there at either AFL or VFL level

Name: Marty Hore
Short: Got his second chance at the Dees after being a mature-age draftee previously, did bring his prolific VFL form to the AFL (averaged over 100 at VFL two years in a row leading into 2024) and now finds himself a depth player

Name: Jake Melksham
Short: The veteran medium forward returned from a knee injury last year, however has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now and when he does play it's as a role player

Name: Oleg Markov
Short: The dashing defender's second year at the Pies wasn't as successful as his first, Houston stepping in probably shuts down any chance of a bounce back

Name: Finlay Macrae
Comment: Finlay is developing well in the VFL in a very hard team to break into. There was no under-age football in his draft year, so we had to rely on his 2019 year where he played as a 17-year-old for Oakleigh Chargers, a team that boasted Matt Rowell, Noah Anderson and Will Phillips in the midfield. Finlay was forced to play mostly across half-forward but showed some great signs and from all reports was more advanced than his (half) brother who by contrast only came good during the second half of his draft year. However, despite putting up consistent numbers in the VFL since being drafted (average over 90), he is yet to lock in a regular spot in the Pies' 22. His career high games is nine and TOG of 52%, which shows that when he is selected he's often used as the sub. It was a bit worrying that he didn't get much of a chance last season, despite the injury worries at the Pies mid-season. So I'm finding it hard to see him change things in 2025 given they are going in with a healthy list.
Short: Brother-of who has averaged over 90 in the VFL since being drafted (career best 101 in 2024), however hasn't locked down a spot in the Pies' 22 and not sure if that changes

Name: Tom McCartin
Short: Gun key defender but three seasons in a row in averaging in the 40s indicates he's not a scorer

Name: Bailey Humphrey
Comment: After a super impressive debut season, the big Humper had a poor 2024 under new coach Damien Hardwick. He's obviously a long way from it, but his debut season showed signs of the De Goey / Petracca / Dusty mould of a very dangerous forward of centre player. It's the role every football team wants but it's a very hard role to play, and when it comes to Fantasy, typically these players are better IRL than their scores suggest. He certainly didn't go on with it in his second season, averaging 6 points per game less than his debut year. He was pretty well eliminated from the centre bounce rotation (4% post-bye after 17% in 2023) and as a pure forward, it's going to be very hard for him to score. I still have hope that he can become a star in real life (and hopefully Fantasy), but I'm certainly keeping my expectations in check for this season.
Short: Pick six of 2022 really impressed in his first season as a powerful fwd/mid which is a hard role to play, stagnated in year two and now the jury are back out

Name: Oliver Henry
Short: Talented forward who is an underrated goal kicker, but Fantasy scoring is limited

Name: Jack Williams
Short: Developing tall has played a fair bit over the last two season with West Coast's struggles, but scoring is very limited and will need time to develop

Name: Dan Butler
Short: 74 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a 50s guy his whole career which is what you can expect from a small forward

Name: Lachie Jones
Short: Strong bodied defender was flagged for mid-time in the past, hasn't really come on for a former first-rounder and scoring at all levels is underwhelming

Name: Tyler Sonsie
Short: Impressed in his debut season and after just three games in his second year played a career high 14 in 2024, didn't see the midfield minutes though where he's averaged decent numbers in the past and I think the new draftees might leapfrog him

Name: Mykelti Lefau
Short: The 195cm high flyer was super impressive in his first season at AFL level, however sadly did his knee and will take a while to return

Name: Ben Paton
Short: Shutdown small defender who now finds himself at the Swans after completely falling out of favour at the Saints, regardless his scoring in that role will be limited - looks like he might play and be a heartbeat

Name: Laitham Vandermeer
Short: Vandermeer has some talent, but scoring has always remained around the 50-mark

Name: Jack Silvagni
Short: Returning from an ACL and said to be training with the defenders, which gives upside to his 44 price-tag, I've got a watch on him although unless it's a distribution role that I doubt, it's still hard to see him improve enough

Name: Michael Walters
Short: 34-year-old small forward who scored well in the past with stints in the midfield, but those days are over now

Name: Charlie Dean
Short: Mature aged key defender managed eight games in 2024 after battling injuries since arriving at the club, purely a role player though

Name: Josh Sinn
Comment: Port Adelaide worked hard to secure the rebounding defender, trading up first during the trade period before trading up on draft day. He backed this up by playing early, debuting in Round 2, however his debut season was hampered by a groin injury and didn't add to his one game. He featured three times in his second season, but sub for two of them and then hamstring surgery finished his season early. It was a similar story in 2024 as his season was interrupted with a collarbone injury. Sinn is now completing his first full pre-season, so he should have every chance to have a breakout season. However, Port have a number of running defenders, even with Houston leaving, so while there is some upside in Sinn, he's not someone I want to punt on until I see him do it regularly first.
Short: Former pick 12 hasn't been able to string many games together due to injury (groin year one, hamstring year two, collarbone year three), highly rated so hopefully he gets a good run at it this season

Name: Nick Murray
Short: Key defender returned from a knee injury but scoring remained in the 40s

Name: Samson Ryan
Short: Mobile ruck/key forward played just eight games after 14 in 2023, showed some great signs but I doubt he'll score much while Nank is healthy

Name: Jackson Archer
Short: The son-of does some nice things in defence and he's now a key part of their 22, however as a role player his scoring will always be limited

Name: Jesse Motlop
Short: Small forward has shown a bit in his first three seasons, but that still led to a sub-50 average such is the role

Name: Aaron Cadman
Short: Former pick one who like all young KPP looked a bit lost in year one, was much better in year two and will likely go on to be a star, however not in Fantasy

Name: Buku Khamis
Short: Moved to defence in 2024 but not going to be a Fantasy scorer

Name: Angus Sheldrick
Comment: Sheldrick is a contested ball winning bull who led the Under-19 Championships in contested possessions, and debuted in Round 1 2022. He didn't play again at AFL level that season, but after a 158 at VFL level, he featured in Round 7 in 2023 for the first time since. He was subbed out on just 18 and went back to the VFL where he scored a 130. He played again at AFL level in Round 10 where he started sub and scored just 8, and also played VFL that week for a 118. So while his career scores at AFL read 28, 18 and 8, he showed at the level below that he had something special. We then finally saw him get a decent run at AFL level, playing four games in a row at 91, despite playing just 64% TOG. He then did his syndesmosis in Round 17 on 46, and he didn't feature again. Then nothing went right in 2024. He broke a finger in a VFL practice match (so he wasn't in line for their Opening Round game) and missed the next three weeks. He returned to the VFL in Round 4 with a 120, and followed it up with 109, 103 and 89. He then injured his ankle on 6 the following game and missed six weeks. He played the final five games in the VFL, which included a game with 36 touches and 114 points in the second last round of the year. He's a genuine scorer. The issue is, where does he fit in the Swans midfield, or team at all. Sub/role and Best 22 risk is there, but if he's assured a spot in the midfield and puts up some scores early, he's one you can jump to priced at 44. 28 FEB UPDATE: Another mid down at the Swans, could very well get his chance. 10 MAR UPDATE: Subbed out in the third quarter of Round 0 and didn't look good when he was on.
Short: Didn't play a game due to injury and form, emerged as a future Fantasy stud in 2023 with insane PPM numbers, the question is if he gets midfield minutes - or even a game - this season

Name: Sam Banks
Short: 15 games in 2024 but used as a wing / half back and scoring output didn’t catch the eye

Name: Logan Morris
Short: Brisbane have found one here at pick 31, great size and offers something different inside 50, however as a Fantasy scorer his output is going to be limited

Name: Calsher Dear
Short: Hawks have found one here at pick 56, looks a genuine star forward of the future and surprised everyone in 2024, however in that role his scoring is going to be limited

Name: Dante Visentini
Short: A ruck project who managed three games in 2023 despite Sweet and Soldo arriving, but he looks the clear third choice option for now and is purely depth

Name: Nathan O'Driscoll
Comment: Looked great on a wing in the All Stars game. Feel like he has that role locked, awkward price for a mid-only though and I think I'd still rather one of the gun rookies. 2 MAR UPDATE: Backed up his All Stars game with another strong performance in the Community game. Young out Round 1 should help and I'm warming to him, although I also find it hard to fit him in unless coming down from a Peatling type who I still have just ahead. Might be a corrective trade if he pops Round 1.
Short: Hard running wing who transitioned into an inside mid at Peel to great effect late in the year (29 touches, six tackles and a goal in GF), I think he takes a regular wing spot in 2025 and might see some inside time, but will still always be on the fringe

Name: Jack Martin
Comment: Martin showed a heap of promise early days but has failed to go on with it. A lot of that could be put down to his reccurring soft tissue injuries, resulting in just three games last season and then being de-listed at the end of it. He gets a fresh start at the Cats, a team which a good track record of getting players in a good space, so I have hope that he returns to his high marking and hard hitting best. However, his three 83+ seasons in a row involved some CBAs, which I doubt he sees at the Cats. So while he will certainly outperform his price if fit, I think he will be more in the 50-60 mark rather than the 60-70 mark required to be a decent starting pick.
Short: A horror run of injuries, hard to remember as it was so long ago now but averaged 83 three times in a row before, could the move to Geelong get him back to his best?

Name: Lloyd Johnston
Short: Rebounding defender who caught the eye with 28 intercept possessions in a NAB League match, but scoring was modest in his first two seasons at senior level where he's spent most of his time forward

Name: Edward Allan
Comment: After making his long-awaited debut against Fremantle in round 11 as sub, the 6ft3 mid was made to wait until the final game of the home and away season for another opportunity, where he showed he can become a regular senior player in 2025 by collecting 21 disposals, 10 contested possessions and six tackles. He was in good form in the VFL prior to that breakout game, collecting 27, 23 (and eight tackles) and 32 disposals and two goals in the three weeks leading in. He's highly rated internally and I wouldn't be surprised to see him be a regular in 2024. Priced at 43, he could end up being a great mid-pricer if he does get the midfield opportunity which he had in Round 24. However, there's no guarantee of that happening, so unless he puts up a big score in a good role in Round 0, he might be one we have to wait on.
Short: Tall mid who went first round in 2022 but couldn't crack into a very strong team, debuted as sub mid-way through last year but it was his Round 24 performance that caught the eye (87 points) and should see a lot more opportunities in 2025

Name: Tom J. Lynch
Short: Been limited to just eight games across the past two campaigns due to foot and hamstring injuries, his best is likely behind him given his age and the Tigers' likely struggles, so while he should outperform his heavily discounted price, it's not enough for me to jump on

Name: Neil Erasmus
Comment: Erasmus is gaining some traction in Fantasy circles this pre-season given his price, forward status and numbers at the lower level. Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 average in WAFL Colts, three x 130+ in WAFL league), high endurance and good size. However, since being drafted, he's struggled for senior opportunity and when he's been there, it's often in the vest. After just four games in his debut season (2 as sub), Erasmus played 14 matches in 2023 (six as sub) and just four again in 2024 (three as sub and subbed out in the other). Of his six games where he wasn't sub or subbed out in 2023, he averaged an impressive 75. Two seasons on, more developed and some impressive WAFL footy behind him (including winning the best on ground in the GF), he should be able to exceed that. The issue is, I'm not more confident in him avoiding the vest. It's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong and Young taking up the majority, however I think he leapfrogs Fyfe this season and gets a decent crack. If there is a green light on selection, he's certainly worth the punt, but the shadow of the vest is going to remain a constant threat. 2 MAR UPDATE: Looks like Reid has overtaken him and if he plays, sub is most likely. I'm avoiding.
Short: Former top 10 pick with big numbers at lower level, however never had a full crack in the middle at AFL level (nine vests in 23 games), but he's an accumulator at the lower level and should see more TOG this season following the departures

Name: Daniel Turner
Short: The natural key defender was used up forward for the Dees given their forward roles, he's averaged over 82 in the VFL in the last two seasons, but scoring will be limited if he continues to gets a chance at AFL level

Name: Noah Long

Name: Ryan Maric
Comment: Maric was taken pick one of the 2023 mid-season draft and been a regular since in West Coast's forward line. He moved to the wing to finish 2024 and while he looked good with ball in hand with his great field kicking, he struggled to get much of the ball. However, it appears that he's moved to half-back in 2025 to be a distributor back there. It's much easier to find the ball back there and with his kicking, he could even see some kick-ins given West Coast's number one player for kick-ins in 2024 was their full back. I'm not expecting a big bump, but he's certainly one to keep on the radar in the pre-season games.
Short: Mid-season pickup with some nice forward craft, used on a wing late in the season and looks good with ball in hand, training with the defenders in the pre-season where it might be a bit easier

Name: Angus McLennan
Short: Lockdown defender with some senior experience but VFL average (62) is modest, so he's certainly not a scorer

Name: Jacob Blight
Short: Mid-season draftee who I thought looked good on debut and was surprised he didn't play more, expect to see more of him in 2025 but in that role his scoring is going to be limited

Name: Hugo Garcia
Comment: Known as a big tackler in his draft year (averaged seven in Coates), Garcia showed he could also tackle at senior level. In eight VFL games he had 10+, including two games with 13, one with 14 and one with 15. This is the kind of pressure that Ross Lyon loves and saw him debut in his first season despite being taken at pick 50. He started sub on debut but came on to lay seven tackles in just 34% TOG, finishing with an impressive 53 points. The next week he played a full game and laid nine tackles, finished with 71. He went on to play eight games for the season, however was sub for five of them and showed enough in a small sample size that he can score with his ability to tackle. A few have gone down at the Saints, so Garcia might be in line to play early. If so, he's worth watching, but the risk of the vest will no doubt continue to be there. FEB 22 UPDATE: Wow. Full time mid role in match sim on a tight rotation. Come from the clouds but on that it's very hard not to pick him at that price in the forward line.
Short: Big tackler (averaged seven per game in Coates, eight of 11 VFL games with 10+) if given an opportunity he should score

At this stage he'd be my R3 but pending on the pre-season games he could make his way to R2. Personally I'd rather Freo just ruck Jackson though,

I just don't know where you'd fit him in as I'm pretty set on the 6 forwards and rookies there as well, so he's a pass for me but I understand the interest.

Name: Elijah Hewett
Comment: Hewett is the modern midfielder who breaks from stoppages and hits the scoreboard. While his numbers don't look great (55 average in his draft year, 46 in his 14 AFL matches and 26 in the WAFL), he's a much better player than that. In his draft year, he scored 115 when returning through the WAFL Reserves in 2022 and had a huge game one for WA in the U18 Champs where he picked up BOG honours, collecting 29 disposals and two goals. He then spent most of his year in the WAFL against tougher opposition, which is why his junior scores are lower than the other first rounders of the draft. He showed some great signs in his debut season in a limited role and TOG. Unfortunately he missed the entire 2024 season with a foot issue, but that looks behind him and he's been training with the mids all pre-season. Outside of Harley, he's West Coast's big hope so he should get all the opportunity he needs in 2025 and as a forward, should be a great option if he stays healthy. 6 MAR UPDATE: Due to miss the start of the season with a quad.
Short: Showed spark in his debut season but missed the entire 2024 with a foot injury, back healthy now and some big hopes on him, as a forward he should play and get midfield time making him a great option at that price
