Short: Small forward who might get more games without Martin and Owies, however even when he does play, he doesn't make an impact in this game

Name: Ollie Lord
Short: Key forward who should see more games in 2025 due to Dixon retiring and Marshall injured, but scoring will be limited in the role

Name: Karl Worner
Short: Averaged 90 in the WAFL since being drafted, played in Round 1 2024 which is a good sign but was badly concussed and only managed three more games (all as sub), job security always going to be an issue

Name: Henry Smith
Short: Development ruck, improved his VFL averaged from 67 to 97 which is a good sign but the Big O is still the man for now

Name: Joel Hamling
Short: Didn’t feature in his first season at the Swans, genuine key back

Name: Deven Robertson
Comment: Robertson was one of the most hyped rookies in Fantasy when he was drafted, following his elite scoring in his draft year; 113 average in the National Championships (ranked 1) and 120 average in WAFL colts (also ranked 1). He hasn’t done a heap at AFL level in his first five seasons, and bottomed out with just two senior games in 2024. His VFL form is still strong, 98 last year and 114 and 104 the years prior. I think the Lions have moved past him now with the Ashcroft boys getting into the midfield it but he's always worth tracking due to his elite scoring at the lower level.
Short: Junior gun who has displayed that same level of ball winning ability in the VFL (114 in 2023, 98 2024), but limited to a forward or defensive role when at AFL level where his scoring has been limited and he might have just been overtaken by the Ashcroft boys

Name: Connor O'Sullivan
Short: Former pick 11 but KPP at the Cats who will likely need some time to develop, talked up internally but hard to see him scoring much as a young key defender

Name: Daniel Curtin
Comment: Adelaide traded up to draft Curtin at pick 8, who was a centre half-back with good foot skills. Curtin produced a huge U18 Champs campaign, averaging 23.5 disposals and 6.5 marks per game for a 104 point average and CHB honours in the Team of the Year. He featured heavily in the back half of the season in the WAFL, holding his own with 16.5 disposals and four marks per game, while he also played through the midfield at Colts level. While it seems more natural to introduce him into the AFL system as a defender, the Crows used him as a midfielder in his limited games last year and that's where he finished at SANFL level. While it sounds good, his scoring would be better as a defender. Regardless, if he's named at that price, he's certainly one to consider given his pedigree and extra year in the system.
Short: Former pick eight who was drafted as a defender, but used as a forward and even midfielder in his first season, looks like the midfield role may stick and while Crows have plenty running through there, if he's named Round 1 he's a sneaky option at that price

Name: Judson Clarke
Short: Missed most of 2024 with an ACL, has some nice forward craft but not in a great Fantasy role and will take time to recover

Name: Robert Hansen Jr
Short: Taken at pick two in the AFL Mid-Season Rookie Draft, small forward role where scoring will always be limited

Name: Brandon Ryan
Short: Picked in the mid-season draft and then traded to Brisbane in the same year, might get more of a go with no Daniher but unlikely to make much of an impact

Name: Oscar McDonald
Short: Found himself at a third club after being named at full-back in the 2023 VFL team of the year, but knee surgery ruled him out of 2024

Name: Arthur Jones
Short: Small forward played 13 games in 2023 and showed great excitement, but just one in 2024 and role when playing isn't good for scoring

Name: Alwyn Davey Jnr
Short: Showed some nice signs in his 20 games since being drafted, small forward role will keep his scoring limited

Name: Ryan Gardner
Short: Key defender missed most of 2024 with a wrist injury, certainly not a scorer

Name: Tom Fullarton
Short: Back up ruck/forward who couldn't get a game with Max injured, now Campbell is there he's even further down the pecking order

Name: Max Ramsden
Short: 202cm ruck is behind the two others at the Hawks, so I doubt we'll see him this season

Name: Clay Hall
Short: Inside mid with senior experience after dominating at lower levels (averaging 27 disposals and 108 points in championships), season was interrupted with an ankle injury and never really got going, West Coast have recruited a few new players but apparently looking good in the pre-season

Name: Jy Farrar
Short: Fringe defender who has never been an accumulator and unlikely to change

Name: Ted Clohesy
Short: Cat-B rook but one with scoring pedigree, averaged 96 at NAB League and 103 last season at VFL level, only two games in 2024 (both as sub) but might see more in 2025 with Cats injecting some more youth

Name: Harvey Johnston
Short: More of an impact player rather than an accumulator in juniors and that showed with his 56 average in the WAFL last season

Name: Corey Warner
Short: Has been a common vest candidate so far in his career and that may well continue

Name: Caleb Graham
Short: Key defender with a very modest scoring history at all levels

Name: Caiden Cleary
Short: Tough inside mid, made All-Australian in his draft year after averaging 29 disposals, five marks, and six tackles for a 107 average, might need time before becoming a regular at AFL level though

Name: Josh Fahey
Short: Continues to put up huge numbers up in the VFL (105 last year) found it hard to crack into the senior team though and his suspension to start the season is going to make it tough

Name: James Tunstill
Short: Hard, contested ball winning midfielder who always gets nice VFL numbers (96 last year) but hasn't cracked it yet in the AFL

Name: Josh Gibcus
Short: Promising tall defender who was taken at pick nine in 2021, missed the entire 2023 season with injury, did his ACL in Round 1 2024 and has a significant hamstring injury this year, hope he gets a run at it soon

Name: Zach Reid
Comment: 25 FEB UPDATE: Scored well in pre-season and even took some kick-ins, bench option only but he might be a better scorer than I first thought.
Short: Former top 10 pick where some thought he was as talented as any, has taken a lot of time to develop and had some injury issues, hopefully gets a nice run at it this season but as a developing key back his scoring will be limited

Name: Conor Stone
Comment: Stone hasn't featured much since being drafted in the first round of the 2020 draft, largely hampered by a tough run of soft issue injuries. However, he was a man in-demand at the end of 2024 following an impressive VFL season which saw him win the Giants' B&F. He averaged 84 for the season (up from 57 in 2023) where he started as a forward, kicking 16 goals from his first seven games, before he flourished as an intercept defender in the second half of the season of which included him scoring 120 and 140 in consecutive weeks. It is this role that he is flagged to take in 2025 following the departure of defender Harry Perryman. With forward status, he becomes a very interesting option in 2025. His Round 0 score will likely make the decision for us, but I think he might be a sneaky pick in 2025.
Short: Former pick 15 has only played the 13 games since being drafted 2020, but was in demand at the end of year and chose to stay, a candidate for Perryman's wing role makes him an interesting prospect

Name: James Blanck
Short: Genuine lock-down key defender coming off an ACL

Name: Harry Rowston
Short: Pick 16 as an inside mid, played seven games with midfield exposure year one but didn’t feature last year, 92 VFL average (up from 75) a good sign but he'll likely remain on the fringe again

Name: Jakob Ryan
Short: Medium defender with massive numbers in his draft year, averaged 67 in the VFL so might be a while before he gets his chance

Name: Jack Buller
Short: Scored well at WAFL League level as a key forward chopping out in the ruck, but as a key forward his scoring will be limited if he ever gets a chance

Name: Harry Barnett
Short: Rookie ruck who has averaged 42 at WAFL level, with Flynn back he'll be in the WAFL to develop

Name: Ashton Moir
Short: A forward with nice goal sense, 49 VFL average suggests he may need some time

Name: Tew Jiath
Short: Broke into the side to debut in 2024, just the one game though and a 64 VFL average suggests he needs some time to develop

Name: Kaleb Smith
Short: Half-back who missed the entire 2023 season with a foot stress fracture but returned to play four games in 2024, VFL average of 77 is promising and we might see some more of him while Richmond are developing

Name: Will Lorenz
Short: Midfielder with okay numbers at underage and in the VFL last year, with Port's midfield I doubt we see him have that role at AFL for a while

Name: Wil Dawson
Short: Tall who can play forward or back, hurt his shoulder when on 0 which cut his season short, might play some more in 2025 but going to need some time to develop

Name: Cooper Simpson
Short: Freo's first pick of 2023 draft played just the two games in his first season as a small forward, didn't shoot the lights out in the WAFL but reportedly had a strong pre-season so we might see more of him in 2025, but not in a Fantasy friendly role

Name: Loch Rawlinson
Short: Small forward who showed a nice pressure and tackle game in the WAFL, debuted in 2024 but scoring in that game and his WAFL season was underwhelming

Name: Ethan Read
Comment: Read had Keeper league coaches excited as soon as he entered the league, given the 202cm ruckman's ability to get around the ground like a midfielder, racking up marks and disposals to go along with his hitouts. He went at 103 and 97 in the U18 Champs and Coates Talent League respectively, which included an average of over 20 disposals and six marks per game. He played four games in his first season, but limited to a tall forward role which was always going to be tough. He'll likely continue to develop in the VFL for the next year or so while Witts is still up to it, but those Keeper coaches shouldn't lose hope of what's to come in a few years’ time.
Short: Ruck taken in the top 10 (doesn't happen often), elite running power for a big man but at AFL level he's going to need some time before he starts displaying that

Name: Angus Hastie
Short: Rebounding defender played five games in 2024 (four as sub) and will likely remain on the fringe for 2025

Name: Caleb Mitchell
Short: Drafted as a winger who has great running capacity, scoring at VFL level improved from 57 to 82 which is a good sign, will likely find it tough for opportunities again though

Name: Max Gruzewski
Short: Drafted as a key defender but played forward in the VFL the last two seasons for a 60 average, will likely need some time to develop

Name: Hugh Davies
Short: Key defender who plays a very disciplined role, but he's not going to be a scorer at any level

Name: Kynan Brown
Short: The lightly built mid won Vic Metro's best and fairest at the National Carnival, played two games in his first season - both as sub - but a rundown tackle on debut was impressive, 79 VFL average is nice but will likely need some time to develop

Name: Lance Collard
Short: Small forward had an interrupted first season at the Saints but managed three games at senior level (all as sub), 40 VFL average suggests he'll need time

Name: Toby Murray
Short: Developing ruck taken in the mid-season draft

Name: Charlie Edwards
Short: Big-bodied midfielder whose scoring at the lower level suggest he might need some time

Name: Oscar Ryan
Short: Rebound defender with solid scoring at junior level, a bit of buzz coming out of Adelaide about him and I wouldn't be surprised if he debuts early in 2025 and makes a nice rookie option

Name: Karl Gallagher
Short: Irishman Category B rookie with a 32 VFL average

Name: Tyler Welsh
Comment: Welsh played for most of the season at SANFL League level, averaging 45 points from 8 disposals, 4 marks and a goal a game. He was dropped once to U18 level but swiftly responded, kicking 8 goals with 17 disposals and 10 marks for a 128. He kicked 8 goals in his 4 games at the U18 Champs but was otherwise quiet, averaging just 6 disposals. Won't be much of a scorer until he refines his game against better opposition.
Short: Well-built tall forward with senior experience

Name: Reece Torrent
Short: Mid with a high kick-to-handball ratio, will likely bide his time in the VFL for a while

Name: Will McLachlan
Short: Forward taken in the mid-season draft, will need time

Name: Zane Zakostelsky
Short: Rucked in his junior days to good effect, but at 196 he's limited to a key defender role in the seniors and scoring will be limited there

Name: Luke Lloyd
Short: Key forward at Brisbane who will need time to develop

Name: Ty Gallop
Comment: The QAFL rookie of the year, Gallop is a key forward who managed 2 games for the Allies at the U18 Champs after strong performances for the Lions Academy and Maroochydore. He also earned a VFL debut, incredibly coming in for the Lions' Preliminary Final, kicking 1 goal from 9 disposals. Daniher retiring might help but he'll need more development before he's in contention for that spot.
Short: Academy-selected key forward

Name: Harry Lemmey
Short: Developing key forward who is behind the best in the comp

Name: Billy Wilson
Short: Rebounding defender with solid Coates Talent League numbers and was okay in his first season of VFL, tough team to crack into though

Name: Hudson O'Keeffe
Short: Tap ruckman whose scores in his draft year and VFL suggest he needs time to develop

Name: Rob Monahan
Short: Irish Cat-B rookie, will need time

Name: Harry O'Farrell
Comment: A dour key defender, O'Farrell's scoring is generally quite limited with his season high of 58 coming when he pushed forward and kicked 2.4. Across the 2023 and 2024 seasons he averaged 46 from 9 games in the Coates League, averaging 33 at the U18 Champs across the same period. There should be plenty of better options and he's one we can look past even if picked.
Short: Key defender coming off an injured draft year

Name: Harry DeMattia
Short: Decent junior numbers but averaged just 58 in his first year in the VFL

Name: Iliro Smit
Short: 19-year-old ruck taken in the mid-season draft, will need time

Name: Joel Cochran
Comment: One of the best runners in the draft, Cochran won the 2km time trial at the National Draft Combine, having also competed at state level in various events as a junior. He played all 4 games for the Allies at the U18 Champs, averaging 14 disposals, 4.5 marks and 2 tackles for 59 points. He also featured for the Swans Academy in the Coates League averaging 4 more kicks and similar numbers across the board for a 72 average. Despite the Pies still looking for a key defender, Cochran is likely a fair way down the pecking order.
Short: Athletic tall defender

Name: Saad El-Hawli
Short: 23-year-old mid-season draftee, running half back who averaged 100 at VFL level and if named in Round 1 will be a very popular defender rookie, however running in the B team in the pre-season

Name: Luamon Lual
Short: Rebounding defender but scoring at all levels isn't great

Name: Lewis Hayes
Short: A near two metre defender with strong intercept marking, will take some time in the VFL before we see him at AFL level

Name: Vigo Visentini
Short: 204cm ruck will need a lot of time

Name: Angus Clarke
Comment: A consistent rebounding defender off half-back, Clarke produced solid numbers at SANFL U18s level and played all 4 games for SA at the U18 Champs. He opened the season with 25 disposals and 8 marks for a 104, then recording between 15 and 21 disposals in all of his completed matches, finishing with a season average of 78 points. He doesn't quite have the ceiling scores we would like, but a low of 60 shows he shouldn't let you down badly.
Short: Medium-tall intercept defender

Name: Odin Jones
Short: Developing ruck who will miss the entire 2025 season after suffering a fractured vertebrae

Name: Ollie Murphy
Short: Key defender who as All-Australian in his draft year as well as Vic Metro MVP, minimal scoring capacity though

Name: Jaren Carr
Comment: Overlooked in previous drafts and nearly taken in last years mid-season draft, Carr is a leaping forward with plenty of senior experience at WAFL League and Reserve level over the last few years. He averaged 16 disposals, 6 marks and a bit over a goal a game for a 76 average in the Reserves although he struggle a bit more at League level. Will need to add a bit more strength to his frame to compete at the top level.
Short: High-flying medium-tall forward

Name: Mitchell Edwards
Short: Young ruck drafted by Geelong, will need some time to develop

Name: George Stevens
Short: Great junior scorer as an inside mid and some flexibility to half-back, might find it tough for games as a kid for Geelong but he looks okay

Name: Cillian Burke
Comment: An athletic, clean ball-user, Burke provided good run-and-carry through the middle third in Gaelic football, running hard off half-back as well as delivering forward.
Short: Gaelic football convert

Name: Zak Evans
Comment: Evans signed midway through 2024, playing 5 games for the Suns' VFL side rotating through the midfield. Excluding his 4 point first game, he averaged 11 disposals and 4 tackles for 43 points. Hardwick has conceeded he'll need plenty of work to be AFL ready so wouldn't be expecting anything this season.
Short: Former cricketer for Victoria and Melbourne Renegades

Name: Phoenix Gothard
Short: Draft bolter, delayed start to his first season after having glandular, small forward role I expect his scoring to be limited if ever given the chance

Name: Wade Derksen
Short: Decent VFL numbers for a key forward but hard to see that translating at AFL level if ever given the chance

Name: Nicholas Madden
Short: 204cm,112kg ruck with some big VFL numbers (166 thanks to 31 touches, 31 HOs and eight tackles, and 131 in back-to-back weeks), Briggs has the spot locked for now but with Preuss delisted he's now the clear next in line

Name: Nathan Wardius
Short: 149 goals in 49 matches in country NSW, found the VFL a bit tougher and will need time to get to the level

Name: Logan Smith
Comment: A big ruckman able to impact around stoppages through both hitouts and disposals, Smith averaged 27 hitouts and 18 disposals across 3 games for the GIANTS Academy in the Coates League. Will be behind Briggs and Madden for a bit so plenty of time to develop.
Short: Academy ruck selection

Name: Jasper Scaife
Short: Tall forward taking in the mid-season draft, will need some time

Name: William McCabe
Short: Has the size of a key defender but plays like a rebounding defender so he had some nice scores in his draft year, injured for much of 2024 but his 44 average through seven VFL game suggests he needs time

Name: Matt Hill
Comment: Formerly a member of the Brisbane Broncos development squad, Hill moved to Victoria and joined the Melbourne Storm's academy. He played AFL as a junior and almost joined the Suns Academy before initially choosing Rugby League at 15.
Short: Former U21 Rugby League player and Academy member

Name: Oliver Sestan
Short: Medium forward drafted from the Goulburn Valley League (didn't play NAB League), but a goal kicker at that level, will need time before making the step up

Name: Jed Adams
Short: Known as one of the best lockdown defenders in the 2022 draft, but that's not going to be a role for scoring

Name: Luker Kentfield
Short: 194cm key forward taken in the mid-season draft, been sidelined by a nasty bout of pneumonia

Name: Matthew Jefferson
Short: Former pick 15 (part of the Luke Jackson trade) who is a key forward, won the club’s Best VFL Player with 29 goals in 2024 but his 54 average suggests he's not a scorer

Name: Aidan Johnson
Comment: Big-bodied and physically capable as a key forward, Johnson played at CHF for the flag-winning Werribee side, catching the eyes of recruiters with an 11-goal 5-game stint through the middle of the year. His numbers otherwise weren't too impressive, with an average of 60 from 11 disposals, but he did show some flexibility by chopping out in the ruck with 130 hitouts for the year.
Short: Mature key forward from the VFL

Name: Finnbar Maley
Short: A 197cm youngster with a basketball background, will need a lot of time to develop

Name: Geordie Payne
Short: Went pick one in the mid-season draft pick in 2024, averaged an impressive 77 in the VFL so he might have some talent

Name: Jacob Konstanty
Short: Part of the Luke Parker trade, a small pressure forward who was taken pick 20 in his draft is now at the Roos, might be closer to a game there but given his role, it’s unlikely he'll be much of a scorer

Name: Brayden George
Short: Once touted as a top 10 pick in 2022 but and ACL injury in the NAB League saw him slide and miss 2023, and then did it again last season to cut his season short, deserves some luck

Name: Luke Urquhart
Comment: After a permanently dislocated hip caused him to miss the entire 2023 season, Urquhart played 3 games at WAFL Colts level in 2024, also managing all 4 games for WA at the U18 Champs with an average of 76. His opening 2 games in the Colts were huge, averaging 24 disposals, 7 marks, 8.5 tackles and 2 goals for scores of 130 & 133. The Roos are looking to mould him into a defensive-minded mid and hopefully there's some opportunity for game time over the course of the year in a young midfield.
Short: Powerful inside mid with a strong defensive game

Name: Hugh Jackson
Short: An accumulator at junior level and carried that into the SANFL where he averaged 86, touch midfield to crack but one to keep an eye on

Name: Xavier Walsh
Short: Developing key forward, will need time

Name: Tom Anastasopoulos
Short: Small forward who kicked 21.2 (!) in 11 games in the Coates Talent League, tough role for Fantasy scoring though

Name: Jacob Moss
Comment: Began training with the Power midway through last year, playing 2 games on limited minutes and sustaining a concussion. Was formerly an academy member at the Adelaide 36ers and played for SA Red at the Australian U20 Basketball Championships. Has a strong leap at the ball and is height will mean he's likely to be deployed through the ruck or as a key forward.
Short: Former basketballer

Name: Campbell Gray
Short: Mid-season pick who can play defence, forward and ruck, will likely need some time

Name: Oliver Hayes-Brown
Short: 208cm basketballer, will need time

Name: Mate Colina
Short: Tallest AFL listed player in history at 213cm, still developing in the VFL and had back issues in 2024

Name: Jasper Alger
Comment: As expected with his role, Alger's output game-to-game can vary quite heavily going goalless in 4/10 games across the Coates League and U18 Champs. With an average of 58 and a highest score of just 73, there should be better options even if he gets selected.
Short: Medium forward able to play taller than his size

Name: Max Heath
Short: The tallest man on St Kilda’s list, any thought of him getting an early run with Campbell leaving and Marshall injury has been squashed with the arrival of Boyd who looks more progressed

Name: Max Hall
Short: Young midfielder/half-forward taken in the mid-season draft after plying his trade at the Box Hill Hawks in the VFL, scoring is good at VFL level and at age 22 he's one to watch if ever given the chance

Name: Liam O'Connell
Short: Irish Cat-B rookie, will need time

Name: Hugh Boxshall
Comment: Racking up big numbers in the WAFL Colts, Boxshall brushed off a quiet Round 1 to average 27 disposals, 4 marks, 5.5 tackles and 96 points for the remainder of the season. He lifted his disposal average from 20 to 29 after returning from the U18 Champs, but the increase was made up almost entirely of handballs, as his average kicks stayed around 9 per game.
Short: Very handball-happy big-bodied mid

Name: Indhi Kirk
Short: Cat-B rookie will need time, son of Brett

Name: Tom Hanily
Short: Mid-season draftee who averaged 25 disposals from his four games with Gippsland in 2024 and then went to average 86 in the VFL, one to keep an eye on

Name: Patrick Snell
Short: Key defender with low scoring history

Name: William Green
Short: Young ruck taken early in the draft so he must have some talent, however at 19 will need time to develop

Name: Riley Bice
Comment: An attacking threat off half-back, Bice played the full season for premiership-winning Werribee side in 2024, with several huge games in the back half of the season. He passed 100 on 6 occasions, and showed his capability to go big by passing 120 in 5 of those. He averaged 91 for the season, but it was the marked improvement from R9 onward, averaging 24 disposals and 8 marks for 104, that saw him rocket into consideration at AFL level. While he won't make it into Sydney's full strength side, his experience at senior level should mean he'll be a capable replacement if spots open up for any reason.
Short: Mature-aged defender plucked from the VFL

Name: Coen Livingstone
Short: Developing ruck with some nice VFL scores, will need time before he makes an impact at AFL level based on his WAFL numbers from last year

Name: Tom Gross
Comment: A consistent performer, Gross produced consecutive seasons in the Coates League averaging 22 disposals, 4 marks, 3 tackles, and a goal, with similar numbers for Vic Metro in the U18 Champs. He had a bit of a fall off in the second half of his season averaging 19 disposals in his final 4 games compared to 25 in his first 4, also halving his tackle numbers. We'll wait and see how he shapes up, but his height might mean he'll be pushed into more of a forward role at the top level.
Short: Powerful mid-forward

Name: Jedd Busslinger
Short: Not many key defenders go pick 13, so he might have something special, hasn't played yet but with the injuries to the talls I expect him to debut early in 2025 and while scoring may be limited as a young key back, he's an okay D8

Name: Lachlan Smith
Short: 202cm tall, will need time

Name: Sam Davidson
Comment: Having won the award for the VFL's best young player, Davidson's chances of playing look good, with all of the previous 17 winners making an AFL debut. His best performance was a 6 goal effort from 19 disposals and 8 marks for 97 points, while he also managed 2 tons throughout the season. A 68 average at VFL level is handy enough and his senior experience should mean he's a fine pick at basement price when/if he makes a debut.
Short: Mature age medium-tall forward from VFL

Name: Sam Lalor
Comment: Despite a range of injuries interrupting his draft year, Lalor showed plenty in the games he did play, featuring as an inside mid in the Coates League while pushing forward in the U18 Champs. His games for GWV stood out especially, averaging 27 disposals, 7 marks and 4 tackles for 109 AF. After Richmond's off-season exodus there should be plenty of midfield time available this year and you'd think the prized pick will have first go at it. Keep an ear out for where they think they'll play him, as a midfield role could be fruitful but up forward he's probably a pass at this price.
Short: An explosive mid-forward with match-winning capabilities

Name: Finn O'Sullivan
Comment: Despite playing just 6 matches in his draft year due to injury, you can see how highly clubs rated O'Sullivan, given he was kept in Pick 1 conversations right up until the draft. His numbers don't jump out, averaging 17 disposals, 4 marks, and 4 tackles from his 4 Coates League games, while he was also reasonably quiet in his 2nd year at the U18 Champs after earning All-Australian selection as a bottom-ager. Noted for his versatility, he can play both inside and outside while also able to hit the scoreboard, as shown by his 5 goals in the Coates League. Given how deep the draft pool was this year, O'Sullivan's price might mean we see better value scoring options, but definitely keep an eye on selection as he should be a safe pick.
Short: A well-balanced mid but not quite an accumulator

Name: Jagga Smith
Comment: Averaging a massive 34 disposals from 12 Coates League games, Smith added to his game by hitting the scoreboard later in the season with 7 goals in 7 games. His biggest performance came in Round 9 with 50 disposals, 6 marks, and a goal for 157 points, incredibly following this up with 2 more games of 40+ disposals. He kept his good form in the U18 Champs, averaging 29 disposals and 95 points, while also averaging 27 disposals from 3 games in the VFL. 20 FEB UPDATE: Shocking news as he's out for the year with an ACL.
Short: An ultra-consistent accumulator at all levels - out for the year with an ACL

Name: Sid Draper
Comment: A consistent performer who was rewarded with SA captaincy at the U18 Champs, Draper averaged 21 disposals from 4 games, backing up his 22 disposal average from 6 SANFL games. However, in the U18 Champs he averaged just 62, compared to his 86 average at SANFL League level. The main difference in scoring came from his tackle numbers, registering 10 and 11 in his only 2 tons (115 & 118) at SANFL level, while he managed just 5 tackles across 4 games for SA. Being the player with the most senior experience, he should be ready to slot straight in to the midfield at Adelaide, and could provide a point of difference to their usual setup.
Short: A fast, clean mid with solid senior experience

Name: Levi Ashcroft
Comment: Seemingly a gift that he slid down a few picks to save us some cash, Levi Ashcroft should see plenty of game time, especially after Fagan declared he could've played last year if eligible. Averaging a goal and a half, 31 disposals and 5 marks for 117 points in the Coates League, his most notable performance came in his VFL debut, where he racked up 35 touches, 8 marks, 5 tackles and a goal for 145 AF. The only question mark behind him will be his role, as he finds himself coming into a premiership winning side with an already stacked midfield.
Short: A prolific, consistent onballer who should see consistent games and opportunity

Name: Harvey Langford
Comment: A bit of a bolter over the year, Langford produced a consistent season to launch himself into consideration right up the top of the draft. In the Coates League he averaged 26 disposals, 5 marks, and 5 tackles for a 107 average while also kicking 20 goals in his 15 games. His best performance saw him kick 4.0 from 33 disposals, adding 5 tackles for a score of 120. Petracca coming back in and an expectation that Oliver will be in better shape likely means there isn't going to be as much midfield opportunity as there was toward the back end of last year, but he should slot in behind Viney and Rivers as the next option. Here's hoping his capability as a forward doesn't work against him and we get to see him through the middle.
Short: A big-bodied mid-forward with a strong contested game and lethal kick

Name: Josh Smillie
Comment: A taller mid at 195cm, Smillie produced consecutive strong seasons in the Coates League, averaging 26 disposals, 4 marks, and 4 tackles for 97 points, while he was also accurate in front of goal, kicking 16.5 from his 12 matches this year. His numbers across the lines dropped a bit in the U18 Champs, but he was able to show his strength in the contest, averaging 10 contested possessions and 5 clearances. As with many of Richmond's other draftees, expect Smillie to get a good go at it early and feature in the midfield rotation.
Short: Another big-bodied mid who should see opportunity in a depleted Tigers side

Name: Tobie Travaglia
Comment: Modelling his game on Will Day, Travaglia is a rebounding defender who clubs believe will be able to push into the midfield later in his career. Playing off half-back in the U18 Champs, he averaged 22 disposals and 6 marks for an 83 AF average. In the Coates League he saw a bit more time through the middle, averaging 24 disposals, 6 tackles, and 4 marks for a 101 average. His last 5 games were especially strong, averaging 9 tackles and hitting the scoreboard hard, kicking 8.2 in that period for a 116 average. Perhaps surprisingly for someone in his role, he is a bit handball happy, generally averaging 12-13 handballs per 10 kicks. He should slot straight in at the Saints in Round 1, though will face some competition for the ball unless Sinclair and NWM push into the middle.
Short: Hard-working running defender with midfield potential

Name: Leonardo Lombard
Comment: A bit of a slider due to being a Suns Academy product, Lombard dominated at the U18 Champs, earning MVP honours after averaging 26 disposals, 3 marks, 4.5 tackles, and a goal a game for a 98 average. He also has good senior experience, having played 11 VFL games for the Suns over the last 2 years, including being a member of their flag-winning side in 2023. His best VFL game came this year in Round 19, where he kicked 3.0 from 22 disposals, with 6 tackles helping him to a 99. His only downside may be his height, as we've seen plenty of junior mids be pushed into pressure forward roles once they hit the top level. He'll definitely see plenty of game time, it just comes down to what role that'll be in.
Short: A dominant junior midfielder though his size may work against him

Name: Alixzander Tauru
Comment: The first non-midfielder taken in the draft, Tauru is an intercept defender with the ability to be thrown forward when required. He averaged 15 disposals and 6 marks in the Coates League for a 64 average and kicked 7.8 in his final 5 games when he flexed forward at times. His pre-season has been delayed due to a stress fracture in his back so don't expect him to play early, if at all.
Short: Tall, athletic defender with a strong intercept game

Name: Xavier Lindsay
Comment: An exciting prospect from early on, Lindsay featured for 3 years in the Coates League, where his draft year saw him average near 24 disposals and 4 marks for a second consecutive year. Interestingly, playing through the midfield saw him increase his K:H ratio, also booting 7 goals across the year for an average of 89. His best Fantasy game came in Round 15 in the Coates League, where 31 disposals (22 kicks), 10 marks, and 3 tackles produced 128 points. However, he saved his best for the U18 Champs, averaging 23 disposals, 7 marks and 5 tackles for a 99 average in 3 games. He might not be able to squeeze into the Melbourne midfield, but given his previous experience off half-back, could we see him play a Daicos/Sheezel type role in his first year?
Short: A damaging kick through the midfield and previously off half-back

Name: Taj Hotton
Comment: After playing primarily as a forward in his underage year, Hotton moved to the midfield with instant impact. An ACL injury cut his year short, but from his 3 games he averaged 29 disposals and 7 marks for a 116 average. His best game showed he could still hit the scoreboard from the midfield as he racked up across all stat lines, kicking 4.1 from 32 disposals to go with 10 marks and 5 tackles for 158 points. If he impresses enough once he reaches full training, he could be a nice downgrade target in the second half of the season.
Short: High impact mid-forward but still recovering from an ACL

Name: Isaac Kako
Comment: Perhaps a bit of a slider due to the Dons' draft hand knowing he could be matched, Kako is a small forward who could also drift through the midfield at junior level. In the Coates League he averaged 19 disposals across 12 games, though this consisted of 3 games of 12 or less and 4  games of 24+. He managed to consistently hit the scoreboard but his inaccuracy in front of goal hurt what could've been, with 20.24 for the season. His best game came against the SUNS Academy, where he kicked 3.2 from 29 disposals, with 6 marks, 4 tackles and 12(!) I50s for 133. He's expected to slot straight in at senior level, though with how we expect our forward lines to structure up this season, the likelihood is you'll be paying up for him to sit on your bench.
Short: An electric small forward though somewhat inconsistent

Name: Jonty Faull
Comment: Faull is a well-developed key forward, able to use his size to assert dominance in the contest and through the air. Coming off a back injury early in his draft year, he booted 16.6 in his first 5 games back in the Coates League, while also stepping up in their finals push with 4.2 and 5.2 in the Qualifying and Prelim respectively. Early word is he is a chance at playing early, but will be a slow burn at best and probably one you can avoid with the other available forward options.
Short: Strong-marking key forward able to kick a bag

Name: Joe Berry
Comment: Berry started the season on fire, kicking 4 goals in 4 of his first 5 games in the Coates League, though finished quietly as he managed multiple goals just once in his final 7 games. He stood up at the U18 Champs, kicking an equal-high 9 goals across 4 games and averaging 13 disposals, 3.5 marks, and 3 tackles for 70 points. He's another who will be a decent chance at playing early, but likely a squeeze to fit him in the forward line in our teams.
Short: Crafty small forward who earned AA honours at the U18 Champs

Name: Bo Allan
Comment: Having started the year as a defender, Allan played through the middle captaining WA at the U18 Champs, averaging 20 disposals, 3 marks, and 6 tackles for an 88 average. He played 11 games at League level in the WAFL with a mix of midfield and defensive roles, averaging 11 disposals, 3 marks, and 3 tackles. Don't expect too much from his scoring if he's playing as a defender, but he might be an option we have to take if we're spending up elsewhere.
Short: Versatile mid-defender with good senior experience

Name: Murphy Reid
Comment: Having always been penetrative and composed with ball in hand, Reid was able to up his output this season with a move into the midfield earning him MVP honours for the Championship-winning Vic Metro side. At the carnival he averaged 25 disposals, 3 marks, 3 tackles, and a goal a game for a 93 average, also producing very similar numbers in the Coates League. He managed 4 tons for the year, including consecutive scores over 110 to start the finals off, with 3 goals and 25+ disposals in each. Pretty low chance he is able to get a game in the Freo midfield, but worth keeping an eye on in the pre-season and whether he could sneak a role up forward for now.
Short: Smooth mover in the midfield but might be a squeeze to play early

Name: Oliver Hannaford
Comment: Initially a rebounding defender, Hannaford shifted through the midfield and up forward across his draft year, producing strong performances wherever he was deployed. His best performances came in the big games in the Coates League, kicking 6.0 in the Qualifying final and backing up with a team-high 24 disposals and 9 tackles in the Grand Final. The Giants did see quite a few departures in the off-season with Stringer the only in, however most were fringe players and it's hard to see him getting the nod ahead of their other small forwards to start the season.
Short: Small-medium utility but roared up the draft order as a small forward

Name: Harrison Oliver
Comment: Oliver possesses a piercing left foot kick off the back 50, which he put on full display at the U18 Champs as he averaged 16 disposals at 83% efficiency. His Coates League numbers were consistent but produced no ceiling games, recording 12-19 disposals and 61-85 points in all 10 games. Haynes, Cumming and Perryman all rotated through the backline in previous years which should mean some minutes at half-back are available, and although you never know with the Giants, he probably doesn't make the side if they're at or near full strength.
Short: Intercepting defender with elite ball use, but could use higher disposal numbers

Name: Cooper Hynes
Comment: Capable of big games in either line, Hynes kicked 23 goals in 15 games in the Coates League and averaged 24 disposals, 4 marks, and 3 tackles for 92 points. He kicked 3+ goals 4 times and managed 30+ disposals twice, though his quietest games came in the back end of the season, 3 times recording 17 or less disposals after never dipping below 20 previously. His middle period of the season was among the best of any draftees as he recorded 5 tons in 6 games (avg 116), averaging 28 disposals, 5.5 marks and 2.2 goals. Looks as though he's unlikely to play early, but definitely one worth keeping an eye on as he should score well if given the chance.
Short: A big-bodied mid-forward able to produce monster games

Name: Luke Trainor
Comment: Unlike many of the other key position players in the draft, Trainor puts up strong numbers at whatever level he plays. His numbers were near identical across the U18 Champs and the Coates League, averaging 20 disposals, 6 marks, and 2 tackles for 80 points. Playing for the AFL Academy, he performed strongly against VFL opposition, averaging 20.5 disposals including a BOG performance against Coburg. Currently looks like he's in the mix for the last few bench spots at the Tiges, so might be one to avoid unless we can get more concrete word that he'll definitively play.
Short: Key defender but can still accumulate through marking chains and intercepts

Name: Jesse Dattoli
Comment: A crafty small forward, Dattoli has long been in the eyes of recruiters, featuring in the Coates League for the last 3 seasons after strong performances at club and school level. He averaged 23 disposals, 4 marks, and 2 goals for a 93 average, with his best coming as a midfielder as he racked up across the board, recording 35 disposals, 6 marks, 6 tackles, and a goal for 135. Unfortunately he suffered a stress reaction in his lower back and will miss a minimum of 4 months to start the season.
Short: Dangerous small forward but injured to start the season

Name: Harry Armstrong
Comment: One of the premier key forwards in the Coates League, Armstrong earned Team of the Year honours after kicking 27.10 from 10 games, including 5 hauls of 4. He also kicked a competition high 9 goals in the U18 Champs despite missing the first game, including 5 in the final as Vic Metro won after the siren. Despite the opportunity he is likely to be given, young KPPs generally don't score too well and our forward line structures will probably mean we pass on him to start the season.
Short: High-flying sharpshooter with the size to cause immediate impact

Name: Cody Angove
Comment: A huge draft bolter, Angove is an athletic high half-forward who best impacts game with his speed on the outside. He kicked 3 goals in his 4 games for WA at the U18 Champs, averaging 12 disposals, 3.5 marks, and 2.5 tackles for 55 points. In the WAFL Colts he averaged 18 disposals, 3.4 marks, and 3 tackles as well as booting 11.8 from 10 games. His highest scoring game came playing more through the midfield, where 27 disposals, 6 marks, and 4 tackles got him to 93. The GIANTS player bio notes that they expect he will take some time to be physically ready so don't expect him to play early, if at all, this season.
Short: A small mid-forward with a strong outside game

Name: Sam Marshall
Comment: One of the premier accumulators in his draft class, Marshall's 27 disposal average for the Allies at the U18 Champs was the second highest only behind Jagga Smith. He also averaged 5.5 marks and 4 tackles per game for a 99 point average. In the Coates League he was highly consistent, never dipping below 21 disposals after Round 1. His best game came in the winning Grand Final, as 28 disposals, 5 marks, and 2.1 saw him get 109 points and earn BOG honours. As good as he should be, it's hard to see the Lions making enough changes for him to squeeze in. Should score well if given the opportunity but realistically might only be one to keep an eye on if an injury opens up a spot later in the year.
Short: A well-balanced accumulating midfielder taken as an Academy selection

Name: Ned Bowman
Comment: Shot into the spotlight after taking a huge grab in the SANFL U18s, Bowman played all 4 games for SA at the U18 Champs, kicking 5 goals, of which 3 came in a strong second-half performance against WA. He led his side for goalkicking in the SANFL U18s, kicking 18.8 from 10 games and averaging 12.3 disposals at 80% efficiency for 63 points. His highest score of 96 came from 16 disposals (15 kicks), 5 marks, 4 tackles, and 3 goals. There weren't too many changes in the off-season for Sydney, and given they had such a strong year, we probably won't see too many major changes. Might be one to challenge for Parker's open spot but they've got plenty of options (Adams, Cleary, Wicks etc.) who might be ahead depending on the type of player they are looking to slot in.
Short: High-marking medium forward

Name: Matt Whitlock
Comment: A highly athletic tall, Matt Whitlock kicked 27 goals in 14 games in the Coates League, yet recruiters saw more interest in his intercept work down the other end. As a defender he averaged 18.5 disposals, 8 marks, and 76 points, while as a forward he kicked 3 goals a game with 12 disposals and 4 marks for a 65 average. He earned AA honours at fullback in the U18 Champs after averaging 14 disposals and 5 marks, also kicking 2 goals in his stint up forward. Might need a bit more time to develop before he's ready to play a the top level.
Short: A tall swingman able to play as a KPP at either end of the ground

Name: Thomas Sims
Comment: Though a bit inconsistent, Sims is capable of huge games up forward, while he also took extra rucking responsibilities toward the end of the season in the Coates League. For the season he kicked 23.14 from 15 games, but it was his performance in Round 6 - 15 disposals (all kicks!), 10 marks, and 7.4 for a 122 that caught the eye. He did make a senior debut at his local club but might need a bit more development before an AFL debut, and his scoring potential means there are better options unless all of Richmond's rucks fall over (again) and they need to turn to him.
Short: Athletic key forward also capable in the ruck

Name: Lachie Jaques
Comment: An elite ball user off half-back, Jaques averaged 16 disposals at 78.5% DE and 5 marks for a 65 average in the U18 Champs. To go with great efficiency, he also had a great K:H ratio for Fantasy coaches - 3:1 and 4:1 in Coates League and U18 Champs respectively. He reached 25 or more disposals in half his games, with his biggest game coming in Round 6, where 24 disposals (21 kicks), 11 marks, and 3 tackles came to 116 points. Will be a handy scorer if he gets afew games but not like the Dogs are short on distributors off half-back.
Short: Medium-size rebound defender with strong intercepting ability

Name: Jobe Shanahan
Comment: Initially projected to be taken in the first round, Shanahan is a key forward capable of kicking a bag on his day and able to stand up against stronger opposition. He kicked 23.12 from 11 games in the Coates League, though 15 of those came from 3 games, and just 1 other game featured multiple goals. He impressed enough to earn a VFL debut with Essendon, kicking 4.0, 2.3, and 5.0 across 3 games to finish the season. Unlikely to play and there should be better scoring options up forward for us anyway.
Short: Inconsistent key forward but performed strongly at higher levels

Name: Josh Dolan
Comment: Although the middle of his year was disrupted by a knee injury, Dolan performed strongly in the Coates League games he was able to play, averaging 20 disposals and 5 marks for an 80 point average, as well as kicking 8 goals across his 5 games. Taking on more of a pure forward role in the U18 Champs, he averaged 13 disposals and 4 marks for a 61 average. His size will likely mean he'll feature as a pressure forward rather than a midfielder so this is closer to what we should expect from his scoring.
Short: High half-forward and can pinch hit through the middle

Name: James Barrat
Comment: Starting the season as a forward, Barrat kicked 18 goals in 6 games in the Coates League, though it could have been a whole lot more as he matched that with 18 behinds. After AFL clubs pushed for him to play defence at the U18 Champs, he played the second half of the Coates League as a back, averaging 20 disposals (incl. 16 kicks), 9 marks, and 94 points. His biggest game came as he mixed the two roles in a losing final, kicking 2.1 to go with 25 disposals, 7 marks, and 5 tackles for 117. He has some experience against bigger bodies, playing seniors in his local league from as young as 14, while also featuring for Essendon VFL in 2024. Keep a closer eye on a defensive role, but likely he'll need more development before featuring at either end.
Short: A key position swingman who can play up in size

Name: Jack Whitlock
Comment: Similar to twin Matt, Jack Whitlock is key forward with great athleticism - he placed 2nd for standing vertical jump and =4th for running vertical at the Draft Combine. He matches his leap with strong hands to be a great aerial threat in the contest. At Coates League level he averaged 16 disposals, 5 marks, and 2 goals per game for an average of 80, with similar numbers at the U18 Champs, though 1 less goal per game. Scoring will likely be limited as a key forward, and he's likely going to sit a bit behind in the pecking order until he develops a bit more.
Short: Athletic tall forward who can pinch hit in the ruck

Name: Charlie Nicholls
Comment: A huge aerial threat, Nicholls averaged 15 disposals, 7.5 marks, and 2 goals at SANFL U18 level for an 83 point average. His best game came among a stretch of 3 consecutive tons, kicking 3.2 from 22 disposals and 13 marks (6 contested) for a 118. Following this he featured for SA at the U18 Champs, earning a debut in the SANFL Reserves level for 3 games on his return. Won't push either of Amiss or Treacy out of the side and the double ruck setup means Freo likely aren't looking to fit another tall in.
Short: Strong contested marking key forward

Name: Noah Mraz
Comment: Caught the eyes of recruiters in his under-age year as a tall utility, but he played just 3 games in 2024 (2 Coates League, 1 AFL Academy) before an ankle injury ruled him out for the rest of the season. Not too much to go off of scoring-wise given the low sample size, but a sub-50 average from 12 games in 2023 isn't great. Given he's coming off little-to-no footy and the Hawks acquiring two key backs in Barrass and Battle, expect Mraz to be developing in the VFL for a while to come.
Short: Key defender coming off an injury ruined 2024

Name: Jack Ough
Comment: Generally consistent but with numbers that don't jump off the page, Ough is a winger/onballer who can score well when he gets access to outside ball. His season was a tale of two halves, with his Coates League output improving massively on return from the U18 Champs despite a quiet performance there (avg 53 from 4 games). He went from a 20 disposal average to 25, doubled his tackle numbers and averaged 103, up from 79 in the first half. Will be a handy scorer if he gets an opportunity, just hard to see when that chance will come.
Short: Tall, outside mid and an efficient ball user

Name: Kayle Gerreyn
Comment: The first ruck taken in the draft, Gerreyn was absolutely dominant in the WAFL Colts, earning himself a debut at League level later in the year. He averaged 22 disposals, 22 hitouts, and 6 marks for a 107 average, also kicking 18.16 from his 11 games. His biggest game was a monster 148 from 30 disposals, 8 marks, 30 hitouts and 2.3, coming amid a stretch where he averaged 126 in the final 6 games of the season. Very few rucks play in their first year, but he's definitely one to keep an eye on for the future.
Short: A dominant ruck with multiple facets to his game

Name: Eamonn Armstrong
Comment: An U-20 star in Gaelic Football, Armstrong is a highly talented athlete, having also represented Ireland in soccer at a younger age. He provides great run off half-back and should add some exciting flair once he develops his game.
Short: Code switch from Gaelic Football

Name: Harry Boyd
Short: NULL

Name: Rhett Bazzo
Short: Young lockdown key defender dealt with a groin last year and now has a broken foot

Name: Luke Beecken
Short: Running defender taken in the mid-season draft, mature age and nice VFL numbers but it is a hard back six to crack into

Name: Darcy Craven
Short: Another mid-season selection by the Lions when they were in their injury crisis, 66 VFL average suggests he might be a way off

Name: Ben Camporeale
Comment: Sliding down the draft as a result of committing as a father-son pick, Ben Camporeale averaged big numbers through the midfield at all levels. In the SANFL U18s he averaged 32 disposals, 5 marks, and 4 tackles for a 109 average, also earning MVP honours for SA at the U18 Champs, averaging 27 disposals, 5 marks, and 4 tackles for 97 points. It's a big midfield to break into at Carlton, but his price means he's almost a must pick if he gets an opportunity at some stage.
Short: Midfield accumulator and excellent outside runner

Name: Lucas Camporeale
Comment: Not quite the ball magnet like his twin, Lucas Camporeale averaged 25 disposals at 90%(!) efficiency across 8 games at SANFL U18 level. He recorded 30+ disposals 3 times across the season, managing 120+ in 2 of those games. At the U18 Champs, he averaged 21 disposals @ 71%, 5 marks and 3 tackles for an 83 average, however it was largely built off his uncontested game, recording just 13 contested possessions total. His outside game may mean he's slightly closer than Ben to a debut, but hard to see that coming early without a spate of injuries/suspensions.
Short: Hard-running and an accurate ball-user on the outside

Name: Harry Charleson
Comment: Captaining the GWV Rebels in the Coates League, Charleson averaged 21 disposals and 70 points across 16 games. While he uses the ball well (79% @ U18 Champs), he scoring is somewhat limited as he doesn't fill the statlines - only twice each did he reach 5 tackles or 5 marks in a game this season.
Short: Rebounding defender with efficient ball use

Name: Matt Duffy
Comment: Duffy was picked up prior to last season, however in the month before he was set to come over, he tore his ACL playing Gaelic Football and opted to stay in Ireland for most of his rehab. He returned midway through 2024 and has since been working with strength and conditioning coaches. He's a noted gut-runner and will likely be deployed off half-back or in a wing role.
Short: Gaelic footballer returning from ACL

Name: Oscar Steene
Short: 20-year-old ruck with limited scoring history, a toe injury held him out for a lot of 2024

Name: Charlie West
Comment: A solid scorer at SANFL U18 level, West primarily played as a key forward, kicking 17 goals from 9 completed games and averaging 17 disposals, 6 marks and 88 points. He broke through for a debut at League level, playing 2 quiet games (avg. 18) before returning to U18 level with 3 consecutive tons including a 132 which involved 21 disposals, 5 goals, 10 marks and 13 hitouts.
Short: Key forward who can chop out in the ruck

Name: Will Hayes
Comment: A speedy runner on the outside, Hayes averaged 14.4 disposals, 3.6 marks and 60 points at WAFL Colts level, with similar numbers at the U18 Champs for WA. He was wasteful with opportunities in front of goal, kicking 2.6 for the season but was disciplined otherwise, recording just 2 FA over his 10 games. He's still a bit undersized and will need to build himself up a bit before he comes into the frame for a debut.
Short: Hard-running wingman

Name: Rhys Unwin
Comment: Despite playing through the middle in his draft year, Unwin's size will likely mean he'll be squeezed into a pressure forward role at the top level where he played most of his junior footy. Though he averaged 67 in 2024, we should expect scoring closer to his mid-50s average when he played up forward.
Short: Midfielder previously a small forward

Name: Zak Johnson
Comment: With nearly 80% of his possessions uncontested, Johnson provides great run and carry off half-back as well as breaking away from contests. He averaged 26 disposals and 5 marks in the Coates League, also kicking 9 goals in 12 games for a 97 average. He showed great consistency through the middle of the season by racking up 27+ disposals in 7 consecutive games, as well as averaging 6.5 marks in the same period. Had a shoulder injury to finish the season and will need some work on his contested and defensive game over the pre-season.
Short: Outside player off half-back and through the middle

Name: Archer Day-Wicks
Comment: Having played 3 seasons in the Coates League, Day-Wicks' numbers stalled going into his draft year, averaging 17 disposals, 4 marks and a goal in both seasons for mid-70s. It was similar in the U18 Champs, backing up his 54 point game in 2023 with a 55 average from 3 games in 2024. As a game-breaking type player he is very inconsistent game-on-game, recording 5 scores of 97+ but also 6 games of <60.
Short: X-factor mid-forward

Name: Jayden Nguyen
Comment: Posessing elite athleticism, Nguyen recorded top-5 finishes in 4 tests at the National Draft Combine, including both standing and running vertical jumps, allowing him to play above his size if required. He played a range of positions across the season, averaging 19 disposals, 3 marks and 3 tackles for 72 points in the Coates League. He also featured in the Bombers' VFL side, finishing with 16 touches and a goal.
Short: Small utility

Name: Jack Delean
Short: Small forward with minimal scoring outside of kicking goals

Name: Aiden Riddle
Comment: In his third season in the WAFL Colts, Riddle locked down a spot as an over-ager, playing 14 games and earning a spot in WAs U18 Champs side. He finished his season strongly in the Colts, averaging 17 disposals, 29 hitouts and 4 marks for 101 over the final 6 games. Will be a project player with plenty of ruck options already at Freo.
Short: Tap-dominant ruckman

Name: Oliver Wiltshire
Short: Mature age forward plucked from country football after a dominant few years, only averaged 40 in the VFL though

Name: Jay Polkinghorne
Comment: Had a delayed start to his season with a knee injury, but Polkinghorne came back strongly in the SANFL U18s and finished the season in a flag-winning Reserves side. With 15 goals in 6 games, he averaged 70 at U18 level with a high of 92 coming from 16 disposals, 5 marks, 5 tackles, and 4 goals. Although his other games at the level were limited (45 points, 5.5 disp, 1.5 goals), he saved his best Reserves performance for the GF, accumulating 17 disposals, 8 marks, and 2 goals for 84. Hard to see him getting any sort of consistent games and likely a limited scorer anyway.
Short: Strong-marking key forward

Name: Jacob Molier
Comment: A genuine ruck for the first half of the season, Molier averaged 23 hitouts and 71 points before spending more time forward after Round 12. Interestingly, it was his Round 12 game that was his best of the season, recording 17 disposals, 9 marks, 5 tackles and 25 hitouts for a 114. Can't see a first year ruck playing at Geelong though so not relevant to us this year.
Short: Ruck who tested forward late in the season

Name: Lennox Hofmann
Comment: Able to play as a 3rd tall, Hofmann has a strong sense reading the play and knowing when to leap for intercept marks. He averaged 49 points from 12 disposals and 4 marks across 10 games in the Coates League, with similar numbers in the U18 Champs. Can probably avoid based on scoring history so far.
Short: Quick, intercepting defender

Name: Keighton Matofai-Forbes
Comment: Matofai-Forbes averaged 12 disposals, 4 marks and 63 points with 11 goals across 7 games in the Coates League. He managed 1 game for Vic Metro at the U18 Champs, though was relatively quiet with no goals and 9 disposals for 51 points. His journey also might be over before it starts as he's being investigated for assault in the pre-season.
Short: Powerful forward

Name: Joe Pike
Comment: With 3 seasons in the Coates League under his belt, Pike dominated the ruck as an over-ager, averaging 16 disposals, 28 hitouts and 95 points in 2024. While he didn't produce any massive ceiling games, he showed great consistency, with just 1 game under 85. He also played a few games for Geelong's VFL side, kicking 3 goals in his 6 games, as well as averaging 20 hitouts and 10 disposals for 63 points.
Short: Physically dominant ruck

Name: Patrick Retschko
Comment: Although he didn't earn an invite to the National Draft Combine, Retschko's 6:07 2km time trial at the state combine would've had him second overall. He averaged 17 disposals and 3-4 marks in both the Coates League and at the U18 Champs, averaging 59 across 12 games at both levels.
Short: Hard-running wingman

Name: Xavier Ivisic
Comment: A hard-running midfielder, Ivisic put up solid numbers at all levels this season. He averaged 25 disposals, 5 marks and 4 tackles for 98 in the Coates League, including 4 straight tons in the middle. He also performed well at the U18 Champs for Vic Country, averaging 22 disposals and 4.5 marks for 83 points. Showed some promise playing forward at times and his height might mean that he'll be pushed into a forward role.
Short: Evasive midfield accumulator

Name: Asher Eastham
Comment: Eastham is a high-flying tall forward who provided a consistent threat forward in the Coates League, showing his versatility late in the season switching down back. Across the first 9 games he averaged 2 goals per game, though his biggest score came down back when he racked up 20 touches (16 kicks) and 11 marks for a 102. Could use some work on his tackling, just once recording more than 3 tackles in a game.
Short: Tall swingman

Name: Lachlan Gulbin
Comment: A long time member of the Suns Academy, Gulbin featured in 10 VFL games for Gold Coast, kicking 11.5 and averaging 8 disposals, 3 marks, 3 tackles and 49 points. While he didn't produce any ceiling games, he was consistent in his performances for the Suns Academy in the Coates League, scoring between 59 and 67 in all 4 games.
Short: Medium forward with senior experience

Name: Max Knobel
Short: 20-year-old ruck plucked from Freo by the Suns, with Witts still the man and Moyle developing, it might be a few years before we see him at senior level

Name: Cooper Bell
Comment: Despite being a GIANTS Academy member, the Suns moved up the draft to bid on Bell, showing how highly they rate the key tall. While he is highly versatile, having played key position at both ends as well as chopping out in the ruck, he's not that relevant for us, as shown by his 34 average playing all 4 games at the U18 Champs. He didn't fare too much better scoring-wise for the GIANTS Academy, averaging 52 points and 9 disposals across 3 games. One we can pass on even if he plays.
Short: Tall defender but capable around the ground

Name: James Leake
Short: Played across all three lines in his draft year, delayed start to 2024 but got going to average 95 in the VFL, impressive for a 19-year-old, training with the mids this pre-season with talk he might get a run there early

Name: Josaia Delana
Comment: The GIANTS Academy captain, Delana provides great defensive pressure around the contest, as well as up forward when deployed there. He averaged 13 disposals and 7 tackles at the U18 Champs, including a monster game against WA where he accumulated 19 disposals and laid 14 tackles. He also featured 9 times for the GIANTS at VFL level averaging 11 disposals, 3 tackles and 44 points. More likely to be deployed up forward given his height.
Short: Electric small mid-forward

Name: Bodie Ryan
Short: Medium defender with versatility, Hawks aren't short of those though

Name: Jaime Uhr-Henry
Comment: Played 1 season at U17 level and some as a junior, but has otherwise been a career basketballer. At 209cm, he has been targeted for his athleticism as a potential ruck project.
Short: Project ruck converting from basketball

Name: Cody Anderson
Comment: While he managed a few games with good disposal numbers, Anderson's best weapon is his defensive game, averaging 7 tackles per game from R1-R11. Across that same period he averaged 23 disposals and 100 points before a quiet final 2 games after a decent layoff. His tackling nature should mean he'll score well enough if given the chance to play.
Short: Strong inside bull

Name: Will Verrall
Short: 21-year-old ruck with okay scoring at VFL level, Tom Campbell's arrival probably means we won't see him this year even if anything ever happens to Max

Name: Ricky Mentha
Comment: An electric small forward, Mentha played for various representative sides, including NT, Allies and the National Academy. He also showed his flexibility by switching to defence late in the season. Overall though, his numbers aren't too impressive in a scoring sense, averaging 12 disposals, 2 marks and 2 tackles across 14 games.
Short: Versatile small forward

Name: Taylor Goad
Short: A young ruck who developed strongly over his draft year but will need more for the top level as his 20 average in the VFL suggests

Name: River Stevens
Comment: A creative small forward, Stevens doesn't quite have the tackle numbers of other small forwards but works hard up the ground to deliver the ball inside, as well as get on the end of it at ground level. He averaged 15.4 disposals, 4.6 marks and a goal per game for a 71 average in 7 Coates League games, though never put up a ceiling performance, with a high of 85. Noted by the Roos recruiters that he'll need plenty of development so won't be relevant for a while.
Short: Small forward with clean ball use

Name: Lachlan Charleson
Short: Small forward who kicked 17 goals in his last five games in the Coates Talent League, including a monster 8.4 to go with 22 disposals in Round 16 for 126, averaged 42 at VFL level and touch to score in that role at senior level

Name: Christian Moraes
Comment: A promising under-age midfielder, Moraes' game transitioned to hitting the scoreboard more in his draft year, but limiting accumulation. From 16 games in the Coates League, he averaged 24 disposals, 5 marks, 4 tackles and a goal and a half per game for 95 points. He had a good showing for Vic Metro at the U18 Champs, averaging 21 disposals and 6 marks for an 88 average. Having shown his skills forward of the ball and being on the smaller side compared to current midfielders, we might see Moraes feature more as a forward option, limiting his scoring.
Short: A well-balanced midfielder who can hit the scoreboard

Name: Benny Barrett
Comment: Naturally inconsistent due to the role of a small forward, Barrett was able to put up some strong scores in the SANFL U18s, with his tackling pressure providing a decent scoring base. His biggest score was a 127 from 25 disposals, 6 marks, 7 tackles and 2 goals, while he also managed a 114 off the back of 12 tackles and 19 disposals. His lowest scores were still not too poor however, 6 times scoring between 55 and 70.
Short: Agile small forward

Name: Tom Cochrane
Comment: Starting the year strongly, Cochrane averaged 23 disposals and 100 points over his first 6 games at SANFL U18 level, however he dropped away considerably, averaging 18 disposals and just 71 points for the remainder of the season. He failed to ton again after the hot streak, struggling up forward as well as he failed to kick multiple goals in a game in the second half of the season.
Short: Mid-forward who tailed off over the year

Name: Liam Fawcett
Short: Key forward with decent scoring in draft year, missed most of 2024 with a back stress fracture and returned to average just 25 in the VFL

Name: Isaac Keeler
Short: Key forward who can go in the ruck, will need a lot of time to develop

Name: Alex Dodson
Comment: Despite juggling basketball commitments, Dodson put up strong numbers at SANFL U18s level and earned AA honours at the U18 Champs after rucking for SA. He managed 3 tons in the SANFL U18s, including a 145 from 32 disposals, 34 hitouts, 5 marks and 5 tackles, finishing the season with a 95 average. A prototype of the modern ruck, he's one to keep an eye on in the future.
Short: Basketball background ruckman

Name: Patrick Said
Comment: After a quiet first 2 rounds, Said managed to goal in every game after with great accuracy (23.6), including 5 consecutive 2 goal games to finish the season. He also managed 6 consecutive games of 20+ disposals through the middle of the season including a 130 from 2 goals, 26 disposals and 12 marks.
Short: Mid-forward with consistent scoreboard impact

Name: William Edwards
Short: Strong key back (100kgs and 197cm), but averaged under 50 in the VFL over the last three seasons

Name: Riak Andrew
Comment: Overlooked in his original draft year, Andrew earned another chance in the Coates League and rose strongly across the year to bolt into draft contention. Scoring-wise he's not too attractive however, averaging 53 across 12 games in the Coates League, 42 from 10 games the year before, and 26 from his only game at the U18 Champs. With his upside he could be a great player but doubt he'll be too relevant for our teams.
Short: Athletic over-age key defender

Name: Blake Leidler
Comment: Generally tasked with lockdown roles on small forwards, Leidler's scoring is wildly varied but still generally limited overall. Aside from a 24 disposal effort for his high score of 80, he failed to pass 18 touches in any other game for the season, including 5 games with <10. Probably one to avoid even if picked.
Short: Accountable small-medium defender

Name: Archer Reid
Short: The less talked about Reid that West Coast drafted in 2023, developing key forward who can chop out in the ruck is getting some big wraps, I think we'll see him play a lot in 2025 but given age and role, keep scoring expectations in check

Name: Lucca Grego
Comment: While he had a quiet U18 Champs showing in a stacked Vic Metro side, Grego performed strongly as the captain of the Western Jets in the Coates League. Playing a mix off half-back and through the middle, he averaged 23 disposals, 5 marks and 4 tackles for 92 points. His biggest game could've been even bigger if not for inaccuracy in front of goal, racking up 34 disposals, 7 marks, 4 tackles, 12 I50s and kicking 1.4 for a 136. The Eagles have him currently training in a half-back role which should be conducive to scoring if he gets a chance so keep an eye on him.
Short: Medium mid-defender who is tough around the contest

Name: Hamish Davis
Comment: Davis started the year in a predominantly forward role, booting 9.4 across his first 4 games in the WAFL Colts. He later transitioned to a midfield role which proved fruitful, averaging 30 disposals and 7 marks for 112 points over his final 4 games. These performances allowed him to break through to League level for 7 games where he averaged 14 disposals and 56 points. Has the build and flexibility to play as either a big-bodied mid or up forward if required which could help to earn a debut at some point in future years.
Short: Medium-tall forward also featuring through the middle

Name: Malakai Champion
Comment: Dangerous inside forward-50 defensively and offensively, Champion performed strongly in the WAFL Colts and earned a debut at League level in 2024. He started hot at League level, kicking 7 goals in his first 3 games, though couldn't hit the scoreboard in his next 2 before returning to the Colts for finals.
Short: Small forward with senior experience

Name: Jordan Croft
Short: Taken in the first round as a Father-Son pick, Croft is a 200cm key forward who will need time to develop

Name: Luke Kennedy
Comment: With some senior experience at club level, Kennedy played through the middle for the flag-winning Sandringham side in the Coates League. However, apart from a strong performance in the Prelim, he was generally pushed to the wing with other draftees such as Levi Ashcroft and Sam Marshall preferred when they were available. This heavily limited his scoring and consistency - he had 4 games with 28+ disposals (avg. 110) but failed to reach 20 in his other 14 games (avg. 61). With a spot in the middle very unlikely, we'll need to see him improve his outside game to become a possible selection.
Short: Natural onballer often on the wing
